<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Hospital     05-19 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Hospital,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weary Doctors Try to Save Shelling Casualties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The young doctor moved through rows of
casualties from the artillery battle between Christians and
Moslems. ``I'm so worn out I sometimes lock myself in my room and
cry, just cry,'' he said.
   His name is Pierre, he is 26 and he asked that his surname not
be used because he is a Christian working at the American
University Hospital in Moslem west Beirut.
   It was before the cease-fire negotiated by the Arab League on
May 11 had brought a halt to the artillery war. Shells and rockets
were exploding. Ambulances raced up to the hospital's tree-shaded
entrance.
   ``We go through this almost every day,'' Pierre said. He and the
other interns rushed to aid victims who were carried into the
emergency ward on blood-stained stretchers, many screaming in pain
or terror.
   Within minutes, the long corridors were filled with dead, dying
and the wounded. Doctors and nurses shouted for plasma and bandages.
   ``We try to hold up in front of the patients, but inside we're
really sick and tired of all this,'' Pierre said.
   By the end of his tour, 20 of the new arrivals had been
pronounced dead and 36 had undergone emergency surgery. Eighteen
had wounds light enough to be treated and released.
   Sirens wailed in the distance and Pierre winced, hiw eyes red
from lack of sleep. ``Let's hope it's not more casualties,'' he
said. ``We've had enough.''
   More than 350 people have been killed and nearly 1,400 wounded
in the often indiscriminate artillery and rocket barrages that
began March 8. Most of the casualties have been civilians.
   The hospital compound has been hit many times, once by a 155mm
shell that penetrated the fourth floor but did not explode. Seven
of Beirut's 24 hospitals have been damaged.
   Dr. Najat Daou, who treats wounded children, told of a
13-year-old who staggered into the emergency ward holding her
7-year-old brother under her right arm and said: ``Don't worry
about me. Just please save my brother. He's the only one left.''
   Her left hand was broken when a shell hit their home. It killed
her father, mother and four sisters. She carried her brother more
than a mile to the hospital, but he was dead.
</TEXT>
