<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cannes     05-19 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannes,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toxic Schlock Meets High Art at Riviera Movie Mart</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Toxic Avenger cavorts on the beach,
while in a theater nearby critics weigh the latest entry in the
International Film Festival.
   It is part of the incongruous reality that is Cannes, where
movies like ``Video Demons Do PsychoTown'' or ``The Toxic Avenger:
Part II'' are promoted alongside those competing for the coveted
Golden Palm award.
   The world's most prestigious showplace for film also is the
industry's biggest marketplace, and movies in the official
selection may die an artsy death while those shown in backstreet
theaters go on to blockbuster success.
   ``It's the first encounter of the first degree. The life and
death of a motion picture is decided here,'' said Menahem Golan, a
leading independent Hollywood producer-director in town for the
42nd annual festival.
   Thousands of producers, film makers and distributers from around
the world set up shop for two weeks each year in Cannes. They hawk
their wares in the basement of the Palais des Festivals, in hotel
suites or, for those able to pay for an aloof but powerful
presence, on yachts anchored in the Mediterranean.
   Giant movie banners are strung across the white facade of the
swank Carlton Hotel, which reigns over the Croisette, the
waterfront boulevard. Inside, the lobby is overrun with stands and
the upstairs suites are transformed into office space.
   Having a suite at the Carlton for doing business ``is like
having box seats to a Mets game,'' said Rob Aft, acting
international sales director for Troma, Inc., a small New
York-based company that is becoming a major force in the
exploitation film genre.
   ``We are never going to have an official selection at the
Palais,'' he said. ``But we're known here.''
   Troma is the creator of the Toxic Avenger, a former 98-pound
nerd named Melvin from Tromaville, N.J., who was transformed by
chemical waste into a deformed and hulking hero.
   In the first five days of the 13-day festival, Troma, which
buys, sells and distributes movies, did about $500,000 in business.
Troma President Lloyd Kaufman said he expected to close about $2
million in deals by the festival's end May 23.
   ``Cannes is known for being a fairly conservative, artistic
festival,'' said Aft. ``All the better for Troma,'' he added.
``They make films. We make movies.''
   Golan said that in less than a week, he closed more than $20
million in deals _ pre-sales on 20-film packages to countries like
Spain, Australia, Greece, Belgium, the Netherlands, Portugal and
Peru. He inaugurated his company, 21st Century, with the first
announced deal in the marketplace, worth ``multimillions.''
   The market first sprang up around the festival 29 years ago, and
organizers say it has grown into the world's largest. There are no
official figures on transactions.
   Film critic Roger Ebert says in his book about Cannes, ``Two
Weeks in the Midday Sun,'' that he once came across a man who sold
movies by the pound.
   Golan, whose brassy style _ rainbow suspenders over a T-shirt _
shines like the glitz of Cannes, cannot go unnoticed here.
   He mounted the festival's most aggressive publicity blitz, with
fliers strewn along the Croisette, dozens of daily full-page ads in
the various festival trade journals and a large office on the
ground floor of the Carlton.
   Golan co-founded Cannon Films with his cousin, Yorum Globus, and
produced an eclectic combination of high profile movies and schlock.
   Now, he talks up 21st Century products like ``Phantom of the
Opera'' and ``Mack the Knife,'' an adaptation of the musical ``The
Threepenny Opera.''
   Golan vows he he is ``getting out'' of exploitation movies,
saying, ``I want to associate myself with what is considered the
better product.''
   But 21st Century's repertoire includes ``Caged Fury'' and
``Deceit,'' the latter billed as a sci-fi space comedy about a
nuclear-armed alien sex fiend looking for earthly love.
</TEXT>
