<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PlutoniumBan     05-19 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plutonium Ban,395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose U.S.-Soviet Talks To End Plutonium Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy is leading a
congressional drive to push the Bush administration into
negotiations with the Soviet Union on a mutual halt to production
of plutonium, a key ingredient in all nuclear weapons.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., on Thursday unveiled a legislative proposal,
introduced in both the House and Senate, that would shut down parts
of the U.S. nuclear weapons complex unless President Bush pursued
such negotiations within six months.
   More than 90 congressmen cosponsored the House bill, and the
Senate version had seven sponsors. More than 20 environmental, arms
control and religious organizations announced their support for the
measure.
   The United States currently is unable to produce any plutonium
because of breakdowns in its weapons production complex, but Bush
has proposed spending several billion dollars to modernize and
expand plutonium production in the 1990s.
   The size of the U.S. plutonium stockpile is classified, but
private experts say there is enough to last for hundreds of years
without further production.
   Kennedy said the unplanned suspension of U.S. plutonium
production gives the administration an opening to counter Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's recent flurry of arms control
initiatives.
   ``We can't let him trot around the globe making it look like
he's the only one interested in arms control,'' said Rep. Ron
Wyden, D-Ore., a cosponsor of the House bill.
   The White House said no one was available to comment on the
legislation.
   The bills say that six months after enactment, Bush would be
prohibited from operating any of the facilities dedicated to
production of plutonium for military purposes unless he certified
one of the following conditions:
   _The Soviets refuse to negotiate a ban on plutonium and highly
enriched uranium.
   _The United States is unable to determine whether the Soviets
have halted production, or
   _The Soviets continue to get plutonium by operating civilian
plants.
   Gorbachev announced in London last month that he would shut down
by the end of the year three reactors that are producing enriched
uranium and plutonium for the Soviet nuclear arsenal. He called the
move a ``major step toward the complete cessation of production of
fissionable materials for use in weapons.''
   The Soviets will still have 11 reactors producing nuclear
weapons materials, according to congressional testimony Wednesday
by Energy Secretary James D. Watkins.
</TEXT>
