<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Judges     05-19 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judges,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Judge Candidate Still in the Running Despite Cranston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp criticism from Sen. Alan Cranston will
not block action on the nomination of San Francisco attorney Vaughn
Walker for a federal judgeship, the chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee says.
   ``I have no desire to hold up Walker,'' Judiciary Chairman
Joseph Biden, D-Del., told reporters Thursday following a committee
meeting.
   Cranston has opposed Walker's nomination to the U.S. District
Court in San Francisco, citing the attorney's vigorous defense at a
1988 hearing of a private club that allegedly discriminates against
women. He also says Walker waited too long before he resigned from
the club.
   Biden said Cranston's opposition ``will affect Walker
negatively'' but will not kill the nomination outright as would
have been the case under customs that once prevailed in the Senate.
   Under the Senate's old traditions, a judicial candidate's
home-state senator could torpedo the nomination outright merely by
sending the committee what lawmakers call a ``blue slip'' with a
negative recommendation.
   In that case, all work on the nomination would stop immediately
and the candidate's hopes for becoming a judge would be effectively
dead.
   Biden said the tradition changed in 1978, when Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., became chairman of the committee. He said Kennedy
believed that no individual senator should have the power to veto a
nominee.
   Biden said he would modify that formula. He said a home-state
senator now can veto a judicial candidate with a blue slip but only
if the administration neglects to consult with lawmakers before
making the nomination. Still, he said other senators should give
due weight to a negative recommendation from a home-state senator.
   He said he has discussed the need for consultations with the
administration officials and received assurances that they will
take place.
   Cranston has submitted a negative blue slip in Walker's case,
citing his defense of San Francisco's Olympic Club and criticizing
Walker for waiting until February to resign. The club does not
allow women to become full-fledged members. It attracted attention
previously when Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy resigned from
it a month before his confirmation hearings.
   Walker's confirmation is being urged by Sen. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif.
   Walker resigned from the Olympic Club in February saying he
enjoyed being a member but that ``unfortunately the club's present
membership practices are wrongly based on a policy of exclusion.''
   He said the club ``has certainly recently demonstrated that
race, ethnicity, religion and other arbitrary factors do not play
as role in club membership.
   ``Nonetheless,'' Walker added, ``I, as a member of the club,
have been disappointed that the club has not taken longer strides
toward making full membership status available to women.''
   Biden said he has not set a hearing date for Walker.
   Meanwhile, the Judiciary Committee sent to the full Senate with
favorable recommendations the four other judicial candidates whose
names currently are on Capitol Hill.
   They are Pamela Ann Rhymer of Los Angeles and Ferdinand F.
Fernandez as judges of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals;
Robert C. Bonner of Pasadena, Calif., as judge of the U.S. District
Court for the Central District of California; and Melinda F. Harmon
of Houston as District Court judge for the Southern District of
Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
