<FIRST>r w PM-NASAAppointments     05-19 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NASA Appointments,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>For A Change, Someone Moving To NASA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official from a space consulting firm is
bucking a trend and moving to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to take charge of its troubled space station program.
   Dr. William B. Lenoir, a former astronaut, is taking the post of
associate administrator for space station, which was recently left
vacant by the third resignation in a year.
   Asked about his moving back to a NASA job when others are
fleeing from NASA to industry, Lenoir joked that ``I get the
buy-low, sell-high part wrong all the time.''
   Lenoir flew in 1982 on the fifth flight of the space shuttle and
left NASA in 1984 for the firm of Booz-Allen &amp; Hamilton, Inc.,
which has a role in the space station program. He is a vice
president and a member of the board of the company and manages its
space systems division.
   Richard Truly, who awaits confirmation as administrator of the
agency, said he appointed Lenoir to the space station post because
``it's a program I'm committed to, it's a program I will continue
to fight for and I want to send the best signal that I can that we
are sending in a team of people that can do that.''
   Truly also announced the appointment of Richard Kohrs as
director of the space station, which will be called Freedom. Kohrs,
currently deputy director of the shuttle program, will be
responsible for design, development and future operations of the
station.
   Ray Tanner becomes deputy director of the station program.
   The space station, now in the design stage, faces rough sledding
from a budget-minded Congress this year _ including efforts to kill
the $32 billion program altogether.
   Lenoir told a news conference announcing his appointment the
program ``must turn the corner'' this year with sufficient funding.
   ``I do think that we should do something that presents this
country with a working space station on the time scale that we have
set, or admit that we can't; set it down and pick it up sometime
later,'' Lenoir said.
   Lenoir's new post was most recently held by Thomas L. Moser, who
served as acting associate administrator for space station for less
than a month before announcing his retirement. Moser had succeeded
James B. Odom, who held the job for only a year before resigning.
   In recent months NASA has lost its administrator, James C.
Fletcher; his deputy, Dale C. Myers, and the third-ranking
official, Noel C. Hinners. Hinners said he resigned partly because
of new federal ethics rules that would place strict restrictions on
post-government employment. He has taken a job with Martin
Marietta, a major space contractor.
   Since Hinners' announcement, there have been a spate of
resignations in various government agencies in addition to NASA. On
Tuesday, President Bush signed legislation to postpone the measure
for 60 days, until July 16.
   The new rules would have banned federal contractors from hiring
government officials who have supervised their competitors'
projects.
</TEXT>
