<FIRST>r w PM-SEC-Ruder     05-19 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Ruder,675</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Chairman Leaving After 2 Years In Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman
David S. Ruder, who was expected to be replaced by President Bush,
is resigning after leading the agency through two of its roughest
years.
   The 60-year-old attorney said Thursday he will return to his
teaching post at Northwestern University School of Law in Chicago
by the end of August. The precise timing of his departure will
depend on when Bush appoints a successor.
   Ruder's term expires in June 1991 and he gave no reason for
leaving. But Bush had been widely expected to replace him even
though senior Democrats in Congress were urging Ruder to stay on.
   Had he remained, Ruder faced the possibility of presiding over a
commission that could have been increasingly out of step with his
views.
   Ronald Reagan, a month before leaving the presidency, replaced
Aulana Peters, a Ruder ally, with Mary Schapiro, a former futures
industry lobbyist. The term of Charles C. Cox, another frequent
Ruder ally, has expired and his nomination by Reagan was never
acted on.
   The list of possible successors includes attorney Thomas A.
Russo, a former division director at the Commodities Futures
Trading Commission, and Edward H. Fleischman, who already holds a
seat on the five-member SEC. Also mentioned are Kraft Inc. Chairman
John M. Richman of Chicago and Harvey L. Pitt, former SEC general
counsel.
   White House spokesman B.J. Cooper said the administration was
reviewing the appointment and declined further comment.
   Ruder, known for his professorial manner, took over the SEC in
August 1987 and two months later found himself embroiled in the
aftermath of October 1987 stock market crash, the sharpest one-day
drop in stock prices since World War I.
   Also during his tenure, the seeds of the agency's historic
investigation of insider trading on Wall Street, planted by his
predecessor John S.R. Shad, bore fruit in the largest-ever
securities fraud case, settled for $650 million by Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Democrats in Congress were at first skeptical of Ruder, whose
scholarly experience in securities regulation included little
background in prosecution.
   However, one opponent, former Sen. William Proxmire of
Wisconsin, who was chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, now
says, ``I was wrong. ... I think he worked out well.''
   Ruder won friends among Democrats on Capitol Hill during the
post-crash debate over market reform for hewing to a somewhat
independent line from the free-market Reagan administration.
   The White House and Treasury Department resisted any attempt to
combine the regulation of stock and futures markets, which are
regulated with a lighter hand by the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission.
   Ruder, alone among top administration officials, argued that
stock and futures markets are closely linked and said his agency
should coordinate regulation of both.
   Also, in the wake of an outcry from small investors who lost
money in the crash, he pushed the securities industry to improve
its system of arbitrating disputes with customers and to take other
steps to restore public confidence.
   ``Ruder believes strongly in regulation,'' Proxmire said. ``He
believes that securities issuers should be vigorously required to
provide information to investors and if they don't they should be
penalized, fined or jailed.
   ``I think the Reagan administration felt that regulation of our
markets was not desirable and that we should have less regulation
rather than more,'' he said.
   Ruder ``exhibited real political courage in ... proposing
much-needed reform,'' said Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce finance subcommittee.
``Unfortunately for the nation (the reforms) were not supported by
the free-market theorists within the administration.''
   However, Roderick M. Hills, chairman of the SEC during the
administration of Gerald Ford, praised Ruder for resisting pressure
from the most ardent regulation advocates.
   ``I thought he brought an unusually scholarly and calm
perspective to one of the more turbulent times in the market's
history. He probably will be respected more for what he didn't do,
rather than for what he did do. Namely, he didn't overreact,''
Hills said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AgingAirliners     05-19 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Airliners,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Industry, Boeing React Favorably To Aging Airliner Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The airline industry and Boeing Co. are
welcoming government orders that will alter the way airlines keep
aging passenger jets safe.
   In a series of ``airworthiness directives'' announced Thursday,
the Federal Aviation Administration said it plans to order 161
modifications on older Boeing 727s, 737s and 747s and will give
airlines up to four years to comply.
   ``We think this is an important step in the right direction and
will further increase the already high levels of safety in the
industry,'' said Stephen Hayes, vice president of the Air Transport
Association, which represents airlines.
   The directives are expected to become law by late summer, after
a period for comment and modification. They would replace a method
of dealing with aging airliners which requires periodic inspections
and replacements only when parts show excessive wear.
   The FAA said its action ``marks a fundamental change in FAA's
philosophy for maintaining the airworthiness of older aircraft.''
   The FAA estimated the cost of modifying the 115 oldest jets at
$142 million. Other airliners would be affected as they age. An
industry group estimates the orders, which have been anticipated
for several months, eventually will cost U.S. and foreign airlines
more than $800 million and affect 1,300 planes.
   A Boeing statement said other countries' aviation agencies are
expected to adopt the orders.
   ``High standards must be maintained to assure the safety of
aging airplanes until economics dictate their retirement,'' said
Ben Cosgrove, a Boeing senior vice president.
   Only a handful of airliners have been retired in the last decade
as traffic throughout the world continues to increase and orders
for new jets are backlogged. The average age of the worldwide fleet
of passenger jets exceeds 13 years, and aviation experts expect it
to steadily increase.
   The new directives will require replacement or strengthening of
part of the fuselage, wings, doors, tail assembly, landing gear and
engine struts of airliners as they age.
   ``Due to the magnitude of the modification program, FAA
anticipates that the work will be staggered over a period of time
and generally coordinated with other scheduled maintenance,'' the
agency said in explaining its decision to give airlines four years
to comply.
   The action was prompted partly by the April 1988 accident over
Hawaii in which a Boeing 737 which had made almost 90,000 flights
lost an 18-foot section of its fuselage. A flight attendant was
killed but the aircraft landed without any other fatalities.
   The new requirements will force airlines to replace aging parts
earlier in a plane's life: 60,000 flights for 727s, 75,000 for 737s
and 20,000 for 747 jumbo jets. The larger aircraft make fewer but
longer flights. Airliners that reach 20 years old would also be
affected even if they have logged fewer flights.
   One requirement for 747s calls for a major modification of the
fuselage shell structure from the nose to the forward main
passenger entry door. The FAA estimates the work on that and 28
other modifications will require 35,000 man hours per airplane.
   For 737s, 58 changes are mandated, requiring more than 14,000
man hours; for 727s, the 74 required modifications will take more
than 17,000 man hours to complete.
   The FAA said the orders would initially affect 67 Boeing 727s,
28 Boeing 737s and 20 Boeing 747s owned by U.S. airlines.
   The FAA action follows guidelines proposed Feb. 28 by a
150-member task force of aviation industry and government experts
set up by the ATA and the Aerospace Industries Association.
   At that time, task force member Clyde Kizer told an interviewer
that ``the aircraft that are out there right now are perfectly
safe. ... This supplies an extra protection margin.''
   Other task forces are examining airliners manufactured by
McDonnell Douglas and other aircraft builders, and the FAA said it
plans to issue similar directives affecting other planes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AntarcticSpill     05-19 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antarctic Spill,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Group Alerts Skinner To Antarctic Fuel Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An environmental group wants Transportation
Secretary Samuel Skinner to look into a four-month-old accident and
fuel spill involving an Argentine Navy supply ship in Antarctica.
   The Environmental Defense Fund says that while the government
pushes cleanup of the Alaskan oil spill, little attention is being
paid to damage and danger from the Bahia Paraiso, which lies
overturned a mile from the U.S. scientific outpost at Palmer
Station, Antarctica.
   Fund lawyer Bruce Manheim, in a letter Thursday to Skinner, said
the Bahia Paraiso ran aground Jan. 28, spilling 170,000 gallons of
diesel fuel. But 70,000 gallons remain, posing a hazard because the
wreck could be crushed by severe ice conditions which are expected
with the onset of the Antarctic winter this month, he said.
   Manheim urged Skinner to determine the likely fate of fuel still
aboard the vessel, contact Argentine authorities to determine if
they plan further action and ``implement measures to eliminate
further pollution from the ship if a grave or imminent threat of
pollution exists.''
   Manheim said that while the Exxon Valdez spill of 11 million
gallons of crude oil on March 24 into Alaska's Prince William Sound
has produced a massive cleanup effort, Argentina ``has essentially
walked away'' from the Bahia Paraiso shipwreck.
   He asked Skinner to consider acting under international
agreements that Manheim said would allow the United States to
protect marine life and U.S. scientific interests on the icy
continent.
   Transportation Department spokesman Bob Marx said Skinner's
office had received the letter but would have no comment until it
could be reviewed.
   ``We'll see what action we could take,'' said Marx.
   Manheim said the spill has killed seals, penguins and other
Antarctic marine life and has destroyed important U.S. studies on
the effects of ozone depletion.
   ``Antarctica's worst environmental disaster has become a
forgotten oil spill,'' he said. ``The situation is bound to get
worse.''
   The Environmental Defense Fund describes itself as a non-profit
organization of scientists, economists, lawyers and others
interested in finding economically viable solutions to
environmental problems.
</TEXT>
