<FIRST>r w AM-StealthCritic     05-19 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Critic,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departing Pentagon Official Says Stealth Should Be Canned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon official who left his post a week
ago says the stealth bomber program should be scrapped because of
cost overruns and sloppy quality control by the company building
the long-range bomber, according to a published interview.
   Robert B. Costello, former undersecretary of acquisitions, told
The Washington Post in its Friday editions that Northrop Corp.'s
quality controls on development and production of the planes is
``terrible.''
   He said each of the planes will cost at least $600 million each,
but he said development is in such early stages that the Air Force
might not be able to calculate the true costs.
   Northrop's chief executive officer, Thomas V. Jones, defended
the radar-evading aircraft in a speech Wednesday to shareholders,
saying the airplane has achieved ``unprecedented technological
success.''
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci fought efforts by
Costello to kill the program, the newspaper said. But the new
Pentagon chief, Richard B. Cheney, has recommended slowing
production by at least a year while costs and technical problems
are reviewed.
   The Air Force has spent $15 billion on the stealth and has six
aircraft in various stages of construction. The program calls for
132 aircraft.
