<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Palme     05-19 0123</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Palme,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assassination Trial Postponed in Palme Case Until June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a man charged with killing
Prime Minister Olof Palme has been postponed for up to two weeks.
   Prosecutor Solveig Riberdahl said the reason for the delay was
that defense attorneys had not finished reading all 3,000 pages
from the interrogation files of the suspect, Christer Pettersson.
   The trial was originally set to start on May 29.
   Pettersson, who has a previous manslaughter conviction and long
criminal record, has denied killing Palme. Pettersson was arrested
last December after a lengthy investigation.
   The prime minister was shot to death on a main Stockholm street
on Feb. 28, 1986, while walking home from a movie with his wife.
</TEXT>
