<FIRST>r i PM-Niger-Elections     05-19 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Niger-Elections,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incumbent Named Sole Candidate in First Niger Vote Since 1974 Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Ali Saibou, Niger's president the past
18 months, has been named the sole candidate in the first
presidential elections in this West African country in nearly 20
years.
   Saibou was elected as president of the National Movement for a
Society of Development, which was created last year as the first
political party sanctioned since a 1974 military coup. It remains
the only legal party.
   Saibou, 49, is the third president this landlocked nation of 7
million people on the southern edge of the Sahara has had since it
became independent from France in 1960. Hamani Diori, president
from independence until the 1974 coup, was re-elected in 1965 and
1970.
   Saibou was picked by his fellow army officers to succeed Gen.
Seyni Kountche, who led the coup and held power until his death in
November 1987.
   Under Saibou, all political prisoners have been freed and
workers and students have had greater freedom of expression. But he
has ruled out permitting a multiparty system and said the army will
continue being a major factor in the country's politics.
   Elections are scheduled for December, though no date has been
set.
</TEXT>
