<HEAD>Marcos `Very Critical,' Suffering Organ Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 15th graf, `Asked if...,' to UPDATE with
comments from Imelda Marcos, spokesman; picks up 16th graf, `Marcos has...'
Raises 9th graf pvs, `In the...,' to 3rd graf to clarify purpose of surgery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos was
in ``very critical'' condition Thursday, suffering from kidney,
cardiac and pulmonary failure, hospital officials said.
   Marcos, 71, suffered acute renal failure and was taken to St.
Francis Medical Center's operating room late Thursday morning for
vascular access surgery, according to Gene Tiwanak, the hospital's
assistant administrator.
   In the 2}-hour surgical procedure, his veins were prepared for
hemodialysis, or the removal of body wastes from his blood by
machine, Tiwanak said.
   Marcos also experienced cardiac and pulmonary failure Thursday,
Tiwanak said.
   ``The prognosis is very poor and his condition is very
critical,'' Tiwanak said.
   Marcos, who was undergoing kidney dialysis, suffered severe
infection, including pneumonia, according to Dr. Azucena Ignacio,
his personal physician and an internist at St. Francis.
   Ignacio said Marcos was being treated with antibiotics and a
heart medication, which she refused to name.
   ``Some medications are working, some are not,'' Ignacio said.
   Marcos family was informed of his worsening condition and that
he was conscious before surgery, and had been conscious on and off
since, she said.
   ``The problem is that his kidneys failed and we had to get him
on dialysis quick,'' Tiwanak said.
   The deposed president, who is also suffering from pneumonia, was
placed on dialysis in the hospital's intensive care unit, Tiwanak
said.
   The procedure was not life-threatening, but the hours following
the surgery would be crucial, considering Marcos' frail health, the
hospital administrator said.
   Earlier, Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad had said Marcos had
only a 2 percent chance of surviving the operation, but Tiwanak
refused to comment on Marcos' prospects.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, was praying in the hospital chapel with
son Ferdinand Jr., nicknamed ``Bong Bong,'' Trinidad said.
   Asked if the Marcos family had given up hope, Trinidad said,
``No, we have always thought he would live. The thought of him
dying has never entered our minds.''
   Mrs. Marcos left the hospital later in the evening without
discussing the situation with the news media.
   ``I believe the hospital has issued a medical bulletin and
that's all I'm going to say,'' Mrs. Marcos said before getting into
a van.
   ``She's on her way to the house to make one call, one last
appeal'' to Philippine President Corazon Aquino to let Marcos
return home, said Marcos aide Arturo Aruiza, who accompanied Mrs.
Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly cited national security in rejecting
previous Marcos' requests to return to his homeland.
   Marcos has been hospitalized for heart, kidney and respiratory
ailments since Jan. 15. He was moved to the hospital's intensive
care unit on Monday and lapsed into critical condition the
following day. Before that, he had spent a month in the telemetry
ward, which monitors heart patients.
   The former president and his wife are under U.S. indictment on
charges of diverting more than $100 million from the Philippines
during their 20-year reign. Marcos has been separated from the case
because of health problems, but the case against his wife continues.
   The Marcoses have lived in exile in Hawaii since they were
toppled in a popular uprising in February 1986.
   Marcos has been hospitalized here three times since early
December for pneumonia, bronchial asthma and congestive heart
failure. He last entered the hospital Jan. 15 and underwent a
tracheostomy Feb. 1, after which he lapsed into critical condition.
   He eventually was upgraded to guarded condition and transferred
out of the intensive care unit, but doctors said he was
``chronically ill'' and unlikely to recover.
</TEXT>
