<HEAD>Stock Prices Fall on Rumors Marcos Died</HEAD>
<UNK>With AM-Marcos</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell Friday on the
Manila Stock Exchange following rumors that ousted President
Ferdinand Marcos had died in Hawaii, traders said.
   Marcos was reported in critical condition Thursday in a Honolulu
hospital after undergoing emergency surgery. Hospital officials
said the 71-year-old former Philippines leader was suffering from
kidney, cardiac and pulmonary failure.
   There was no immediate reaction from President Corazon Aquino to
Marcos' illness. Mrs. Aquino succeeded Marcos after the 1986
uprising that toppled his administration and forced him into exile
in Hawaii.
   But the Manila Stock Exchange's composite index fell to 1,084.53
from Thursday's close of 1,102.97.
   Traders said rumors of Marcos' death triggered a selling wave
around 11:40 a.m. that continued throughout the session.
   ``It provided a good reason for market participants to take
profits,'' said Edward Lee, president of Citisecurities Inc.
   Manila radio stations, the principal source of news for most
Filipinos, broadcast frequent reports on Marcos' condition
throughout the day.
   In Honolulu, Gene Tiwanak, assistant administrator of St.
Francis' Medical Center, said Marcos also suffered cardiac and
pulmonary failure.
   ``The prognosis is very poor and his condition is very
critical,'' Tiwanak said.
   The deposed president, who is also suffering from pneumonia, was
placed on dialysis in the hospital's intensive care unit, Tiwanak
said.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos to return from Hawaii,
citing national security reasons. On Thursday, presidential
Executive Secretary Catalino Macaraig said there was no change in
that position.
   On Friday, the Philippine Daily Globe reported from Honolulu
that doctors had told U.S. and Filipino officials that
``progressive and massive organ failure is beginning to take
place.''
   The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said doctors
believed Marcos could ``fight back'' if his will to live was strong.
   ``If he does fight back and lasts several more days, it won't be
because our diagnosis is wrong,'' the paper quoted doctors as
saying.
   The report appeared before word from Hawaii that Marcos had
undergone surgery.
