<HEAD>Dickinson Wants Decision on Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should quickly make up its mind about
whether to approve President Bush's plan to proceed with
development of two kinds of land-based nuclear missiles, says the
top Republican on the House Armed Services Committee..
   Rep. Bill Dickinson, R-Ala., asked Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
to seek congressional approval if he intends to use money
designated for deployment of the rail-mobile MX missile to keep the
Midgetman missile program alive for the remainder of fiscal 1989.
   In his new Pentagon budget request for fiscal 1990, Bush calls
for $1.2 million for deployment of the MX and $100 million to
continue research and development of the Midgetman.
   Both weapons are intended to be part of the nation's land-based
arsenal of atomic-tipped missiles, but critics say the efforts to
cut the federal deficit mean both weapons can't be built.
