<FIRST>r w PM-MilkShortages 470   05-19 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milk Shortages, 470</SECOND>
<HEAD>De la Garza Concerned About Lunch Program, Food Bank Shortages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School lunch programs could face milk and
cheese shortages as early as this fall because excesses of dairy
products have been reduced, says the chairman of the House
Agriculture Committee.
   Because Congress passed legislation four years ago to reduce
excess dairy-farm output, surpluses available for government
purchase have been sharply reduced, Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas,
said Thursday.
   ``We had to change the legislation and reduce the expenses of
the government ... and once the surplus stock is reduced then we
don't have enough for the school lunch and commodity distribution
programs for the poor,'' de la Garza said.
   ``Food banks, food for the elderly, Head Start, every place that
gets butter, cheese, non-fat dry milk is being reduced or will have
to be reduced because we don't have the ample surplus,'' he said.
   Jack Parnell, deputy secretary of agriculture, has confirmed
that ``due to reduced surplus production of dairy goods there will
far less milk and other dairy products to distribute to school
districts for use in lunch programs across the nation,'' de la
Garza said.
   A spokeswoman for the Food and Nutrition Service, the
Agriculture Department agency that administers the school lunch
program, agreed there will be less dairy products available next
fall.
   Kelly Shipp, spokeswoman for Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter, said the milk and cheese in question are ``bonus''
commodities given to schools in addition to what they ordinarily
receive.
   ``The problem is we don't have it,'' she said. ``The stocks (of
non-fat dry milk and cheese) are so low, we have a very limited
amount.''
   De la Garza said the Commodity Credit Corp. purchased 12.3
billion pounds of surplus dairy goods in fiscal 1986 for
distribution to various agencies. The following year purchases
dropped to 5.4 billion pounds.
   According to figures from the Department of Agriculture, the CCC
purchased 9.7 billion pounds in fiscal 1988 and current projections
indicate this year's totals will reach at least 8.2 billion.
   But a USDA official said most of the 7.4 billion pounds of food
purchased to date has been butter. The official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said cheese represents only a fraction of
this year's purchases and not one pound of non-fat dry milk has
been bought since last June.
   The official said USDA can only buy what the dairy industry
offers to sell. This year, because of a strong commercial demand
for non-fat dry milk and cheese, most of the products offered to
the government under the price support program have been butter.
   De la Garza said some commodities may have to be bought on the
open market, but the cost would be about one-third more expensive
than purchasing surplus milk and cheese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
