<DOCNO> AP890519-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Exxon-Meeting 1stLd-Writethru a0739 05-19 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Meeting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0739,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Holds Annual Meeting, Demonstrators Gather Peacefully</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with RAwl promising Exxon drug
testing, report on number of credit cards returned, quotes. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, `As we've...' ADDS 2 grafs with final tally of votes, other reforms.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Exxon Corp. shareholders
dragged their chairman through a 4-hour, 20-minute annual meeting
on Thursday, challenging him to explain the company's actions in
the nation's worst oil spill.
   Outside, about 250 demonstrators gathered peacefully, listening
to speeches by ecologist Barry Commoner and others. Three dozen
police officers kept them from the entrance of the suburban hotel
35 miles west of New York City where the meeting was held.
   Exxon Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl rejected one suggestion that he
resign from the biggest American oil company and another suggestion
that he put his Exxon shares into a special fund for ensuring oil
tanker safety.
   But he assured stockholders that he and other Exxon management
would be part of major policy changes at the company, including
random drug testing.
   ``I want you to know there's going to be equity,'' Rawl told
about 1,700 Exxon shareholders attending the first annual meeting
since the March 24 spill by the tanker Exxon Valdez. ``We will have
random testing of our people and of senior management, including me.
   Exxon President Lee Raymond said the number of customers who had
returned their Exxon credit cards, apparently in response to the
oil spill, was up to 18,000 out of a total of 7 million.
   ``As we've said before, the board and all of our employees are
profoundly sorry about the impact this major accident has had on
the natural environment and the people who live and work in the
region,'' Rawl told about 2,000 shareholders and others.
   ``The accident itself cannot be undone,'' he said.
   ``In time when the job is done I'm confident that it will be
evident to every fair-minded person that our employees met this
major challenge with a high level of determination and
professionalism.
   ``We're determined to show through deeds that we really care
about the environment and wildlife,'' Rawl said.
   Rawl showed a 15-minute film prepared by Exxon on the March 24
spill by the Exxon Valdez in Alaska's Prince William Sound.
   During a prolonged question-and-answer session afterward, Rawl
rejected a suggestion that he resign, made by Ed Rothschild of the
activist group Citizen Action.
   ``The answer is, no, I won't,'' Rawl said to a mixture of
applause and boos. He said his resignation would distract the
company at a critical time.
   ``Management has to take responsibility,'' said shareholder
Dorothy Braude Edinburg. ``Some heads have to fall.''
   Some shareholders came for the excitement of potential
confrontation between environmentalists and company management. In
fact, the questioning was tough but orderly.
   ``We expected fireworks and didn't see it,'' said shareholder
Herbert Forrest.
   Outside the meeting, Commoner, a former presidential candidate,
told the crowd that the spill points out what he called U.S.
overreliance on fossil fuels.
   ``We are here to pass judgment on a crime against nature and the
American people,'' Commoner said. ``That is the only adequate
description for what Exxon has done in Alaska.''
   One demonstrator, Isabel Byrd of Trenton, N.J., was dressed in
an overstuffed tuxedo, wore a pig's nose and walked on stilts. She
identified herself as a ``pig from Exxon,'' and said her outfit
represented the company's corporate mentality.
   ``We just came to say we don't have to care, because we're
Exxon,'' said Ms. Byrd. ``We're greedy and we're pigs.''
   A federal investigation began this week into the causes of the
spill, which has fouled hundreds of miles of Alaskan waters and
coastline and killed numerous fowl and wildlife.
   Several pension funds with large holdings of Exxon stock
publicized their dissatisfaction earlier this month with the
company's handling of the spill and cleanup. The groups also
demanded changes in what they called Exxon's ``inadequate state of
preparedness'' for dealing with future problems and said thy would
vote their shares against Exxon management if it failed to
adequately address those concerns.
   Alaska pension fund officials said they would withhold their
650,600 shares from voting to underscore the state's concern about
the spill.
   The largest shareholders included pension funds from New York
City, New York State and the California Public Employee Retirement
System, the largest individual U.S. public pension fund.
   Together, the funds own more than 20 million shares of Exxon
stock valued at more than $800 million, amounting to less than 2
percent of the company's total 1.33 billion outstanding common
shares.
   In the final tally at the meeting, 976.6 million shares, or 77.8
percent, were voted in favor of electing the current slate of
directors.
   Among the demands by the institutional shareholders were the
appointment to the board of an environmental expert and the
formation of a committee to review Exxon policies on the
environment and worker safety and health.
</TEXT>
