<HEAD>Dollar Off Slightly Against Yen, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed slightly lower against the
Japanese yen Friday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange regained its
losses of the previous day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
136.12 points Thursday, gained 144.65 points, or 0.44 percent, to
finish the week at 34,000.98.
   The dollar closed at 138.77 yen, down 0.11 yen from Thursday's
finish of 138.88 yen. Opening lower at 138.55 yen, the currency
moved between 138.15 yen and 138.90 yen.
   Traders said the dollar slipped following its overnight decline
in New York, spurred by coordinated intervention by central banks
in the United States and Europe.
   During morning trading, the Bank of Japan stepped into the
market, selling an estimated $400 million to support the yen,
traders said.
   On the stock exchange, the market's main index suffered a slight
setback in early trading due to speculation over a possible hike in
the nation's key interest rates, but later rebounded on
expectations of higher prices next week, dealers said. It was also
helped by the dollar's slight retreat against the yen, they added.
