<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--AIDS     05-19 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--AIDS,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>The AIDS Trend: More Drug Users Users</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AIDS is being seen more and more often among drug
abusers, the national Centers for Disease Control reported.
   Homosexual and bisexual men still account for most AIDS cases in
the United States. The CDC reported Thursday that they made up 63
percent of the AIDS cases reported last year. That was down from 70
percent in 1987 and 72 percent in 1985, the CDC said, in an
analysis of AIDS in the United States.
   Meanwhile, the proportion of adult or adolescent men with
intravenous drug abuse as their lone AIDS risk factor jumped from
14 percent in 1987 to 20 percent in 1988.
   The percentage of cases listing both homosexual activity and
drug abuse was 8 percent in 1987, 7 percent in 1988.
   In the agency's latest monthly AIDS statistics, 56,783 of the
nation's 94,280 reported AIDS cases were homosexual or bisexual
men; 18,819 were drug abusers, and 6,620 were both.
   Although 91 percent of the adult AIDS cases reported since 1982
have been males, drug use is a strong factor among the number of
female AIDS cases as well.
   The percentage of drug use among female adult and adolescent
AIDS patients decreased from 60 percent in 1984 to 49 percent in
1987 but rose again to 53 percent last year.
   By the end of 1988, 3,589 heterosexually acquired AIDS cases had
been reported to the CDC. The majority _ 65 percent, or 2,340 _
were in people who reported sex with high-risk partners.
   The agency also noted that blacks and Hispanics still ``have
suffered a disproportionately large share of the burden of AIDS in
the United States.'' U.S. blacks have an AIDS rate of 84 cases per
100,000 people, and Hispanics have a rate of 73 cases per 100,000,
compared to 26 for whites and 14 percent for Asians and Pacific
Islanders.
   ``The racial distribution of cases has remained stable over
time, with few exceptions,'' the CDC said.
   The U.S. Public Health Service has predicted that the United
States will report 365,000 AIDS cases by the end of 1992, with
263,000 patients dead by then. In 1992, a projected 172,000 AIDS
patients are expected to need medical care at a cost of $5 billion
to $13 billion.
   In the CDC's latest monthly statistics, through April, 54,402,
or 58 percent, of 94,280 reported patients have already died. The
actual AIDS fatality rate ``approaches 100 percent within five
years of diagnosis,'' the CDC said, noting some patients' deaths
never are reported to authorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0507EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev     05-19 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interview: Soviet Leader Earns $22,800 a Year, Loves Walks in Woods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev earns the equivalent of
$22,800 a year, loves to walk in the woods and was raised in a
peasant family where he began working at age 13, the official news
agency Tass said.
   The Soviet president did not make any startling revelations
about himself during an interview in a Communist Party publication
that Tass quoted Thursday, but he did provide some details to
Soviets wanting personal information about their leader.
   That kind of information has been kept strictly secret by
previous leaders, but Gorbachev, 58, gradually has been breaking
down the barrier with his policy of glasnost.
   ``Virtually all my time except for several hours needed for
sleep are given to work,'' Gorbachev told the News of the Communist
Party Central Committee, a monthly journal. Gorbachev has led the
Soviet Union for four years.
   ``I try to use my rare rest hours to their fullest,'' he added.
``My interests are varied: reading literature, the theater, music,
film. My favorite form of rest is walking in the forest. But I have
to admit: I manage to do it less and less.''
   Gorbachev said his schedule is a strain not only on himself but
on his family, and he said he valued the support of his wife,
Raisa, as well as that of his daughter, Irina, and her husband,
Anatoly, who are doctors.
   Gorbachev has two granddaughters, Ksenia and Anastasia.
   Like any other member of the ruling Communist Party Politburo,
Gorbachev said he receives a salary of 1,200 rubles (about $1,900)
a month. Candidate members of the Politburo receive 100 rubles
($160) less, he said.
   His salary is about five times the monthly wage of the average
Soviet industrial worker.
   Gorbachev said all the money he has received for his book
``Perestroika and New Thinking,'' 2 million copies of which have
been published in almost 100 countries, went to the party budget or
to several favorite charities. Among them he named the funds to
help victims of earthquakes in Armenia and Tadzhikistan, the Soviet
Culture Fund of which Mrs. Gorbachev is a board member, and for
construction of a new children's park in Moscow.
   Speaking about the technology that keeps him in touch with the
Kremlin when he is traveling, Gorbachev said he first learned about
the Dec. 7 Armenian earthquake that killed 25,000 people in a
telephone call he received from Moscow while on a ferry boat in New
York harbor. He was in New York for a U.S.-Soviet summit meeting.
   Gorbachev has an apartment in Moscow, believed to be in the
Lenin Hills area, and a country house provided by the Soviet
government. ``Not I, not any member of my family has ever owned a
country house anywhere,'' Gorbachev said.
   Gorbachev emphasized his rural roots and said he was proud of
his father Sergei's service in World War II. His father was wounded
in Czechoslovakia during the war, he said.
   Gorbachev said he started doing farm work at age 13 and was
working as a helper on a combine when he was 15.
   The News of the Communist Party Central Committee has become the
party's favorite means of releasing controversial material.
   Several months ago it published the text of former Moscow party
chief Boris N. Yeltsin's 1987 speech warning that a cult of
personality could develop around Gorbachev.
   Less than a month after the speech in October 1987, Yeltsin was
fired as Moscow party chief. But his speech was not published until
early this year.
   In another issue, the journal published for the first time in
the Soviet Union Nikita S. Khrushchev's 1956 ``secret speech''
denouncing dictator Josef Stalin.
   Its circulation is limited. About 650,000 copies are printed for
a country of almost 287 million people.
</TEXT>
