<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-19 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What do Vice President Quayle, ``Cousin Brucie''
Morrow, and Malcolm Forbes have in common?
   Paternity, if nothing else.
   The three shared the luncheon dais Thursday with seven others
named Fathers of the Year by the National Father's Day Committee.
   Morrow, host of CBS radio's syndicated ``Cruisin' America with
Cousin Brucie,'' asked the vice president if he could call him
``Cousin Dan,'' ribbed him about getting stuck in traffic caused by
his motorcade and asked if he could deduct the extra $4 cab fare as
a business deduction on next year's income tax.
   ``No,'' Quayle replied.
   Quayle quoted his 14-year-old son, Tucker, as saying, ``Dad,
Father of the Year? That can't be. ... The year's not over yet.''
   The vice president said he solves all the problems around his
house _ ``by letting the kids hear those three little words: ask
your mother.''
   Quayle and his wife, Marilyn, have three children.
   Millionaire-publisher Forbes was asked if his financial status
allowed him to give his five children anything they wanted when
they were growing up.
   ``Not really,'' said Forbes, a motorcycle and hot-air balloon
enthusiast, ``because by the time I was through buying my toys,
there was no money left over for theirs.''
   The other winners were NBC sports commentator Len Berman; Sen.
Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., New York Mets pitcher Ron Darling; CBS
newscaster Bob Schieffer, New York Knicks coach Rick Pitino, Fox
Television media critic Stewart Klein, and New York City newscaster
Ernie Anastos.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While state representatives were debating
deer vasectomies and tossing around a plastic urinal, their august
Senate colleagues staged a speed voting contest.
   ``Remember the Mickey Mouse Club had `anything can happen day?'
This is one of them,'' Rep. James Kosteva said Thursday, during the
House's seven-hour budget debate.
   The flying red urinal, normally used by bedridden men,
interrupted Rep. Carl Gnodtke's speech on the tourism potential of
strategically placed portable toilets with ``Say Yes! to Michigan''
stickers on them.
   Rep. Margaret O'Connor proposed an amendment to ensure tax
dollars would not be used for vasectomies to control the deer
population of Detroit's Belle Isle. The amendment lost.
   Meanwhile, Senate leaders challenged the chamber to see how fast
it could approve a series of minor bills.
   The first passed in 40 seconds, not fast enough for Majority
Leader John Engler, a Republican.
   ``We can do better than that,'' he said. ``Everybody's in their
seat. Let's try again.''
   The second bill was launched in 11 seconds, the third in four.
To cheers and applause, the senators mustered the votes for the
final bill in just two seconds.
