<FIRST>r a PM-SalemBombs     05-19 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salem Bombs,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indiana Lawmaker Relieved After Arrests in Planting of Bombs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state lawmaker says he is relieved two men
have been arrested in connection with 13 bombs planted around town
last summer but he may never rest easy again.
   The largest bomb _ 52 sticks of dynamite _ was found under a
stairwell behind state Rep. Frank Newkirk Jr.'s law office.
Although no bombs were found at his home, Newkirk said he always
feared for his wife and their four children.
   ``Every night I still walk around the house with a flashlight to
make sure there's nothing out there,'' he said Thursday. ``That's
probably a habit I'll never end.''
   John M. Hubbard III, a 31-year-old factory worker, and Gerald
Conrad, a 42-year-old co-worker, were arrested Wednesday, accused
of planting explosives targeted at Newkirk, 32, who also is the
mayor's son.
   They were indicted Thursday on federal charges of possession of
stolen dynamite, conspiracy, making bombs and attempting to destroy
roads and buildings in this southern Indiana community of 6,000.
   Hubbard and Conrad are being held in Indianapolis.
   The bombs were planted around Salem, under bridges and behind
buildings. Three of the bombs fizzled; none of the 13 exploded.
   Authorities have declined to speculate on a motive, but a
criminal complaint filed in federal court described Hubbard as a
``lifelong rival'' of Newkirk's.
   Newkirk and Hubbard were in the same Cub Scout pack and competed
for leading roles in high school plays.
   ``If there was a rivalry, it was in John's mind,'' Newkirk said.
``I understand maybe he wanted to achieve some of the things I
had.''
   Newkirk, a Democrat, said the two men disagreed on politics and
sometimes debated issues when they happened to pass on the
sidewalk. ``John believed government was too involved in people's
lives,'' Newkirk said.
   The relationship between Newkirk and Hubbard dates back to their
Scout pack, which was led by Newkirk's father.
   ``My father really liked John,'' the younger Newkirk said.
``John was overweight and I was overweight, too. My father realized
how cruel children can be about things like that, and I think my
father kind of went out of his way to look after John.''
   Newkirk said Hubbard once complained about losing out to Newkirk
in leading roles in high school plays.
   Newkirk, a former deputy prosecutor who was first elected to the
Legislature in 1984, said he became suspicious of Hubbard about two
weeks after the bombs were found.
   He and his wife, Denise, were working in a booth at a county
fair when they ran into Hubbard.
   ``After a while, he began to talk about the bombings,'' Newkirk
said. ``He had a lot of information. He told me where the bombs
were located, what the dynamite would do if it were exposed to fire
and what would have happened if the bombs had gone off.''
   Newkirk took that information to state police.
   Hubbard's mother, Opal Kramer, said Thursday she was not
surprised her son was able to talk specifically about the bombs.
   ``Everybody in town was talking about the bombings,'' said Mrs.
Kramer, who has taught kindergarten in Salem for 23 years. ``The
pictures were very vivid on TV and in the papers.''
   She described her son as a vocal, opinionated, intelligent man
who liked guns but would not harm anyone ``unless he's under the
influence, and I don't know that he would (harm anyone) then.''
   She said Hubbard had been hospitalized for about a month for
alcohol abuse treatment earlier this year.
</TEXT>
