<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-19 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held steady in calm European
trading this morning following a day of erratic trading marked by
central bank intervention.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the dollar remained well-supported from a
fundamental point of view, with large institutional investors
attracted by relatively high U.S. interest rates that show no signs
of being lowered.
   This dollar-buying would be balanced by profit-taking, they
said, but most agreed that the dollar would be unlikely to drop
sharply in future.
   Some predicted the central banks would intervene if the dollar
hit the 1.9700 German mark level.
   On Thursday, the U.S. unit was boosted by news that the West
German Bundesbank's central bank council had decided to leave its
key interest rates unchanged and by a rise in U.S. consumer prices.
   But a wave of concerted intervention started the dollar on its
downward move to its late levels.
   In London today, the dollar rose against the British pound. It
cost $1.6179 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6180 late Thursday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Thursday:
   _1.9692 West German marks, up from 1.9660
   _1.7560 Swiss francs, up from 1.7552
   _6.6665 French francs, up from 6.6490
   _2.2166 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2240
   _1,434.25 Italian lire, down from 1,439.50
   _1.1885 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1927
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.11 yen to close at 138.77 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 138.80 yen.
   Gold opened in London at $367.85 a troy ounce, down from $370.75
late Thursday. At mid-morning, London bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $366.25.
   In Zurich, gold fell to $366.15, compared with $370.25 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.51 to close at $367.22.
   Silver fell on the London market where the metal was trading at
$5.36 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $5.43.
</TEXT>
