<FIRST>r i PM-Australia-USNavy     05-19 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Australia-US Navy,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine Drowns When U.S. Landing Craft Capsizes Off Australia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amphibious landing craft from the
USS Duluth capsized today during naval exercises off northeastern
Australia, drowning a U.S. Marine and injuring two others, the U.S.
Embassy said.
   Fifty-two people, including an Australian, were thrown into the
water when the small craft overturned off Shoalwater Bay, 745 miles
north of Sydney, according to an embassy statement. Australian
defense sources said nine inflatable Zodiac boats carrying five
people each were involved.
   Embassy spokesman Arthur Lefkowitz said Marines from the USS
Duluth, an amphibious transport dock ship, were being put ashore
when the accident occurred.
   ``They were making a landing and apparently the surf was heavier
than they anticipated or the winds were wrong,'' Lefkowitz said.
``Several of the boats overturned in the surf, dumping all the
Marines aboard into the water.''
   The embassy said the military exercises were suspended
temporarily after the accident. The exercises, codenamed ``Valiant
Usher,'' started Monday and involve seven U.S. and Australian ships
and 5,000 Marines and sailors.
   The embassy said helicopters from the Duluth and the USS Bellau
Wood buzzed the accident site, but rough seas and overcast weather
hampered the rescue effort.
   The identity of the dead Marine was witheld pending notification
of relatives, but Lefkowitz said the Marines were based at Camp
Pendleton, in Southern California.
   Australian defense sources said the Marine drowned when the
inflatable craft overturned in rough conditions.
   ``The Americans are dealing with the injured themselves. They
have not told us very much about (it),'' said an official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Lefkowitz said the Marines were wearing life jackets at the
time. He described the injuries as minor and said the injured
Marines were being treated on board the Duluth. The other U.S.
ships taking part in the exercise are the Belleau Wood, Germantown
and Frederick.
   The Australian vessels were the guided missile destroyer HMAS
Brisbane, the destroyer escort HMAS Torrens and the patol boat HMAS
Townsville.
</TEXT>
