<FIRST>r a PM-LATeachers     05-19 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Teachers Strike Enters 5th Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Inside Strike, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers entered their fifth day of a walkout
today demanding a chunk of the state's newly announced tax surplus
in their negotiations with the nation's second-largest school
district.
   Neither the district nor the teachers would discuss with
reporters what progress had been made in talks held Thursday night.
   ``There are going to be some meetings on our side in the morning
and some meetings on their side in the morning and we'll be back
tomorrow,'' United Teachers-Los Angeles President Wayne Johnson
said after the talks at a downtown hotel broke up around midnight.
   More than 22,000 teachers are on strike, with about 11,000
remaining teachers and substitutes crossing picket lines at the
city's 600 schools.
   Only 283,620 of the Los Angeles Unified School District's
551,759 students attended classes Thursday, school officials said.
   A state fact-finder's report this week concluded that no
additional money was available for teachers' salaries beyond the
district's offer of a 21.5 percent raise over three years.
   But confusion over the salary issue arose after Gov. George
Deukmejian announced Wednesday that the state expects to receive an
extra $2.5 billion windfall in unanticipated tax revenues over the
next two years.
   According to the terms of the state's Proposition 98, virtually
all revenue above an expenditure limit is to be given to schools.
   The Los Angeles district reportedly could receive $120 million
to $228 million of that money. But Board of Education President
Roberta Weintraub said the district could not improve its wage
offer because it had no assurances it would get the additional
funds.
   Johnson, encouraged by the windfall report, immediately raised
the union's wage demand from 21 percent over two years to 26
percent over three years, including a 10 percent retroactive boost
for the first year. The teachers have been working without a
contract since September.
   ``It is not acceptable,'' Weintraub said. ``We will not even
consider a 10 (percent first-year raise).''
   ``If they stand firm, the union's strike is going to continue,''
Johnson said. He dismissed the fact-finder report, saying its
author did not know about the extra state money.
   Ms. Weintraub said the district might offer a 24 percent raise
over three years, with 8 percent for each year, ``If we get the
money'' from the windfall.
   The strike is the district's first since a 23-day walkout in
1970.
   Teachers annual salaries range from $23,440 to $43,319, with the
high end of the scale for those with doctorates, 98 extra course
units and 19 years' experience.
</TEXT>
