<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-China     05-19 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Students Pledge Support to China's Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at a Taiwanese university pledged
their support today for Chinese students whose hunger strike for
democracy in Beijing has won widespread backing in mainland China.
   ``You are our brothers,'' said a statement signed by all 12,000
students at the National Chengkung University. ``Although you do
not know us personally, please remember that we are with you all
the time.''
   The students at Chengkung, an engineering university, said they
regretted thousands of Chinese students have had ``to treat
themselves in such a harsh way to gain a brighter future'' for
China.
   Student leaders from Chengkung and 19 other Taiwanese
universities were scheduled to meet later today to discuss ways to
support the Chinese students, who began their hunger strike in
Beijing's Tiananmen Square on May 13.
   The hunger strike is the largest show of defiance in 40 years of
Communist rule on the China mainland. The Chinese government today
issued an order effective at midnight forbidding demonstrations.
   On Wednesday, the ruling Nationalist Party said it would provide
support ``through various channels'' to the pro-democracy student
demonstrators. It did not elaborate.
   A major Taiwanese newspaper, The United Daily News, said in a
dispatch from Beijing that the Chinese students have declined any
medical or other assistance from Taiwan to avoid a crackdown on
their movement by Chinese authorities.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 when they lost a
civil war on the mainland, are still technically at war with the
Chinese Communists.
   They continue to reject any official contacts with the
Communists, although they have adopted a more flexible policy the
past two years that allows Taiwanese and Chinese to exchange visits
and trade through third countries.
</TEXT>
