<HEAD>Noriega Appears But Makes No Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega made his
first public appearance since the nullified May 7 elections before
a cheering crowd, but he had nothing to say about his country's
crisis or his future plans.
   Noriega was greeted with roars and chants by the more than 1,200
military, government and party workers who gathered Thursday night,
but he gave no speech and made few comments to reporters.
   ``I'm fine,'' Panama's de facto ruler said repeatedly when asked
how he had held up in the tension-filled weeks since May 7.
   When asked how much longer he could go on, he laughed and said,
``That's a good question.''
   The elections were nullified by a government tribunal even as
international observers said opposition candidate Guillermo Endara
was leading Noriega's handpicked candidate 3-1.
   Noriega, commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces, has been
accused of ordering the beatings of opposition candidates May 10.
   At the rally, Noriega supporters watched a series of traditional
music and dance mixed with anti-American skits, poetry and a
recitation of U.S. interventions in Panama.
   ``With Noriega to the Year 2000,'' signs declared. Members of
the crowd said they were members of the government party or
government workers, or both.
   ``We came voluntarily, we weren't forced,'' said one woman, who
refused to give her name but said she worked in a hospital laundry
in Colon, 50 miles north of Panama City. She said she was bused in
after work.
   She and her friends joined in a chant of ``Noriega, for sure,
hit the Yankees hard!'' which rhymes in Spanish.
   Noriega was pursued by a pack of journalists as he left the
convention center but did little more than smile in reply to
repeated requests for a message to Bush or to the Organization of
American States.
   Bush and the OAS have condemned election fraud and repression,
and the OAS is sending a committee of foreign ministers to report
on the situation in Panama.
   News media run by the Noriega regime denounced Wednesday night's
OAS resolution condemning Noriega.
   In an interview with WBAI Radio early Thursday in New York,
Noriega declared that the United States was persecuting Panama
``because we are black.''
   In other interview comments, Noriega repeated his frequent
assertions that the U.S. Embassy in Panama is misinforming the
White House and that the United States was engaged in aggression.
   Noriega was indicted on drug smuggling and money laundering
charges in Florida in February 1988. Washington and the local
opposition since then have mounted a concerted campaign against him
to no avail.
   Noriega denies the drug accusations. He and his supporters
contend the United States has slandered him as part of a scheme to
renege on its commitments under the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties.
   The pacts oblige Washington to hand over complete control of the
waterway to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
