<HEAD>Parents Plead for Hostage's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of kidnapped Belgian physician
Jan Cools today pleaded with his captors to free their son or
``give us at least a sign'' from him.
   Cools' parents were in Sidon to try to gain their son's release.
He was kidnapped May 21, 1988. The 32-year-old doctor was working
for the Norwegian humanitarian agency, Norwac, when he disappeared
after leaving his base in the Rashidiyeh Palestinian refugee camp.
   ``We appeal to the Lebanese and Palestinian peoples and groups
to release Jan,'' Paul Cools told a news conference. His wife,
Louisa, fought back tears as she addressed the captors: ``We want
to ask you to give us at least a sign of Jan.''
   A previously unknown group calling itself Soldiers of Justice
claimed it kidnapped Cools, and it branded him a spy.
   Also today, Beirut's Ash-Shiraa magazine said the ``file of the
foreign hostages held in Lebanon is now in the hands of Ahmad
Khomeini,'' son of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran.
   In a brief, unattributed report, the magazine said Ahmad
Khomeini ``has recently summoned several officials of Hezbollah to
discuss this issue.'' It said Khomeini had taken charge of the
hostage issue from Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani and
Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri, who was forced to resign last
month because of his criticism of Khomeini's policies.
   The fundamentalist Shiite Moslem Hezbollah, or Party of God, is
believed to be the umbrella for pro-Iranian factions that hold most
of the 15 foreigners held hostage in Lebanon.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Two West German relief workers also reportedly were kidnapped in
Sidon on Tuesday, but no group has claimed to hold them.
