<HEAD>Dissidents Arrested for Attempting Contact With North Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with South Korea urging restraint in U.S.
contacts with North Korea. EDITS to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident poet and another activist
were arrested today on charges they violated a national security
law by attempting to contact communist North Korea, prosecutors
said.
   Ko Un, the poet, and Lee Jae-oh, a leader of a dissident
alliance, sought private talks in the border town of Panmunjom with
North Koreans on national reunification, the prosecutors said. The
capitalist South bans contacts with the North on reunfication and
other issues.
   Also today, South Korea's Foreign Minister Choi Ho-joong urged
the United States to show restraint in diplomatic contacts with
North Korea. U.S. diplomats met this week in Beijing with North
Korean diplomats for the fourth time since Washington lifted its
ban on talks with the communist government.
   Ko, 56, was accused of attempting to take six literary figures
to the border truce village in March to meet with North Korean
counterparts for talks on reuniting two countries that have been
divided since 1945.
   Lee, chairman of the Committee of the Fatherland of the United
National Democratic Movement, also was accused of trying to hold
separate talks in Panmunjom with North Korea's Communist Party
panel on unification.
   Lee, 45, was charged with conspiring to plan the Rev. Moon
Ik-hwan's recent secret visit to Pyongyang, the communist capital.
Moon, adviser to the United National Democratic Movement, was
arrested April 13 upon return from Pyongyang.
   Foreign Minister Choi said today the United States should
improve relations with North Korea only if its allies, China and
the Soviet Union, take similar measures in relations with the South.
   ``Our government has been notified afterward about contact
between the United States and North Korea,'' Choi said.
   North Korea wants the U.S. to withdraw its troops, stationed in
the South under a mutual defense pact since the 1950-53 Korean War.
</TEXT>
