<DOCNO> AP890519-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NaziScience     05-19 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nazi Science,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists, Victims Argue Use of Holocaust Experiment Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Data from experiments on prisoners in Nazi
concentration camps should be available for use in research if
lives could be saved, a hypothermia researcher says.
   Researchers currently have to dig through archives for the
material.
   ``The value of human life is great, and if we have the means to
save life _ even if the data is suspect _ we should use it,'' Dr.
Robert Pozos said Thursday at an international conference on the
meaning of the Holocaust for bioethics.
   The public must be educated about what went on in the camps as
the data were being gathered ``so they can understand and make
their own decisions,'' Pozos said.
   The suggestion that the data be used drew angry reaction from
three Holocaust survivors who participated in a panel reaction to
Pozos' address.
   ``This is an issue fraught with much emotion,'' said Pozos, vice
president for minority affairs at the University of Washington and
former director of the Hypothermia Research Laboratory at the
University of Minnesota-Duluth.
   ``It is very difficult, even for me, to disassociate what
happened to the people at Dachau, Buchenwald and other
concentration camps with the data that was gathered,'' he said.
   Pozos said his research could benefit from experiments done by
the Nazis. So far he has refrained from using the data and did not
make clear whether he would use it.
   He said 80 to 90 prisoners died in cold-water immersion
experiments conducted at Dachau, where non-consenting prisoners
were placed in brutally cold water to see what would happen to
Luftwaffe pilots if they were shot down.
   Information from the experiments still useful to today's
scientists includes data showing that rapid rewarming with warm
water is effective only for severely hypothermic patients and that
body-to-body rewarming is ineffective.
   Data showing the head and neck are especially vulnerable to cold
have been used in designing hypothermia suits, Pozos said, and
other experiments provided the basis for using lowered body
temperature during cardiac surgery.
   ``The situation is one which I think good might come from
evil,'' Pozos said.
   ``The experiments, the tortures we're talking about are the very
tortures that killed my sister, the tortures that were done to
me,'' said Susan Seiler Vigorito, a teacher of Judaic studies from
Cleveland, Ohio, and a survivor of the experiments conducted on
twins by Dr. Josef Mengele at Auschwitz.
   ``The real issue is the method. The method is as much a part of
the data as the data itself. The data doesn't tell us anything
about the evil of the Holocaust,'' she argued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
