<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan     05-19 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Politician Burns Himself to Death at Dissident's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of Taiwan's main opposition party
burned himself to death today in front of thousands of people
attending a memorial service for a dissident publisher who
committed suicide to avoid arrest.
   Several of the nearly 10,000 people attending the service
outside the president's office said Chan Yih-hua lit bottles of
gasoline strapped to his waist under a black mourning vest and was
engulfed in flames.
   Police fired water cannons as mourners extinguished the flames
with jackets and umbrellas. Chan was taken to a hospital where he
was pronouced dead.
   There were no clashes between the police and mourners.
   More than 3,000 mourners remained outside the building tonight
for a sit-in in rain as thousands of riot police watched behind
shields.
   The mourners, including college students and church members,
urged President Lee Teng-hui to allow freedom of speech for those
advocating an independent Taiwan and for the release all political
prisoners.
   The memorial service, which began Friday, marked the largest
demonstration on this island since Taiwan lifted 38 years of
martial law in 1987.
   An unidentified man standing beside Chan was also burned and was
hospitalized in serious condition, officials said.
   Chan, in his thirties, was a member of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party, which was formed three years ago.
   Party officials said Chan was an admirer of Cheng Nan-jung, 42,
publisher of the Freedom Era weekly, who was accused of publishing
seditious articles in his magazine. Cheng died in a fire April 7
after battling police with firebombs from an apartment to avoid
arrest.
   Cheng's relatives and police said the publisher committed
suicide, and his friends said he had vowed to burn himself to death
to avoid arrest.
   Cheng's coffin was taken on a two-hour funeral procession
through Taipei streets by 2,000 supporters before the memorial
service outside the Presidential Office Building. The crowd later
swelled to nearly 10,000 people.
   Riot police erected barbed-wire barricades outside the
Presidential Office Building to prevent the mourners from getting
too close to the building.
   Police said the procession was illegal because demonstrations
are not permitted in the vicinity of th Presidential Office
Building.
   After Chan's self-immolation, a Protestant priest, Kao
Chun-ming, led the crowd in singing hymns and a Taiwanese folk song
``We Are All (Native) Taiwanese.'' The crowd also shouted slogans
of ``Taiwan Needs Independence.''
   The mourners included Chen Wan-chen, a dissident Taiwan
journalist who has lived in exile in the United States for 10 years
and who has been banned from returning because she has advocated an
independent Taiwan. Dissidents said she slipped back into the
country last week from the Phillipines.
   Opposition legislator Hsu Jong-shu said both Cheng and Chan had
died for press freedom and political liberalization, and she
promised to campaign to achieve their objectives.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war in China, continue to maintain they are the legitimate
government of all China and that Taiwan is a Chinese province.
   Taiwan and China are opposed to an independent Taiwan, and China
indicated it would use force to prevent the establishment of an
independent Taiwan.
</TEXT>
