<FIRST>r a PM-Lukens-MichiganArrest     05-19 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens-Michigan Arrest,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Reports Congressman Arrested For Child Molestation 35 Years Ago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens, facing trial
Monday on charges he had sex with a teen-ager, was arrested for
investigation of child molestation 35 years ago in Michigan but was
never charged, an aide said.
   Lukens denied the accusations in both cases.
   ``It wasn't true 35 years ago, and it's not true now,'' Bill
Jarrell, Lukens' press secretary in Washington, said Thursday.
   Lukens, an Ohio Republican, faces trial in Franklin County
Juvenile Court in Columbus on a misdemeanor charge stemming from an
alleged sexual relationship with a Columbus teen-ager.
   A Michigan televison station on Wednesday revealed the child
molestation investigation of 1954.
   Lukens could not be reached for comment today. A message was
left at his home. Reached Thursday night by The Columbus Dispatch,
he declined to comment, other than to say: ``It was no case.''
   Detroit television station WJBK reported that Lukens was
arrested by police at a boarding house in Royal Oak, Mich., on May
9, 1954, on suspicion of sexually molesting a young girl. Lukens
was a salesman at the time.
   The case was dropped when the child's parents refused to press
charges, the station quoted unidentified police sources as saying.
The age and identity of the girl were not known.
   Donald Brown, a former Oakland County, Mich., prosecutor who
handled the case, told WJBK the child's parents did not want their
daughter to testify at a trial.
   ``The young girl and her parents adamantly refused to sign a
complaint and follow through with the testimony,'' Brown said.
   Lt. Don Novak of the Royal Oak, Mich., police department
confirmed that a person was arrested at a suburban Detroit boarding
house on May 9, 1954, for investigation of child molestation. He
refused to identify the person arrested, citing advice of the city
attorney.
   Lukens, 57 and divorced, was indicted by a Franklin County grand
jury Feb. 23 on a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the
unruliness and delinquency of a child. The charge alleges that
Lukens had sex with a 16-year-old girl in November.
   Lukens has denied the charge and said he was set up by the girl.
He said she was seeking money.
</TEXT>
