<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0553 05-19 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Summons Defense Advisers To Discuss NATO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates and edits to trim, no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush summoned his top
defense advisers to his seaside home today to discuss NATO's
nuclear arsenal as his spokesman indicated arms issues dividing the
alliance remain ``subject to discussion.''
   Bush met with Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, Joint Chiefs of
Staff Chief Adm. William Crowe and other military advisers in
advance of a weekend meeting with French President Francois
Mitterrand, said presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``The SNF (short-range nuclear forces) issue of course is one
that's under cosndiration right now and is driving the meeting,''
Fitzwater told reporters.
   The Bush administration wants to upgrade NATO's nuclear weapons
while West Germany has called for early U.S.-Soviet talks on
reducing the nuclear arsenal in Europe _ talks the United States
has rejected. The flap threatens to disrupt the NATO summit in
Brussels later this month.
   Fitzwater said he did not know if a compromise could be struck
before the NATO meeting.
   At the same time, Fitzwater denied that comments by Mitterrand
the day before in Paris urging a go-slow approach on modernizing
NATO's nuclear forces were in conflict with the U.S. stance.
   ``President Mitterrand's comments yesterday indicate that his
position is very similar to ours. (He) shares our general concern
about the strength of the NATO alliance,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``I'm sure all of that is subject to disscussion,'' he said.
   Fitzwater dismissed news accounts suggesting Mitterrand's party
was unhappy with accomodations in Kennebunkport.
   ``As far as I know, the accomodations are satisfactory to the
French delegation. The discussions of accommodations have gone
quite well. We don't have any problems,'' he said.
   The New York Daily News, in today's editions, quoted
unidentified souces as saying Mitterrand was unhappy with the size
of the bed and the height of the toilet in the house in
Kennebunkport where he and his wife will be staying. The house,
owned by Bush's mother, is next to the president's home. The
article also said that Barbara Bush was upset about the
Mitterrand's visit, claiming it to be disruptive.
   Bush on Thursday told a Rochester audience, ``We're having the
president of the French Republic come to our hourse. So first she
(Mrs. Bush) bawled me out about that ... because the house has been
closed all winter.''
   Fitzwater said today that the Bushes had decided to restrict
press coverage of the Mitterrand visit within the oceanside
compound.
   ``The family feels their home is their private residence and
should not be used for publicity purposes. They want to keep it
pesonal, and I think that's reasonable,'' he said.
   Bush arrived here Thursday, and immediately took his powerboat
for a spin. His motor got hung up on lobster pot lines and he had
to hang overboard to untangle.
   At one point, the president was almost upside down, with Secret
Service agents holding onto his thighs as he worked to unsnarl his
propeller.
   ``Had to lift up the prop to free the line,'' Bush later told
reporters.
   Bush was out for several hours at the wheel of his 28-foot
Cigarette speedboat, crashing through the waves of the open
Atlantic. It was the first time Bush has been out on the boat as
president, and he was accompanied by several Coast Guard vessels
that stood guard.
   Bush and Mitterrand are to meet on Saturday for a session that
aides said would focus on the NATO summit in Brussels later this
month.
   Bush has invited Mitterrand to visit with him for the weekend,
and was to take the French leader with him to Boston on Sunday,
where Bush was to give the commencement address at Boston
University.
   High on the agenda of a planned Saturday work session between
the two presidents will likely be the issue of short-range missiles
in western Europe.
   The French leader has voiced general support for Bush's
opposition to a West German call for early negotiations with the
Soviets for eliminating tactical nuclear weapons in Europe.
   However, while reiterating that it was still too early for such
talks to begin, Mitterrand said in Paris on Thursday that the NATO
allies should allow ``time for reflection'' and give conventional
disarmament talks a chance before deciding to modernize U.S.
short-range missiles in Europe.
   The decision to update Lance missiles stationed in West Germany
_ which the United States has proposed _ will not become urgent
until about 1992, Mitterrand told a news conference.
   He said he hoped the issue of short-range missiles, which has
split NATO, could be dealt with calmly at the Brussels meetings of
the alliance.
   ``If we have to modernize, then let's do it,'' he said. ''But
how do we know it's necessary?''
   Still, the French president said he thought ``the time has not
come, far from it,'' for a ``zero option'' eliminating all
short-range missiles from Europe.
   France, which is a member of NATO but not part of its integrated
military command, has already decided to modernize and extend the
range of its own short-range nuclear missiles.
</TEXT>
