<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Sherpa     05-19 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sherpa,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sherpa Dies on Everest Descent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phu Dorje, a Sherpa who guided a
U.S.-Mexico expedition this week that put the first Mexican atop
Mount Everest, fell to his death during the descent, according to a
report received here Friday.
   Dorje, 26, slipped and fell to his death at the 28,044-foot
level Tuesday, the same day he and another Sherpa, Dawa Norbo, had
reached the 29,028-foot summit along with Ricardo Torres Nava, 34,
of Mexico City, the report from the expedition's base camp said.
   The expedition was led by Walter McConnell, 57, of Wharton,
N.J., had launched their successful summit bid from their assault
camp at 26,950 feet.
   On the descent, they reached the south summit 270 feet below the
main summit, and Dorje told the others that ``he would go ahead''
and asked them to come down ``slower and carefully,'' the report
said. He was killed shortly after that.
   Dorje was on his second conquest of Everest. He had climbed it
last autumn along with a U.S. expedition from the Pacific Northwest.
</TEXT>
