<FIRST>u a PM-Marcos 3rdLd-Writethru a0538 05-19 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0538,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Remains in Very Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Imelda Marcos phone interview,
Aquino saying Marcos can't be buried in Philippines, source saying Marcos
responding to treatment, moves up that he has been hospitalized 4 months,
other details. Picks up 11th graf, `Marcos was...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor NY23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
was in very critical condition today following kidney, cardiac and
pulmonary failure, hospital officials said.
   His successor, Corazon Aquino, said she would not permit Marcos
to return to the Philippines to die despite an appeal from Marcos'
wife, Imelda. She said today that the government also wouldn't
allow him to be buried in his homeland.
   Marcos, 71, who has been hospitalized for more than four months,
suffered kidney failure Thursday morning and underwent surgery to
prepare him for kidney dialysis, said Gene Tiwanak, assistant
administrator at St. Francis Medical Center.
   The former president also suffered cardiac and pulmonary failure
and had pneumonia and other severe infections, said Dr. Azucena
Ignacio, an internist at St. Francis and one of Marcos' personal
physicians.
   Marcos' fever rose this morning, Mrs. Marcos told reporters as
she left the hospital to go home and make telephone calls. She
planned to return later.
   The former president appeared to be responding to treatment but
was still in very critical condition, a hospital source told The
Associated Press.
   ``The doctors fear for his life, that he could go anytime,''
Mrs. Marcos said in a telephone interview from her home. She said
she had been trying repeatedly to get through to Malacanang Palace
to appeal to Mrs. Aquino personally to let her husband ``go home to
his fatherland as his dying wish.''
   She said if the United States granted them permission to return
to the Philippines, it ``would show a humanitarian and a kinder and
gentler America.'' The Marcoses cannot leave the island of Oahu
without U.S. permission.
   When told by reporters earlier that Mrs. Aquino had announced
her decision to bar Marcos from returning, Mrs. Marcos said, ``We
are aware, but I am a believer and I am an optimist. I know
miracles can happen.''
   Marcos was lapsing in and out of consciousness after the
operation, said a hospital source who asked not to be identified.
   Marcos was being treated with antibiotics and heart medication,
Ignacio said. ``Some medications are working, some are not,'' he
said.
   Mrs. Marcos and their son, Ferdinand Jr., spent part of Thursday
praying in the hospital chapel, and about 70 supporters attended a
prayer service for Marcos in the evening.
   Marcos' sister, Fortuna Barba, was also at the hospital, and the
couple's daughter, Irene Araneta, was coming to Honolulu from her
home in Woodside, Calif., said Joe Lazo, president of Friends of
Marcos.
   The Marcoses have lived in exile in Hawaii since they were
toppled in a February 1986 popular uprising that ended two decades
of rule and brought Mrs. Aquino to power. Mrs. Aquino has
repeatedly cited national security in rejecting previous requests
from Marcos to return to his homeland.
   Mrs. Aquino said today in Manila that she was sorry to hear that
Marcos' condition had deteriorated ``and I pray that he will be
able to recover.''
   ``I regret to inform Mrs. Marcos, if indeed she is asking me for
reconsideration, because as I have said in the past, much as I
agree that Mr. Marcos has his rights, I still have to consider also
the rights and interests of millions of Filipinos,'' Mrs. Aquino
said.
   ``I have already said in the past that we will not allow his
remains to be brought back here,'' she added.
   Mrs. Aquino's national security adviser, Rafael Ileto, had said
earlier that Cabinet officials would meet next week to discuss,
among other things, whether to allow Marcos to be buried on
Philippine soil.
   Share prices fell today on the Manila Stock Excange following
rumors that Marcos had died, traders said.
   Marcos entered the hospital Jan. 15 with heart, kidney and
respiratory ailments. He lapsed into critical condition Tuesday,
one day after he was moved into the intensive care unit.
   It was the third time Marcos has been hospitalized since early
December, when he was admitted for pneumonia, bronchial asthma and
congestive heart failure.
   The Marcoses are facing federal racketeering charges for
allegedly looting more than $100 million from the Philippines to
buy art and real estate in New York. Marcos has been separated from
the case because of his ill health. Mrs. Marcos is free on $5
million bail.
</TEXT>
