<FIRST>r a PM-TelevisedManhunt     05-19 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Televised Manhunt,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Show Leads to Arrest of Fugitive In Medicaid Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tips generated from a network anti-crime program
led to the arrest of a fugitive convicted of stealing more than $16
million in the largest theft of Medicaid funds since the program
began 22 years ago.
   Sheldon Weinberg, 64, was arrested Wednesday night in
Scottsdale, Ariz., just hours after he was featured on NBC-TV's
``Unsolved Mysteries.''
   An anonymous caller, one of hundreds of viewers who phoned in
tips, gave the FBI Weinberg's alias and address at a
garden-apartment complex.
   Weinberg and his two sons, who had operated a Brooklyn health
clinic, were convicted Nov. 30, 1988, of stealing more than $16
million from Medicaid between 1980-87.
   ``It is fitting indeed that ordinary citizens, whose millions of
stolen tax dollars directly financed Sheldon Weinberg's obscenely
lavish lifestyle ... should be the instrument of his ultimate
downfall,'' said Deputy Attorney General Edward J. Kuriansky.
   Kuriansky said Weinberg had used the money he defrauded from
Medicaid to finance an $18,000-a-month apartment in Manhattan's
Trump Tower, a $5 million lakefront mansion in Boca Raton, Fla.,
yachts and a fleet of custom cars.
   ``This reverse Robin Hood has finally gotten his just
desserts,'' he said.
   At the trial in state Supreme Court, prosecutors charged that
Weinberg and his sons falsely billed Medicaid by submitting phony
reimbursement claims for about 400,000 phony patients.
   Weinberg failed to appear at his Jan. 10 sentencing this year
and has been the target of a nationwide search since then.
   Following extradition proceedings in Arizona, Weinberg will be
returned to New York to begin serving a seven-to-21-year prison
term that was imposed in absentia.
</TEXT>
