<HEAD>Italian Premier Submits His Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with resignation submitted. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita resigned today after
repeated sniping by the Socialists, his main partner in the
13-month-old coalition government.
   De Mita turned in his resignation as head of Italy's 48th
postwar government to President Francesco Cossiga.
   The president asked De Mita to stay on in a caretaker capacity.
The political negotiations aimed at forming a new coalition could
take weeks.
   De Mita, a Christian Democrat, announced his resignation after
an urgent Cabinet meeting requested by his main political foe,
Bettino Craxi, a former premier who leads the Socialists. Craxi
called the Cabinet meeting to discuss what he called a ``political
and government crisis.''
   Earlier today, in a closing speech at the Socialist convention
in Milan, Craxi said a ``political and procedural clarification''
about the five-party coalition government was needed immediately.
   The Socialists and Christian Democrats have been squabbling for
weeks over a variety of issues, with Craxi and fellow party members
accusing De Mita of failing to take a leadership role. The
government, which took office in April 1988, also includes the
small Republican, Social Democrat and Liberal Parties.
   Craxi and his aides have made no secret that the Socialist
leader would like o regain the premiership.
   The Socialists are Italy's third largest party but have great
weight in forming a government. That is because no party has a
majority and the Christian Democrats, who have dominated all
governments since the end of World War II, refuse to bring the
Communists, Italy's second largest party, into the Cabinet.
</TEXT>
