<FIRST>r w AM-Lucas     05-19 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate for Civil Rights Post Already Working at Justice Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas is working for the Justice
Department as a $284-a-day consultant while awaiting Senate
confirmation as assistant attorney general for civil rights, the
department said Friday.
   Lucas, whose nomination is opposed by some civil rights groups
who question his professional qualifications, is studying the
Justice Department's role in training law enforcement officials to
be sensitive about civil-rights issues and report potential
violations, said David Runkel, chief Justice Department spokesman.
   The $284 per-day consulting agreement, which took effect March
20, is a common arrangement for Bush administration officials
awaiting Senate action on their nominations, Runkel said.
   Lucas, who garnered more than half his 1988 earnings as a
consultant for the Republican National Committee, continued to work
for the GOP until February, Runkel said.
   The Justice Department consulting contract was negotiated with
Lucas after he stopped working for the Republican Party, Runkel
said. Lucas generally works five days a week as a consultant but is
not paid for the days he spends paying calls on senators who will
vote on his nomination, Runkel said.
   The $284 daily rate is equivalent to an annual salary of $73,840.
   Runkel dismissed suggestions that Lucas was given the contract
simply to tide him over during the Senate conformation proceedings.
   Besides benefiting the department, Runkel said, the study will
help Lucas get ``more deeply involved in what's going on in the
civil rights division,'' Runkel said.
   ``There is a need to do it or it wouldn't be done,'' Runkel said
of the study.
   Lucas will submit a report to the Justice Department following
his review of: training and manpower resources of federal law
enforcement agencies on civil rights, the role the department plays
in training local law enforcement officials.
   The study will also focus on how the Justice Department can
improve the reporting of civil rights violations by state and local
police and obtaining local cooperation in investigating such
complaints, according to the contract he signed with the department.
   No date has been set for Lucas' confirmation hearing by the
Senate Judiciary Committee. The panel's chairman, Sen. Joseph R.
Biden Jr., D-Del., said Thursday he wanted to determine the scope
of the committee staff's investigation before setting a date.
   The major issue being raised by civil rights groups opposing
Lucas is his lack of legal experience, particularly on civil rights.
   On his Senate questionnaire, Lucas said he has never tried a
legal case in court since he entered private legal practice in
Detroit two years ago.
   Before that, Lucas, a former FBI agent and New York City police
officer, served as sheriff and chief executive of Wayne County,
Mich.
   A black Republican who ran unsuccessfully for Michigan governor
in 1986, Lucas had been a lifelong Democrat before joining the GOP
in 1985.
   His financial disclosure form showed that last year Lucas earned
$65,000 as a GOP consultant studying ways to recruit blacks into
the Republican Party. He earned $53,000 as a lawyer last year and
was paid $7,500 as a corporate director.
</TEXT>
