<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Reagan     05-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Reagan,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan's Admirers in Japan Will See Him Again in October</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GROSS</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of Ronald Reagan's greatest admirers are in
Japan, and the former president will visit them in October for a
week of speeches and other events.
   Two of Reagan's friends, however, appear to be sidelined by the
Recruit influence-peddling scandal, which has touched the top ranks
of Japanese politics.
   Reagan and former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone called each
other Yasu and Ron, but Nakasone's office said he had no plans to
see his friend during the visit. His successor Noboru Takeshita,
who also was on a first-name basis with Reagan, has said he will
resign because of the scandal.
   Takeshita and Nakasone are under fire for benefiting from
cut-price unlisted shares in a subsidiary of Recruit Co. that
soared in value when offered on the market. Executives of the
company face trial on charges of bribing other government officials.
   There have been reports of a bidding war to sponsor events
during the Reagan visit.
   New York Times columnist William Safire said he was told the
former president's fee for the week would be about $2 million. He
did not give the source of the information.
   Japanese companies involved have denied the report and Reagan's
office in California declined comment. Mark Weinberg, a Reagan
spokesman, said the fees ``were a private matter.''
   Charles Z. Wick, former director of the U.S. Information Agency
director, helped arrange the visit.
   ``I feel quite certain, as do many other people in Japan and the
United States, that President Reagan's visit ... will serve a
number of constructive purposes for both countries,'' he said.
   While Reagan was in office, Nakasone and Takeshita invited him
to visit Japan. Takeshita made a side trip to California last
winter, after visiting Washington, to renew the invitation and
thank Reagan for the generally good U.S.-Japanese relations during
his eight-year tenure.
   An official Japanese government invitation was sent after Reagan
indicated he could make the trip in October. A Foreign Ministry
official said some details of the visit had yet to be arranged.
   Hideo Sato, professor of international relations at Tsukuba
University, said the Japanese feel some nostalgia for Reagan now
that President Bush has taken over.
   ``During Reagan's administration, there was a feeling that
things were going well, that he supported a free economy, but with
Bush things have changed dramatically,'' he said.
   ``The U.S. goverment's trade council has come to endorse managed
trade and the negotiators have become much more result-oriented. .
.. Now people feel that U.S.-Japan relations may be breaking down.''
   Fujisankei Communications Group, a media conglomerate with
newspaper and television interests, will be the main sponsor of
``Reagan Week,'' which is to begin about Oct. 19. Spokesman Makoto
Matsui said the group plans several speeches and events, but that
details were not yet available.
   When asked about the fee, he said it was ``a private matter''
but the figure of $2 million was not accurate.
   Shuwa Corp., also said to have been a bidder, denied Safire's
comment that it ``reportedly offered $5 million.'' Shuwa has
extensive real estate interests in the United States.
</TEXT>
