<FIRST>u i PM-NorthernIreland 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 05-19 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northern Irish Voters Move From Extremes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more election results. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters edged away from Northern
Ireland's militant extremes and boosted moderates today on both
sides of the communal divide, according to nearly complete returns
from local elections.
   With all but 20 of the 566 council seats counted nationwide, the
gap between moderate and radical parties widened, with moderates
ahead 2-to-1 in both the Protestant and Roman Catholic camps.
   On the Catholic side, the larger Social Democratic Labor Party
was showing the best election performance in its 20-year history,
winning 120 seats compared to 101 in the last election in 1985. It
had gained 3 percent to hold 20.8 percent of the total vote.
   Sinn Fein, the political backer of the militant Irish Republican
Army won 11 percent of the total vote, down slightly from the 11.7
percent it had in the last election. The party was weaker in rural
areas and was expected to lose 15 of its 59 council seats.
   But in west Belfast, Sinn Fein's traditional stronghold, the
party was 3.1 percent stronger and rose to an 18.7 percent share.
Though the Social Democrats increased their Belfast vote by 1.8
percent, Sinn Fein remained the capital's largest party and the
council stayed protestant controlled.
   The shift toward moderates appeared more pronounced on the
Protestant side, where Rev. Ian Paisley's hard-line Democratic
Unionist Party slumped by 6.3 percent and shed about 30 seats to
105.
   The larger, more moderate Official Unionists gained 2.1 percent
and was expected to finish with about 190 seats.
   Local elections matter little since the British government runs
most of the province's affairs. But they are watched closely for
pointers to the relative strengths of moderates and hardliners, and
any gain for Sinn Fein would sound alarm bells in London and Dublin.
   ``It does look as though there has been some move away from the
extremes,'' said Tom King, the Cabinet minister who runs Northern
Ireland.
   But Sinn Fein's Alex Maskey, re-elected in Belfast, said the
vote in the capital endorsed his party's campaign to rid Northern
Ireland of British rule. But the 51-seat Belfast council remained
firmly in Protestant control.
   Among the more spectacular results were the Social Democratic
and Labor Party's 7.8-percent gain in Londonderry, another IRA
redoubt, and Sinn Fein's 4.7-percent slide in Enniskillen, scene of
a November 1987 IRA bombing that killed 11 Protestants and still
arouses abhorrent memories.
   In Paisley's home town of Ballymena, his party lost 11 percent
and three seats.
   Paisley said his voters were apathetic because they believe the
British government is interested only in the balance of power
concerning the IRA.
   The Protestant parties are deeply embittered by a 1985
Anglo-Irish Agreement giving the Irish government a say in Northern
Ireland's affairs. They see Ireland as a hostile,
Catholic-dominated state intent on dissolving their union with
Britain.
   Strong personalities proved able to override doctrinal divides.
   In Larne, popular Catholic priest Pat Buckley promised to serve
all sectors of the community and won handsomely on a largely
Protestant vote.
   In Magherafelt, social worker Mary McSorley romped home as an
independent. She had been kicked out of the Social Democratic and
Labor Party for affronting Irish nationalists by accepting a medal
from Queen Elizabeth II.
   Other mold-breakers were five self-styled Conservatives who
pledged to attract mainland British parties into the province. They
argue this would strip Ulster politics of their sectarian character
and move them onto conventional left-right lines.
   Overall, a pattern emerged of an electorate either indifferent _
turnout was down 4 percent _ or wanting moderate Protestants and
Catholics to work together.
</TEXT>
