<DOCNO> AP890519-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BusRevenge     05-19 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Revenge,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Driver Puts Bus Through Garage Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspended driver drove a bus
through three plate glass windows at a garage station, and fled by
catching another bus, officials say.
   The driver, Rene Rose, 27, had been suspended Wednesday, said
Thomas Sturgess, director of communications for the Bi-State
Development Agency, a transit and economic development agency in
the St. Louis metropolitan area, including parts of Illinois.
   Ms. Rose stopped a bus shortly after midnight on Thursday and
forced the driver to take it to the garage where the buses are
stationed, he said.
   ``She then got in the driver's seat and drove through the plate
glass windows,'' Sturgess said. No one was hurt.
   The bus drove through two saplings spaced about 8 feet apart,
crashed through the windows and became wedged in the garage's
lounge and snack bar, the Belleville News-Democrat reported.
   ``She was in the building for a while, but ran out and caught
another bus to another location'' where police captured her,
Sturgess said.
   She was being held on charges of resisting arrest and traffic
violations, said Officer Willie Haire of the East St. Louis Police.
   Sturgess estimated that the building sustained less than $20,000
damage. He declined to say whether the company would try to recover
the cost of the repairs from Ms. Rose.
   ``There's a possibility she will be fired,'' he said.
</TEXT>
