<FIRST>r a PM-NarcoticsInspection     05-19 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Narcotics Inspection,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fake Narcotics Signs Come Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff has decided to take down
fake signs warning of a narcotics inspection on Interstate 95 after
widespread publicity made it less likely drug couriers would be
fooled into making telltale U-turns.
   State Transportation Secretary Kaye Henderson said last week
that Sheriff Bob Vogel and Volusia County would be liable for any
accident caused by the signs.
   Melvin Stack, a legal adviser to the sheriff, said Wednesday
that Henderson's warning was not the reason Vogel had the signs
taken down. They were removed temporarily because they weren't
serving their purpose anymore after national news reports disclosed
they were fake, Stack said.
   ``In all probability, this will be put on the back burner for a
while until the drug dealers forget about it,'' Stack said.
   ``The Department of Transportation has been giving Sheriff Vogel
a hard time about placement of signs on I-95,'' he said. ``I say
they should get their own house in order and take care of the roads
around here. Stay out of the law enforcement area. That's what we
elected the sheriff for.''
</TEXT>
