<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     05-19 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Imposes Virtual Censorship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military has imposed virtual
censorship on all news about army activity, and threatened to take
legal action against non-abiding publications.
   A statement issued by the army and published in Thursday's
edition of the military magazine Al-Guwat Al-Musalaha said that
revealing activities of the armed forces or publishing information
about the southern rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army would ``be
firmly met with.''
   It charged some newspapers with not obtaining prior official
verification for army information, and of quoting SPLA radio
broadcasts. The statement did not identify the newspapers involved,
but said they were used by the rebels to ``demoralize the armed
forces and the citizens in general.''
   The ban came as the SPLA has been winning victories in its
six-year civil war against the government in Khartoum.
   The military had issued a similar statement in a milder form in
January, but enforced it in only one case. Mohammed Medani Tawfik,
editor-in-chief of Al-Rai was detained for one month in February
for publishing a report on the fall of the southern town of Nasir
to the SPLA forces. The government later confirmed the rebel
takeover of Nasir.
   The SPLA, which took up arms against the government in demand of
economic and social reforms for the south, controls most of the
southern countryside.
  
