<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elvis has been sighted again _ this time
as a candidate for the Onondaga County Legislature.
   Elvis Presley imitator E. Wendell Conley, 30, of Syracuse on
Thursday won the Onondaga County Democratic Committee's blessing to
campaign for the local government seat in the November election.
It's Conley's first try for elective office.
   He's been impersonating the King for the last four years and has
been delivering ``Elvisgrams'' for a year.
   He gets people all shook up at parties, in offices and anywhere
else people will pay him to help them remember the rock 'n' roll
legend.
   ``I've always been a big fan of Elvis,'' said Conley, who
admitted to taking some ribbing from committee members about his
job.
   In addition to Elvis impersonations, Conley is also a
professional musician and clown and runs a business that offers
balloons for all occasions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Murial cq in 6th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STARKEY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this rural hamlet are thinking
about putting in the modern convenience of telephones, but when
they got together to talk about it they had to meet in the old-time
glow of kerosene lanterns.
   A passing storm Wednesday knocked out electrical power _ itself
an innovation that arrived in Starkey just 17 years ago.
   The blackout didn't stop Bob Hald of Telephone Utilities of
Eastern Oregon Inc. from preaching the virtues of the company's
plan to bring phone signals in by microwave to the Starkey Trading
Post and from there to the community's 60 homes by buried cable.
   The community, last in Union County without phones, would have
service as complete as that in any big city, financed by government
money, Hald said: ``Whatever they have in Los Angeles, you can have
here.''
   Wes Delve called it ``a darn good deal,'' but not everyone at
the meeting was thrilled with the idea.
   Murial Wherley, 56, said she had a phone when she lived in
nearby La Grande and doesn't miss it.
   ``We love it without a phone,'' she said. ``If we wanted a
phone, we would have stayed in town.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grandma may have known best after all. After
three years of research, microbiology professor Byron Murray thinks
she knew what she was talking about when she said garlic helps to
fight the common cold.
   Garlic may not be an all-purpose cure, but it kills cold-causing
viruses, at least in a laboratory dish, Murray, a microbiology
professor at Brigham Young University, has found.
   The active chemical in garlic also wipes out viruses that cause
herpes and upper respiratory infections, as well as some bacteria
and fungi, he said.
   The garlic component that thwarts these organisms is allicin, he
said Thursday at the American Society for Microbiology's annual
meeting here.
   Murray isn't sure yet of its structure or how it works, but he
said he has seen it immobilize 90 percent of a virus in a
laboratory dish within 30 minutes.
   The professor doesn't hold with the old recommendation of
wearing garlic in a bag around the neck. He suggests people take
garlic in pill form.
   ``There's a long and historic tale of garlic, going back to
medieval times,'' Murray said. ``There's a good scientific basis.
There are a number of companies that make garlic pills, but we're
doing more definitive anti-viral work with allicin and other garlic
compounds.''

</TEXT>
