<FIRST>u a PM-NerveGas 1stLd-Writethru a0582 05-19 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nerve Gas, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0582,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Korean-born Businessman Guilty Of Conspiracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Assistant U.S. ...' with 2 grafs with prosecutor's
comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-born businessman accused of trying
to export nerve gas bombs to Iran was found guilty of conspiracy
today, but was acquitted of trying to export the gas.
   Juwhan Yun did not react when the verdict was announced. His
wife prayed silently to herself, as she had throughout the trial.
   Yun faces up to five years in prison for the conviction. The
other charge would have added an additional 10 years. Yun's
attorney, Stephen Dratch, said that under new sentencing
guidelines, Yun probably would face about 2{ years.
   Sentencing is set for July 13.
   Dratch said he would ask U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin to
set the guilty verdict aside.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. praised the verdict and
rejected the defense's argument of entrapment, saying that an
undercover operation is virtually the only way to enforce weapons
export laws.
   ``(Yun) was looking for a source of arms,'' Alito said.
   Yun was arrested Jan. 12 at U.S. Customs offices near Newark
International Airport at what he thought was to be a meeting with
an undercover agent posing as an arms dealer. He had called off the
deal for the nerve gas the night before his arrest.
   Yun was convicted of conspiring to export arms without a
license. The verdict came on the third day of deliberations.
   Dratch had argued during the nearly three-week trial that Yun
was entrapped by a slick undercover agent. He maintained that the
agent used economic coercion to entrap Yun.
   Olinsky told jurors that Yun was motivated by greed and chose on
his own to negotiate for the nerve gas sarin.
   Under Sarokin's instructions, the jury had to find that the
government proved decisively that Yun was not entrapped in order to
convict.
