<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FamilyPrincipals Bjt   05-19 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Principals, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dual Principal Family Takes Home Double Honors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grassa O'Neill is cq as second reference, per her preference.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are both principals of tough urban middle
schools. They both won national education awards this year. They
also happen to be married.
   ``There's a wicked rivalry,'' said Thomas P. O'Neill, a 1989
Reader's Digest American Hero in Education. ``That makes us better
principals because we have twice as many ideas.''
   His wife and fellow principal, Mary Grassa O'Neill, claimed a
top honor from the U.S. Department of Education.
   ``I think it carries over to the staff,'' Grassa O'Neill said.
   ``Initially, we didn't think about it at all,'' she said. But
then the Timilty School, headed by Grassa O'Neill, and her
husband's Solomon Lewenberg Middle School began vying for the same
first-place finishes in test scores and the same grant money and
students.
   When Boston school test scores were released recently, Timilty
School staff members were chagrined to place second in reading to
Lewenberg. But they took comfort in the fact that their average in
all subjects put them ahead of Lewenberg, Grassa O'Neill said.
   ``I always tell the staff that Timilty is the best school
compared to all the others,'' O'Neill joked.
   Students seem to enjoy the principal connection.
   Thursday, as the O'Neills toured a Timilty classroom, a student
in the front of the class whispered, ``Is that your husband?'' When
Grassa O'Neill nodded ``Yes,'' heads all over the classroom whipped
in O'Neill's direction.
   Both O'Neills command schools in high-crime areas and have to
cope with the daily realities of inner-city school life. A security
officer monitors visitors at Timilty, a precaution Grassa O'Neill
said is taken at most inner-city schools.
   The O'Neills national awards didn't involve direct, head-to-head
competition.
   Grassa O'Neill's school was one of 218 singled out for
excellence by the U.S. Department of Education. Schools were
nominated by the state and then subjected to intensive, on-site
visits. The award reflected the performance of the entire school,
right down to the custodians, Grassa O'Neill said.
   O'Neill and his school were nominated for their efforts in
turning Lewenberg around. Once on the brink of closure, it not only
has the highest reading scores of all 22 Boston middle schools but
has seen its retention rate soar from the third lowest to the third
highest.
   Reader's Digest gave O'Neill $5,000 and the school $10,000.
Grassa O'Neill didn't get any money, but she will be honored this
fall at a ceremony in the White House Rose Garden.
   Both found out about their awards in April and were
``terrifically excited,'' they said. But Grassa O'Neill's
excitement was tinged with sadness because she found out at the
same time that five of her teachers were being laid off as part of
a citywide budget crunch.
   The couple met in 1969 as English teachers at a middle school.
They married in 1975 and have 4-year-old twins.
   ``Two of everything,'' O'Neill laughed.
   In 1984, Thomas was appointed principal of Solomon Lewenberg.
One year later, Grassa O'Neill got the top post at Timilty.
   The O'Neills said they don't have their eyes on the
superintendent's office just yet, because they're fully occupied
with their present posts.
   ``I think the biggest challenge is trying to keep everybody
motivated all the time. Sometimes that's tough,'' Grassa O'Neill
said.
   ``That as well as the sort of awesome responsbility that running
a school can be on some days,'' O'Neill said.
</TEXT>
