<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GeographyBee     05-19 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geography Bee,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Teen-Ager Wins National Geography Bee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who attends a six-student church
school in Great Bend, Kan., walked away Friday with the
championship of the first National Geography Bee and a $25,000
college scholarship.
   Jack Staddon, 6-foot-6 and 15 years old, correctly named a flat
intermountain area in the central Andes to defeat Michael Shannon,
14, of Reading, Mass. The answer was altiplano.
   Shannon, finishing second, will receive a $15,000 scholarship,
while Kieu Luu, the third-place winner from Landover, Md., won a
$10,000 scholarship. The money will be put into interest-bearing
accounts until the winners go to college.
   Some 15,000 to 20,000 schools in 55 states and territories
participated in preliminary rounds of the bee, sponsored by the
National Geographic Society and open to students in grades 4-8. The
55 state and territorial winners, aged 10 to 15, were in Washington
this week for semifinals and the 10 top winners competed Friday.
   Moderator Alex Trebek, host of the long-running TV trivia quiz
show, ``Jeopardy,'' used maps and slides in questioning contestants
on everything from Zanzibar's most profitable 19th century trading
commodity (cloves) to the two points connected by the Alaskan
pipeline (Valdez and Prudhoe Bay).
   Staddon said he studied geography trivia cards and read through
a college geography book in preparation for the contest.
   Nevertheless, with competitors allowed to miss only two
questions before being eliminated, he blew his first question in
both the final and semifinal rounds.
   On Thursday, shown a slide of the Grand Canyon, Staddon missed
its location by a state or two. ``I said Utah,'' he recalled with a
rueful grin. It is actually in Arizona.
   And on Friday, asked by Trebek to identify an unusual
modernistic building, he replied after a long pause, ``New York. I
don't know.'' The correct answer was the Sydney Opera House.
   ``I had no idea what that was,'' Staddon said, laughing, after
winning the bee. ``I remember reading about that in my book but I
had no idea what it looked like. If I had to do this again I would
concentrate more on the pictures rather than on maps.''
   Staddon said there are two third-graders, two seventh-graders, a
first-grader and an eighth-grader (himself) at the Great Bend
Seventh Day Adventist Elementary School he attends. He said he
wants to follow in the footsteps of his father and become a church
pastor.
   The National Geography Bee, set to become an annual event, is
part of a campaign by the National Geographic Society to improve
geography education. The group also sponsors teacher workshops and
various other programs for students.
   The initiative was launched after an international Gallup Poll
comissioned by the society in 1988 showed that Americans ranked
among the bottom third in geographic knowledge. Those aged 18-24
came in last.
   The geography bee was modeled on a New Jersey bee where Sen.
Bill Bradley, D-N.J., was the host. ``I never thought I'd
appreciate a theft but I certainly appreciate this one,'' Bradley
said before the finals began.
   ``I hope we're beginning a tradition here,'' said Trebek. ``I
hope I'll be asked to do this again for many, many years to come.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Zhao     05-19 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Zhao,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zhao Stands Up to Deng, His Mentor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zhao Ziyang, in his first known rebellion against
his mentor, senior leader Deng Xiaoping, has chosen to resign as
head of the world's largest Communist Party rather than endorse a
crackdown on students demonstrating for democracy, sources said.
   As of Friday night, Zhao's resignation offer had yet to be
decided on by his colleagues in the party, the Chinese sources said.
   However, his failure to appear with Premier Li Peng and other
top party and government leaders when it was announced the military
would move in to end the student unrest appeared to make Zhao's
break with the leadership irrevocable.
   His rebellion contrasts with the fate of his predecessor, Hu
Yaobang, who was forced to step down in January 1987 after failing
to crack down on earlier nationwide student protests. It was Hu's
death April 15 that triggered the new student movement.
   Zhao, 69, tried repeatedly in recent weeks to defuse mounting
tensions between authorities suspicious of any unofficial political
activity and students demanding a free press, an end to official
corruption and other reforms.
   He reportedly sent representatives to campus to talk to students
after their marches drew hundreds of thousands of cheering
residents into the streets.
   Zhao was the first top-level official to endorse student calls
for dialogue after the party mouthpiece, the People's Daily,
condemned the student movement as a ``planned conspiracy'' aimed at
overthrowing the government.
   He spoke April 27 as 150,000 students and supporters marched
triumphantly through Beijing streets to Tiananmen Square in the
first display of the widespread public support for their movement.
   Deng reportedly issued orders to stop that march, but the crowds
of citizens who swarmed to screen the students from police and
soldiers made it impossible without bloodshed.
   Zhao used the student movement to trot out of the closet
proposals for political reform that had been largely shelved since
last summer. Worsening economic problems, including inflation
running at an annual rate of near 30 percent, had weakened his hand
and strengthened the position of officials such as Premier Li who
favored moving more slowly on both economic and political reforms.
   After students began their hunger strike in the square a week
ago, only Zhao impressed the fasters as sincere in his pleas for
them to stop and his promises that authorities were trying to
implement reforms.
   However, the students said he spoke only as an individual and
not for the government.
   Zhao was born in October 1919 to a landowning family in central
China's Henan province. He joined the Communist Party in 1938, and
headed the party committee in his native county for most of the
1937-45 China-Japan war.
   Unlike the previous generation of party leaders, he did not take
part in the 1934-35 Long March, the 7,700-mile trek from
Nationalist government troops in eastern China to the northwest.
   After the communist victory in 1949, Zhao spent most of his
career in regional government and party posts. He was purged during
the 1966-76 far leftist Cultural Revolution, as was Deng, but was
rehabilitated in the 1970s.
   He gained national prominence as party secretary and governor of
Deng's home province, Sichuan, where he implemented Deng's policies
of dismantling communes and allowing private plots and bonuses for
extra work.
   Deng brought Zhao to Beijing as vice premier in 1980. He became
premier six months later, replacing Hua Guofeng. He was made acting
party secretary in January 1987 after fellow reformer Hu Yaobang
was forced to resign.
   Zhao was confirmed in the post at an October 1987 party
conference in which his keynote speech emphasized increasing
production over ideological issues. He also announced Deng's theory
that China was in a ``primary stage'' of socialism, during which
time private ownership of businesses was permissible.
   At the same congress, a new party Politburo Standing Committee
was constituted, made up of Zhao, Premier Li Peng, Yao Yilin, Qiao
Shi and Hu Qili.
   By putting Li and Yao _ relative conservatives _ on the Standing
Committee with liberal-leaning Zhao and Hu Qili, Deng may have been
trying to prevent either faction from becoming powerful enough to
discard him. Qiao, a pragmatist, was the swing vote.
   The set-up made Deng an essential arbiter between the two
factions _ a role he apparently relished.
   In the end, Zhao's failure to win over the conservatives in the
Standing Committee, and Deng's adamant refusal to compromise with
the students, may have forced Zhao to step down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
