<HEAD>Dissident in Poor Health Released from Detention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak human rights activist
arrested in a pro-democracy demonstration at Prague's May Day
parade was released from jail Friday, apparently in poor health due
to a hunger strike, an emigre source said.
   Stanislav Devaty was released following a decision by the
regional court in Brno. He was to stay in the intensive care unit
of a Prague hospital until Monday when he will be transferred to a
hospital in Gottwaldov, where he lives.
   The London-based Palach Press news publishing organization said
several criminal proceedings against Devaty were combined and will
be handled by authorities in Brno.
   The charges against Devaty, 37, were not dropped, and he will
stand trial when he recovers, according to Palach Press, quoting
dissident sources in Prague.
   Before his release was known, The Committee for the Defense of
Stanislav Devaty reportedly wrote a letter to Premier Ladislav
Adamec asking him to release the activist or be held responsible
for his death.
   An urgent appeal also was sent to the premier by the preparatory
committee of the Club for Socialist Reconstruction, Obroda.
   Devaty was charged with violating public order and could face up
to five years in jail if convicted.
   He and fellow protesters were among at least 76 people detained
on May Day when at least 600 people demonstrated on Prague's
Wenceslas Square for more democracy and the release of political
prisoners.
   Another activist, Stanislav Pitas, was sentenced to 10 months in
prison on a charge of assaulting a policeman. Palach Press said the
charge was fabricated, but did not give other details.
