<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NerveGas     05-19 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nerve Gas,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Businessman Guilty Of Conspiracy in Nerve Gas Dealings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean-American businessman was convicted
Friday of conspiring to export deadly nerve gas bombs to Iran.
   The jury, however, acquitted Juwhan Yun, 48, of Short Hills of
attempting to send the gas _ 500 quarter-ton boms of the nerve gas
overseas. No such gas was in Yun's possession, but he discussed the
deal with an undercover agent.
   Yun did not react when the verdict was announced early on the
third day of deliberations. His wife prayed silently and later
sobbed outside the courtroom.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin set sentencing for July 13.
Yun could receive up to five years in prison.
   ``The last chapter hasn't been written,'' said Yun's attorney,
Stephen Dratch. ``It appears the verdict very well may have been
inconsistent'' because the government's evidence was directed at
both charges, he said.
   Dratch said he would ask Sarokin to set the guilty verdict aside.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. said he was pleased by the
verdict and that Justice, military and FBI officials were
considering further charges.
   In pretrial hearings, prosecutors said classified documents were
found at the Summit office of Yun's import-export business, and
that Yun maintained contacts at U.S. military bases and with
officials in the Chinese, Yugoslav and South Korean militaries.
Alito declined to give further details.
   Dratch countered that he and his client ``don't know what
they're talking about.'' He said he has yet to see the allegedly
classified documents.
   During the nearly three-week trial, Dratch argued that Yun was
entrapped by an undercover agent from the Customs Service posing as
an arms dealer. He maintained that the agent used economic coercion
to entrap Yun.
   Alito said entrapment was the usual defense argument when people
are caught in such stings. ``Without doing these undercover
operations, it's virtually impossible to enforce the arms export
laws,'' he said.
   Sarokin had instructed jurors that in order to convict they had
to find that the government proved decisively that Yun was not
entrapped.
   The prosecution and defense agreed that Yun contacted the
undercover agent while looking for legal ammunition, discussed
buying a type of nerve gas called sarin for Iran and called off the
deal Jan. 11.
   That was the day before he was arrested at customs offices near
Newark International Airport at what he thought was to be a meeting
with customs official Richard Kennan.
   The prosecution, however, argued to jurors that Yun only
temporarily called off the deal and intended to renew it.
   Yun said he had no intention of shipping anything illegal and
only discussed the illegal deals to secure the 105mm and 106mm
ammunition.
</TEXT>
