<DOCNO> AP890519-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1513EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Fuel     05-19 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Fuel,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>No PCB-Tainted Fuel Found in Random Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No evidence of fuel contaminated by PCBs has been
found in a week of spot checks of oil tanker trucks entering Canada
from the United States, officials said, but they'll expand tests to
include other toxic waste.
   Canada's Environment Department ordered the random testing May
12, alerted by reports in the Globe and Mail newspaper that
solvents, waste oil and the polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs,
have been mixed into fuels illegally and sold in western New York
and Canada. It said the practice had been going on for four years.
   Jack Trip, chairman of the newly created federal task force on
tainted fuels, was quoted by the Globe and Mail on Friday as saying
about 40 federal inspectors will continue inspections ``for a
considerable amount of time. ... It will be on the basis of spot
checks. We won't be at the border 24 hours a day.''.
   Samples will be analyzed for substances other than PCBs ``in the
order of weeks, if not days,'' Trip said.
   An Environment Department spokesman said its officers had
analyzed 360 samples.
   ``Nothing has been found so far,'' said spokesman K. Shikaze.
   This week the department restricted oil tanker trucks to
entering Canada at 31 of 125 border crossings to control the entry
of any tainted products.
   The Globe and Mail report quoted unidentified law enforcement
sources and unnamed participants in what it said was lucrative
illicit trafficking.
   PCBs were used primarily as a coolant in electrical
transformers, but have been banned in northern America because they
have been linked with cancer.
   Lawbreakers could avoid expensive disposal fees for PCBs and
other hazardous substances and boost profits by diluting fuel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
