<DOCNO> AP890519-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel Bjt   05-19 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, Bjt,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Killed in One of Uprising's Most Violent Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HALHOUL, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Palestinians were
reported killed Friday and a soldier was slain in the first
encounter with armed guerrillas of the 17-month-old uprising
against Israeli occupation.
   The deaths brought to 492 the number of Palestinians killed
since the rebellion began Dec. 8, 1987. Twenty-two Israelis have
been killed, including six other soldiers.
   It was the highest death toll since April 16, 1988, when 14
Palestinians died in a day of widespread clashes after the
assassination in Tunis of Khalil Wazir, the PLO military chief
known as Abu Jihad.
   The army sergeant and three members of a guerrilla squad were
killed by a grenade blast and automatic weapons fire in Beit Aula,
an isolated mountain village in the West Bank, the army said. A
lieutenant colonel was seriously wounded and six other soldiers
were slightly or moderately wounded, it said.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the West Bank commander, said the
Palestinians were wanted for attacking Palestinians suspected of
collaborating with Israel and killing one. The Fatah-Uprising Group
led by Abu Mousa issued a statement in Damascus, Syria, saying the
guerrillas were its members.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, Israeli troops killed five
Palestinians and wounded at least 11 in clashes with stone throwers
at the Rafah and Jebalya refugee camps, Arab hospital officials
said.
   They said those killed were a youth of 17 at Jebalya; the dead
at Rafah were a 50-year-old woman, and men aged 20, 22 and 30.
   Arab reporters said the trouble started when residents went out
to buy food in defiance of curfew. They said the camp has been
under curfew for most of the past two weeks.
   Ten Palestinians were reported wounded in confrontations with
soldiers elsewhere in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Soldiers renewed a curfew Friday on all 700,000 residents of the
Gaza Strip and Arab reports said more than 100 Palestinian
activists were arrested. Gaza had been under curfew since Monday,
but the order was lifted Thursday in some areas.
   Among those reported arrested was Sheik Ahmed Yassin, 52,
spiritual leader of the Moslem fundamentalist group Hamas. The
organization, whose name means zeal in Arabic, is among the
uprising's main coordinators.
   An army spokesman said grenade shrapnel killed Sgt. Itzhak
Revah, 25, and critically wounded Lt. Col. David Valkad at Beit
Aula.
   He said the Palestinians fired automatic weapons and threw a
grenade during the battle in the village 15 miles southwest of
Jerusalem. Soldiers sealed the area, stopping foreign journalists
at the nearby village of Halhoul.
   Israel radio said soldiers later blew up the homes of the three
guerrillas slain in the encounter. It said the houses were in Idna
and Nuba, villages nearby.
   Earlier Friday, the army said it demolished the homes of two
other Palestinians accused of attacking soldiers Surif, a West Bank
village.
   The battle in Beit Aula began after an alleged collaborator from
Nuba called the army, said Palestinians were firing at his house
and asked for help, Mitzna said. The general said soldiers
responding to the call passed through Beit Aula and ``unexpectedly
met a suspect car.''
   ``There was a chase and (the soldiers) opened fire,'' he told
reporters. ``The result was three of the group were killed and one
of our soldiers was killed, and another one was wounded very
seriously.''
   Revah was the first soldier killed in a gun battle since the
uprising began. Underground leaders of the uprising have urged
Palestinians not to use guns.
   Maj. Zeev Erlich, 35, who was hospitalized with shrapnel wounds
in the legs, said some of the soldiers were hit by automatic
weapons fire.
   ``When their car stopped ... we approached and fired on the
three,'' he said.
   ``At a certain stage, after they already laid on the ground and
we were done firing on them, apparently one of them fired a
grenade. The grenade exploded behind me and several others. It hurt
us in the back with shrapnel.'' Another soldier, identified only as
Capt. Rafi, said on Israel radio: ``I was in a vehicle behind the
lead jeep. I opened fire ... and shot the terrorist in the front
seat. I saw another terrorist in the back seat holding an M-16
rifle who was also firing. I reloaded and continued firing.''
</TEXT>
