<FIRST>u w PM-US-Germany 2ndLd-Writethru a0588 05-19 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0588,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, West German Continue Talks on NATO Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 8 grafs to include Stoltenberg, editing changes, picks
up 7th graf pvs, ``The U.S. government...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. and West German governments ``made
progress'' toward bridging their differences in two days of talks
over NATO short-range nuclear missiles, West German Defense
Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said today.
   ``The overall discussions were very, very encouraging,''
Stoltenberg said after concluding a second round of meetings with
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and before a session with
Vice President Dan Quayle.
   The defense minister declined to go into detail on whether the
two sides had reached agreement until he reports back to his
government in Bonn, but as he sat down to talks with Quayle, he
said:
   ``We work for a common position, so we have to argue and try to
come together. And we made progress.''
   Baker and Stoltenberg were working towards a ``gentleman's
agreement'' on the missile dilemma prior to a critical NATO meeting
in Brussels, but no final accord was due, and the U.S.-German
discussions were expected to continue next week, said a diplomatic
source close to the discussions.
   After their talks Baker left for President Bush's retreat in
Kennebunkport, Maine, for meetings touching on the NATO problem and
sessions with French President Francois Mitterrand on Saturday.
   The defense minister, after the meeting with Quayle, was
returning to Bonn for talks Sunday with Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the
diplomatic source said.
   The State Department meeting, the second in as many days between
Baker and Stoltenberg, took place as a senior government source in
Bonn reported the two sides had reached a compromise on the knotty
problem.
   The U.S. government has agreed to support the concept of
negotiations to reduce short-range missiles based in Europe in
return for West German assurances at next week's NATO summit that
the talks would not be aimed at total elimination of those weapons,
the source said.
   The government official said West Germany would go along with
the rest of the alliance at its May 29-30 summit on a statement of
unity that would make it clear NATO does not yet seek the
elimination of short-range nuclear weapons, only reductions.
   The short-range upgrade project, known as ``modernization,'' has
been shelved until at least 1991, the official said.
   The diplomatic source, who spoke on condition he not be named,
said Stoltenberg's aim was to indicate a ``new flexibility'' on
Bonn's part and sound the American side out about the timing of
possible U.S.-Soviet negotiations involving the short-range weapons.
   The United States has steadfastly balked at the notion of
starting such talks, fearing they could lead to stripping Europe of
all short-range nuclear weapons and leave the West vulnerable to
the superior conventional Warsaw Pact forces.
   Stoltenberg was to suggest a possible link between a reduction
of Soviet conventional forces in Europe with the start of
negotiations on reducing the number of short-range nuclear weapons.
The negotiations might not begin until there is ``significant
progress'' toward reductions by the Soviets and its allies, said
the diplomatic source.
   One proposal would be to form a high-level NATO study group,
which would define the ``significant progress'' necessary before
any U.S.-Soviet talks on short-range missiles could convene, the
source said.
   An administration official, speaking on the condition he not be
identified, said the West German proposals would be studied closely.
   ``We'll take a look at what they're trying to sell. But what do
they mean by significant progress? We have to define it,'' the
official said.
   The West Germans also oppose a U.S.-British effort to more than
triple the range of existing Lance missiles to just below 300
miles. The U.S.-built Lance now can hit targets from about 75
miles, and most of the 88 launchers and 700 single-warhead missiles
are based in West Germany.
   That opposition stems from the fact that the Lance is designed
for battlefield use, and if fired from a launcher in West Germany
most probably would strike East and West German territory.
   A group of West German parliament members visiting Washington
shared Stoltenberg's prediction that some agreement in the missile
dispute will be reached prior to the NATO summit.
   ``There's a new flexibility on both sides. The chances we will
reach an agreement are not 100 percent, but given the political
will, there's a good chance we will reach an agreement,'' said
Volcker Ruehe, the deputy majority leader in parliament, in a
meeting with reporters.
   Ruehe and three other parliament members said they were pleased
with the reception they received from officials the State
Department, the National Security Council and on Capitol Hill
during their three-day visit.
   As for U.S. opposition to any negotiations on the short-range
weapons, Ruehe said he'd ``never met anybody who's said they'd
never negotiate (on short-range weapons). ... The question is the
speed of the negotiations.''
   In any case, Ruehe said the West German could not make any
decisions about deploying a modernized version of the weapons until
after Kohl's government faces national elections in the fall of
1990.

</TEXT>
