<FIRST>r w AM-Boren-Gregg     05-19 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boren-Gregg,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boren Advised White House Not to Name Gregg to Top CIA Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., said Friday that he
advised the White House not to name Donald Gregg to a top CIA post
because ``he had become somewhat controversial during the
Iran-Contra hearings.''
   When George Bush was vice president, Gregg was his national
security adviser. President Bush has since nominated Gregg to
become U.S. ambassador to South Korea, and the nomination is stuck
in the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Boren, chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, said he
acted because he believed ``that the agency, because of the nature
of its work, did not need additional controversy at this time.''
   ``It in no way means that I feel that Mr. Gregg should be
automatically disqualified for other government positions,'' Boren
said.
   ``My personal opinion that he should not be named to a CIA post
was simply based upon my view that he had become somewhat
controversial during the Iran-Contra hearings,'' Boren said.
   Bush's nomination of Gregg to be ambassador to South Korea is
stalled in the Foreign Relations Committee because of Gregg's
relationships to key figures in the Iran-Contra affair.
   He also faces allegations that he may have been involved
personally in the illegal resupply of military aid to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels at a time when that was forbidden by
Congress.
   Boren said his committee has never held formal discussions about
Gregg's qualifications to serve in any post in government.
   He added that Gregg's nomination as ambassador has not prompted
him to reopen the Iran-Contra investigation.
   ``No one should draw the conclusion that I would support the
reopening of the Iran-Contra investigation by the Congress on a
major scale,'' Boren said. ``The Congress has other problems to
confront. The Iran-Contra matter is now appropriately in the
courts.''
   Boren said that other than helping to resolve problems about
some of the documents related to the original congressional probe,
``I would personally be opposed to reopening the investigation on a
major scale and have to this point seen no evidence which would
justify it.''
   Boren said he is not privy to any information regarding Gregg
other than what already has been made public.
   Gregg's nomination is opposed by Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.,
who has repeatedly asked the White House to withdraw it.
   Cranston has vowed to hold additional hearings to probe Gregg's
links to the Iran-Contra affair, warning that the results might be
embarrassing to both Gregg and the president.
   Cranston says he is considering calling other witnesses to
obtain their testimony under oath but has made no decisions.
   Gregg has told Senate supporters he had sought to be named to a
post for which Senate confirmation is needed in order to force the
issue, confront the suspicions about his role, and give himself an
oportunity to clear his name.
</TEXT>
