<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0632 05-19 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0632,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Predicts Syrian Offensive; Americans, Britons Advised to
Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs with British Embassy advising citizens to
leave and to CORRECT that U.S. Embassy did not explain timing of announcement.
Pickup 6th pvs, `Syria has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. and British embassies Friday
advised their citizens to leave Lebanon, and the leading Beirut
newspaper predicted a Syrian assault on the Christian enclave
defended by Gen. Michel Aoun's army units.
   The U.S. Embassy said it was ``not in a position to arrange
transportation of citizens from Lebanon,'' but Americans were
``strongly advised to depart Lebanon immediately ... because of the
threat posed by the security situation.''
   An American official at the embassy, speaking on condition he
not be named, said there were ``several hundred Americans in
Lebanon, most of them dual nationals.'' He refused to be more
specific.
   Sixteen embassy employees were evacuated to Cyprus on Feb. 17
during battles between Aoun and the Lebanese Forces, the main
Christian militia. That left about 25 in Lebanon.
   Christian radio stations broadcast a statement from the British
Embassy advising the 99 remaining Britons to leave Lebanon ``before
the sea shuttle service ... stops anew.''
   Ferry service between Lebanon and Cyprus, suspended during the
heaviest fighting of the past two months, resumed last week.
   Since March 8, Beirut has been devastated by artillery duels
between the Aoun forces and a Moslem alliance of Syrian troops and
Druse militiamen that have killed 359 people and wounded 1,393 by
police count. Most of the casualties have been civilians.
   The U.S. Embassy did not explain its timing, but the warning
coincided with a prediction by the daily An-Nahar that the Syrians
would attack to try to oust Aoun, who heads the Christian Cabinet
in Lebanon's divided government and commands about 20,000 men.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League and has become the country's main
power broker during 14 years of civil war.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command said Christian troops were
exchanging machine gun fire and rocket-propelled grenades with
Syrians and their allies at Souk el-Gharb southeast of Beirut.
   No casualties were reported, but ``they fire on us and we fire
on them. This hasn't stopped despite the Arab League-sponsored
cease-fire,'' the spokesman said by telephone, on condition of
anonymity.
   An-Nahar analyst Sarkis Naaoum said Syria ``will not permit''
the Arab League to work out a settlement leaving Aoun in charge in
the 310-square-mile enclave north and east of Beirut where most of
Lebanon's Christians live.
   Repeated efforts by the Arab League to implement a truce it
called April 28 have failed, mainly because the Syrians and Druse
continue shelling the Christian coastline to keep Aoun from
receiving supplies by sea.
   Naaoum quoted ``information recently received in east Beirut,''
the Christian sector, in saying Syria also ``would not allow the
emergency Arab summit conference, due in Morocco next week, to
become an arena for confronting its policy in Lebanon or
criticizing it.''
   ``The practical translation of these two Syrian stands would be
a serious military escalation different in power and size from the
flareup recently experienced,'' the analyst wrote. ``The main aim
of the operation would be to bring Aoun down, either by
overthrowing him or by forcing him to step down.'' He said Syria's
plan included ``destructive bombardment'' of military facilities in
the Christian enclave and a major offensive by its own soldiers or
militia allies.
   Aoun's troops and the Lebanese Forces militia would unite
against such an offensive, said Naaoum, a well-connected analyst
whose columns usually are taken seriously by Arab and Western
diplomats.
   As he described the military plan, the main assault would be
directed at Aoun's heavily fortified lines in Souk el-Gharb, seven
miles southeast of Beirut.
   The strategically located mountain resort commands a network of
mountain roads leading to the presidential palace at Baabda. Aoun
and his family have lived in the palace since President Amin
Gemayel, at the end of his six-year term last September, appointed
the general to lead a Christian government.
   Gemayel acted when Parliament could not agree on a successor.
Moslems swore allegiance to Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who was
premier under Gemayel, and the army also split into Christian and
Moslem commands.
   An-Nahar and other Lebanese newspapers reported earlier in the
week that two Syrian MiG-17 jet fighters flew low over the
Christian enclave Monday on an apparent reconnaissance mission.
</TEXT>
