<DOCNO> AP890519-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senators'Finances Bjt   05-19 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senators' Finances, Bjt,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Senators Wealthy, All Make Money Outside Senate, Forms Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators made extra money last year selling
hay, pitching jokes, collecting pensions, writing books and making
speeches _ lots of speeches. But none had to rely solely on a
Senate salary.
   According to financial disclosure statements made public Friday,
perhaps one-third of the 100 senators are millionaires and most
others are wealthy.
   Most have impressive investments.
   And most routinely accepted speaking fees and travel
reimbursements from special-interest groups.
   Here's how some senators supplemented their $89,500 Senate
paychecks last year:
   _Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., earned $15,000 as a lecturer at C.W.
Post College in Long Island, N.Y.
   _Donald Riegle, D-Mich., made 21 speeches at $1,000 apiece to
Washington Campus, a nonprofit educational organization that
conducts seminars.
   _Paul Simon, D-Ill., reported $3,042 in residuals from four
appearances on ``Saturday Night Live.''
   _Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, grossed $65,000 from five farms but
after subtracting expenses was left with only $6,000.
   _Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., reaped $1,760 selling hay off his farm.
   _Bennett Johnston, D-La., who heads the Senate Energy Committee,
pocketed $377 in oil-well royalties.
   _Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, earned
$22,500 in royalties from ``Men of Zeal,'' a book he wrote with his
Maine colleague, Republican Sen. William Cohen, which reflected
their service on the Senate committee that investigated the
Iran-Contra affair.
   _Cohen listed $25,763 in royalties, including some still coming
in from a novel he co-authored with ex-Sen. Gary Hart.
   _Alan Cranston, D-Calif., received $62,906 in pension from his
service as a California state official and $18,246 in Social
Security benefits.
   _Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., who lost a leg in the Vietnam war,
reported $18,972 from a Navy pension.
   Almost all the 95 senators who filed the required statements
(five were granted extensions) reported receiving honoraria _ which
usually were fees for making speeches to schools, churches and
special-interest groups.
   Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, listed $46,950 in such fees, including $10,000 from
elements of the defense industry. Under the rules, he could keep
only $35,800, so he gave $11,686 to charity.
   Richard Lugar of Indiana, senior Republican on the Agriculture
Committee and former chairman of Foreign Relations, picked up
$72,950 for speaking and turned over $37,189 to charity. His
audiences ranged from the National Pork Producers Council to the
National Association of Arab Americans.
   Wendell Ford of Kentucky, a senior member of the Commerce
Committee, reported $28,500 for speeches, many of them to regulated
groups, including the alcohol and tobacco industries that are
economic powers in his home state.
   Jake Garn, R-Utah, former chairman of the Banking Committee, was
a favorite speaker at financial and banking meetings. He was paid
$37,700 and gave $2,000 to charity.
   Tom Daschle, D-S.D., a freshman who serves on the Finance
Committee, accepted five expense-paid trips, four of them with his
wife. They included stops in Puerto Rico, in Louisville for the
Kentucky Derby, in Fort Lauderdale and Miami.
   Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and his wife accepted a free five-day trip
to Paris in connection with American Airlines' launching non-stop
service from Nashville to Paris.
   Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., was reimbursed by non-government interests
for trips to Cuba, San Francisco and Fayetteville, Ark.
   Not everything senators touched turned to gold last year.
Freshman Herbert Kohl, a multimillionaire, did well with his bakery
stock but his Milwaukee Bucks National Basketball Association
franchise lost $95,000, although it generated revenues of $12.1
million.
   In most cases, it is next to impossible to tell a senator's
financial condition from the disclosure statements. Items of
income, assets and liabilities are listed in broad brackets. Thus,
$6,000 interest earned shows up with a value of $5,001 to $15,000.
A $10 million gain from a property sale would be listed only as
worth $250,001 and up.
   Some of the wealthiest senators have assets in trusts. So, the
statement of Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., gives no clue that he has
an interest in trusts worth tens of millions of dollars. He has no
liabilities.
   Similarly, the extensive wealth of Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., is
tied up in trusts.
   When trusts are excluded, Kohl could be the richest senator,
with assets of up to nearly $28 million and liabilities of less
than $2 million. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., whose grandfather founded
Ralston Purina, lists assets of up to $13 million and no
liabilities.
   John Heinz, R-Pa., whose family started and still owns a large
block of H.J. Heinz Co., the ketchup-and-pickle giant, reported
assets of at least $11.2 million and perhaps $13.6 million, with
liabilities of about $1 million.
   Nancy L. Kassebaum, R-Kan., who owns real estate and a Wichita
radio station, listed assets of up to $4 million with maximum
liabilities of under $1.5 million.
   Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., one of the poorer members, said she
owns shares in a gold fund, but took pains to add the fund has no
investments in South Africa.
   Gifts worth nearly $5,000 were reported by Republican Leader Bob
Dole of Kansas. They included seven lithographs, a dozen silk ties
worth $240, a hand-tailored suit valued at $600, two cases of
champagne worth $888 and a $200 pencil drawing of himself.
   Phil Gramm, R-Texas, reported receiving a gift of steaks worth
$240. Simon, the Illinois senator whose bowtie is a trademark,
accepted a bowtie quilt of unknown value. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said
his wife won two airline tickets worth $1,858 in a raffle. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., said his assets include a 1976 Jaguar, which he
valued at under $5,000.
   Among the assets listed by Pete Domenici, R-N.M.: a mausoleum
crypt worth less than $5,000.
