<FIRST>r a AM-BroadcastHackers     05-19 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Broadcast Hackers,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-TV Executives Given Probation in High-Tech Theft Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former television news executives
apologized publicly and were sentenced to probation Friday after
pleading no contest to breaking into computer news files of a
competing station in what a prosecutor called the first case of its
kind.
   Hillsborough Circuit Judge Edward Ward agreed to withhold a
finding of guilt if Terry Cole and Michael Shapiro successfully
complete five years' probation and 250 hours of community service.
   During probation, the former employees of WTSP must take part in
annual industry seminars to warn others, especially journalism
students, how to ``avoid the pitfalls of a tremendous desire to
succeed.''
   Cole and Shapiro, both 33, expressed remorse for raiding the
files of CBS affiliate WTVT between last November and January. At
the time, Cole was news director at the ABC affiliate and Shapiro
was assistant news director.
   Before switching to WTSP, Shapiro had been an assignment manager
at WTVT and helped set up security for that station's newsroom
computer, including passwords and identification codes.
   To gain a competitive edge, prosecutors said, the pair broke
into WTVT's computer files containing stories, budgets, contracts
and plans of news operations.
   Shapiro was arrested in February, and Cole, his boss, was
arrested in April. Both men subsequently were fired by WTSP.
   The judge said the case involved a violation of trust and
confidence and crossed the line on ethics.
   ``The court is not going to close any more doors in your face,''
Ward said. ``I feel you men have earned a chance ... to have
society attempt to forgive you.''
   The judge sentenced each to one year probation on a single
conspiracy count and five years on 15 other computer-related theft
charges. He ordered the terms to run concurrently.
   Ward followed state sentencing guidelines but warned the
defendants, both first-time offenders, that he had the right to
exceed the guidelines and send them to prison for 22 months.
   Assistant State Attorney Chris Hoyer said it was the first
computer theft case involving the news business that he knew of in
the country.
   ``They knew what they were doing,'' Hoyer said at the 90-minute
hearing.
   Shapiro said: ``I'm extremely sorry about what happened. People
were hurt by it at the stations. My career has been ended. ... I
accept responsiblity.''
   ``I made a mistake,'' Cole said. ``I allowed something to happen
that should not have happened. I've ruined my career. I've lost the
respect of my colleagues. ... I don't know what else to say except
I'm sorry.''
   Greg Jones, a WTVT attorney, said the proceedings ``ought to
send a pretty clear message to anyone who thinks it makes sense to
compete by cheating.''
   He would not comment on the prospect of a civil suit.
</TEXT>
