<FIRST>u i AM-China-Square     05-19 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Square,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Scene of Defiance in Tiananmen Square, Symbolic Center of China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square, the symbolic center of power in
China, remained the heart of pro-democracy protests Saturday
despite the mobilization of troops to restore order.
   Before dawn Friday, Premier Li Peng and Communist Party chief
Zhao Ziyang visited some of the more than 3,000 students who have
been on a hunger strike in the vast square for a week.
   Li and Zhao boarded two of the several dozen buses parked on the
100-acre square that have sheltered the fasting students. After a
short visit, the leaders left without promising to meet demands the
students have raised for ending the strike, such as an official
dialogue with communist officials broadcast live on TV.
   Throughout the day, student leaders debated their next move.
Ambulances with sirens wailing raced out of the square to take
failing fasters to hospitals for treatment. Rumors of troop
movements swirled through the crowd.
   Tens of thousands of other students, some from provinces as far
away as Inner Mongolia, camped in solidarity with the fasters. Many
wore white headbands and armbands with slogans of support.
   The square was filthy from a week of occupation, with garbage
was piled high in several places and broken bottles strewn across
Tiananmen's stone tiles. Hygiene crews spraying disinfectant wound
through the crowd.
   Trucks carrying banner-waving workers and students constantly
lumbered down the streets surrounding Tiananmen. Other groups
marched through the square to support the fasters.
   By evening, student leaders decided to stay in the square but
stop the hunger strike. The fasting students descended from the
buses, carrying dirty quilts and blankets under their arms, and sat
down nearby.
   About 9:30 p.m., the square's official loudspeaker system began
broadcasting speeches of Li and President Yang Shangkun, who
revealed troops were moved to Beijing to restore order, drowning
out rival student broadcasts.
   Large groups gathered around the dozens of speakers, listening
in the eerie light cast by the square's lampposts. They
occasionally jeered Li and angrily shouted obscenities.
   As the speeches were rebroadcast, the students defiantly sang
the ``Internationale,'' the socialist anthem. The incensed strike
leaders, speaking from a bus _ their makeshift headquarters _
immediately announced the hunger strike would resume and claimed
all students in the square would participate.
   Human chains began forming around the perimeter of the square to
act as a line of defense against any troops. Trucks filled with
supporting workers raced down Beijing's streets toward Tiananmen
early Saturday, and a pack of up to 100 motorcylcists also roared
by.
   As the tension mounted, students remained defiant. ``I'm not
afraid to die,'' shouted one hunger striker who vowed not to eat
until the student demands were met.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
