<FIRST>r i AM-Italy     05-19 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Resigns Week Before Bush Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ciriaco De Mita resigned Friday in response
to sniping by Socialist Party rivals in his coalition, creating one
of Italy's periodic government crises a week before President Bush
visits.
   Negotiations to form what would be Italy's 49th postwar
government are expected to take weeks. President Francesco Cossiga
asked De Mita, a Christian Democrat, to stay on as caretaker.
   After giving Cossiga his resignation, De Mita told reporters the
Socialists left him no alternative to resigning.
   Bush is to arrive May 26 on the first stop of a European tour.
Former President Ronald Reagan faced a similar situation in June
1987, arriving in Italy after Premier Bettino Craxi resigned.
   Craxi, who leads the Socialist Party, is De Mita's main foe and
prompted the resignation by challenging the five-party coalition's
viability.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Mark Dillen, said ``it is too early to
say'' whether there will be a change in Bush's plans, which include
meetings with De Mita and Pope John Paul II.
   Bush's nominee for ambassador to Italy, Michigan businessman
Peter Secchia, also has not yet been confirmed by the Senate.
   Maxwell Rabb, who served eight years, held a farewell party
earlier this week and planned to fly home on Saturday, but reports
are that he will stay for the Bush visit.
   De Mita has led the government for 13 months and the Socialists
have accused him for weeks of not showing leadership.
   In a closing speech Friday at the Socialist convention in Milan,
Craxi demanded a ``political and procedural clarification'' and an
urgent Cabinet meeting. De Mita resigned immediately after that
meeting.
   Besides the Christian Democrats and Socialists, his coalition
includes the small Republican, Social Democrat and Liberal parties.
   Craxi leads Italy's third-largest party, after the Christian
Democrats and Communists, and is trying to regain the premiership.
   He and other Socialist leaders have accused De Mita of failing
to implement the coalition's agenda of political and economic
reform, including reduction of a deficit projected at $90 billion
for this year.
</TEXT>
