<FIRST>r a AM-ChinatownReax     05-19 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinatown Reax,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese-Americans Rallying Behind Beijing Demonstrators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though Justin Yu now lives thousands of miles
from his native China, he can't help but feel connected to students
in Beijing who are trying to win political freedoms from a
staunchly Communist government.
   ``I feel like it is happening to me,'' said Yu, president of the
Chinese Language Press Club in New York and a reporter for the
World Journal, the largest Chinese language newspaper in America.
``I wish I could go home and be part of it.''
   Yu, who emigrated to the United States 20 years ago and is now a
naturalized citizen, is one of about 300,000 Chinese in New York,
many of whom are keeping a close watch on developments in Beijing's
Tiananmen Square.
   Some 3,000 students have been on a hunger strike to pressure the
Chinese government into allowing free speech and a free press. Tens
of thousands of other Chinese have held vigils to support the
protesters.
   Developments overseas have been closely monitored and residents
of New York's Chinatown often know what's happened before the rest
of the United States.
   On Friday, while the world was learning that the Chinese
government had sent army troops into Beijing to end the
demonstrations, in what amounted to imposition of martial law,
Samson Ling said he already knew.
   ``We just heard the 27th and 28th armies are moving into
Beijing,'' said Ling, managing editor of China Spring, a monthly
magazine circulated among Chinese students in the United States,
Canada, Hong Kong and Western Europe.
   ``We've already gotten telephone calls from people in Beijing.
... It's a pretty tense time. Now, all we can do is wait and see.''
   In New York, which has the United States' largest Chinese
population outside of San Francisco, student groups, business
people and local Chinatown residents are supporting the students in
Beijing by holding their own demonstrations and raising funds.
   About 1,000 people, mostly students, planned to demonstrate in
front of the Capitol in Washington on Saturday to ask the U.S.
government to support the Chinese students' actions.
   Students from China studying in America also have sent several
thousand dollars to the students in Beijing, according to local
Chinese-American newspapers. Most of the money is to help buy badly
needed telephone, copying and fax machines to help publish fliers
and student newsletters.
   ``Support for the demonstrators is nearly 100 percent from
overseas Chinese,'' said Peter Lee of the Centre Daily News, a
Chinese-American daily.
   ``It's solidified all sorts of people: students; businessmen;
old, established Chinatown residents,'' said Lee. ``Even staunch
pro-Taiwanese have joined forces with pro-communists and agreed to
leave their conflict behind over this issue.''
   ``It's really quite an exciting time, in China and in America,''
said Lee.
   ``This is a great event,'' said Bu Jin, 42, a native of Shanghai
who is studying political science at Columbia University. ``But
people outside of China shouldn't expect the whole communist
government to come tumbling down because of it.''
   ``This movement, as impressive as it is, can hardly be
considered a revolution,'' he said. ``The students are asking so
little, freedom of speech and freedom of press, that's different
from wanting to change the whole system.''
   Yu says he has mixed feelings about events in his homeland.
   ``On one hand, I'm so happy to see there is hope for China's
future. But I'm saddened that students are having to suffer to get
basic rights. We're still having to suffer, after 5,000 years, to
get basic rights that so much of the world has. It's really
depressing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
