<DOCNO> AP890519-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Party     05-19 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Party,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Regional Chief's Job in Jeopardy After Marcos Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top immigration official in Western
states, whose appearance at a party for Ferdinand Marcos
embarrassed the White House, is likely to be replaced, a Justice
Department spokesman said.
   David Runkel, chief spokesman for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, on Thursday described Harold Ezell as a
``short-termer'' in the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
which is part of the Justice Department.
   Ezell, 52, said earlier this week that he made an error when he
attended a party given in Honolulu in August by ousted Philippines
leader Marcos and his wife, Imelda.
   After news organizations obtained a homemade videotape of the
party last week, he said he also erred in leading partygoers in a
prayer asking for the couple's safe return to the Philippines,
which would be against President Corazon Aquino's wishes and U.S.
policy.
   The Marcoses have been indicted in New York on charges of
diverting Philippine government money to buy millions of dollars
worth of real estate. Marcos, who has been hospitalized since
January for a variety of ailments, took a turn for the worse this
week and was listed in critical condition Friday.
   ``I would expect there would be a new INS director in that
region as part of bringing in a new management team for the INS,''
Runkel said. He would not elaborate on his statement.
   Ezell said late Thursday he had not been told his resignation
will be accepted. Ezell, who has been Western regional director of
the INS since 1983, has said he would like to continue in the job.
   ``As far as I know, this guy Runkel doesn't make the decision.
It's up to the White House and the attorney general,'' Ezell said.
``If we don't get to continue, I think we've had a big challenge
and done terrific accomplishments.''
   The outspoken Ezell is credited with playing a major role in
implementing the federal immigration amnesty program. Nearly
900,000 of the 1.5 million illegal aliens who applied for amnesty
were in the Western region.
   However, some critics have accused Ezell of focusing too much
attention on himself.
   ``His grandstanding style of operation and his constant grabbing
of headlines did nothing to bring about a better understanding of
the immigration problem,'' said Peter Schey, executive director of
the National Center for Immigrant Rights in Los Angeles.
   Ezell said if he doesn't keep the job he probably will pursue
business opportunities. He denied reports he is interested in
running for Congress.
   ``I've got zero regrets,'' Ezell said of his INS tenure. ``Since
I took this job on, I really don't think there's a major flaw to
hang our heads about. We've gathered a good team of 5,500 people in
the INS region, and they've done a good job.''
</TEXT>
