<HEAD>Walesa Meets Interior Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd, `Walesa declined...' to ADD comment
after meeting; picks up 4th pvs, `The accords...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and top
union activists and advisers met the interior minister and other
government officials Friday to discuss the political and economic
accords reached last month.
   It was the second meeting of the Arbitration Commission, a group
set up to oversee implementation of the accords reached between
authorities and the opposition April 5.
   Walesa declined to talk to reporters before the start of the
meeting in the parliament building, but the interior minister, Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, said: ``I am sure we assumed the right direction
and this is irreversible no matter if one likes it or not.''
   After the 3{-hour session, Walesa said: ``It is important that
both sides are willing to remove obstacles and understand that they
will occur but have to be reduced.''
   Jozef Slisz, leader of Rural Solidarity, said authorities
accused Solidarity of being confrontational, and Solidarity said
its posters were being torn down.
   A joint communique carried by the official news agency PAP said
authorities criticized the tone of articles in the new opposition
newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza and Solidarity did the same about Trybuna
Ludu, the Communist Party paper.
   The accords resulted in the legalization of Solidarity after a
seven-year ban and provide for partially free elections to the
National Assembly.
   Elections to the Sejm and the newly created Senate _ the East
bloc's first freely elected legislative body _ are set for June 4
with a runoff on June 18.
   The first meeting of the commission was held April 18, one day
after Solidarity was legalized again.
   During those talks, Walesa met with Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski who issued the December 1981 martial-law decree that
sought to dissolve the independent trade union.
   Among those accompanying Walesa were top adviser Tadeusz
Mazowiecki, Wladyslaw Frasyniuk, the Solidarity leader from the
southwestern city of Wroclaw, Warsaw Solidarity leader Zbigniew
Bujak, and political theorist Jacek Kuron.
   Politburo members Stanislaw Ciosek and Wladyslaw Baka, and
Sports Minister Alexander Kwasniewski were among the
representatives of authorities.
