<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SchoolChoice     05-19 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Choice,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos Will Promote Local School Plans that Allow Parents to Choose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos on Friday
announced grants, conferences and other steps his department is
taking to promote state and local plans that let parents choose the
public school their child attends.
   ``I consider choice the cornerstone to restructuring elementary
and secondary education in our country,'' Cavazos said at an
Education Press Association luncheon. ``We must do away with
ineffective conventional arrangements that only block reform.''
   Cavazos said he will personally chair four regional strategy
meetings at which governors, legislators, state education chiefs,
principals, teachers and parents will develop choice strategies for
their states.
   The secretary said he is naming a special adviser to develop
choice initiatives and a task force to evaluate choice programs
around the country. He also said he is directing that choice be a
major priority of grants awarded under the $5.8 million Secretary's
Fund for Innovation in Education.
   Cavazos, President Bush and others contend that giving parents
and students freedom to choose will invigorate schools and assure
that no child is involuntarily subjected to a second-rate
education. They say competition has created top-flight higher
education in the United States and earlier grades will benefit from
the same approach.
   The most ambitious plan is in Minnesota, which offers open
enrollment across district lines, postsecondary options and area
learning centers. Cavazos said the experiment has inspired Iowa and
Arkansas to enact open enrollment legislation and said 21 states
are considering choice programs. Scattered individual districts,
most notably East Harlem, N.Y., also have choice programs.
   At the request of the state of Minnesota, the department will
conduct a three-year evaluation of the impact of its program,
Cavazos said.
   Richard Miller, executive director of the American Association
of School Administrators, accused Cavazos and the Bush
administration of using the choice issue to try to divert attention
from underfunding in programs such as Head Start and Chapter 1, the
major federal effort for disadvantaged children.
   He said open enrollment choice programs can be beneficial to
some schools but charged that Cavazos is dodging real problems with
equity and cost. ``In essence, the secretary's approach would do
the least for those who have the least,'' Miller said.
   The secretary said he is aware of concerns that choice would
create a two-tiered education system, one for the fortunate and the
other for the disadvantaged.
   But he said inequities already exist and choice will enable
parents and students to improve their educational situations.
``Furthermore, armed with the power of choice, parents can force
inferior schools to upgrade or close,'' he said.
   Asked how districts can pay for the added costs of a choice
program, particularly transportation, Cavazos said districts
already are spending an enormous amount of money.
   ``They need to start thinking about where the dollars are going
and redirect those dollars to where they can have the most
impact,'' he said. ``If choice is the goal, they need to address
that transportation issue.''
   Cavazos said his department has published a booklet called
``Choosing a School for Your Child,'' available to parents free of
charge from the Consumer Information Center, Pueblo, Colo., 81009.
   He said two more booklets will be released this summer:
``Parental Choice in Six Nations'' and ``Improving Schools and
Empowering Parents: The White House Workshop on Choice in
Education.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
