<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia 1stLd-Writethru a0621 05-19 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March in Memorial for Victims of Clash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with reports of children poisoned
by gas in schools, dissidents freed from prison, protest shown on TV. No
pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Georgians marched through the streets
of the capital city of Tbilisi on Friday in memory of 20 people who
died in ethnic unrest on April 9.
   A dissident arrested the day of the clash between protesters and
soldiers charged on Friday that children in several schools later
were poisoned by gas that appeared similar to that used against the
demonstrators.
   The poisonings caused ``a great panic in the city,'' said Zviad
Gamsakhurdia in a telephone interview from Tbilisi.
   He was released from prison on Thursday pending trial.
   Yuri Goldadze, an editor of the official Gruzinform news agency,
said in a telephone interview that ``many thousands'' took part in
Friday's 3{-mile march from the city's medical institute to the
Sion church in Tbilisi's Old Town.
   The march ended with a requiem service. It was held on the 40th
day after the clash, a day of religious significance in the
Georgian Orthodox faith.
   The national evening TV news program ``Vremya'' showed streets
full of people and black-clad mourners crying and holding portraits
of the dead. Young men carried flags of mourning and Georgian
national flags and raised clenchedfists during a moment of silence.
   Among the participants were city and national officials, who
granted permission for the march, Goldadze said.
   He said the march and religious service were ``absolutely
peaceful'' and that the requiem service was shown live on the
Caucasus republic's official television.
   Nineteen people were killed when soldiers moved into a crowd of
pro-independence protesters on Tbilisi's Rustaveli Avenue on April
9. One young man was shot and killed later for violating a curfew.
   The clash was another example of the ethnic unrest that has
upset the Caucasus region and many other areas of the Soviet Union,
but caused a particular outcry because of charges of brutality
against the soldiers. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev called it a
blow to his reform program.
   Witnesses said the soldiers beat protesters with shovels and
Georgian officials said the soldiers used a chemical substance that
had an effect similar to nerve gas on some of the protesters.
   However, Moscow officials said the soldiers only used a chemical
agent similar but stronger than tear gas.
   Gamsakhurdia, a member of the Tbilisi Helsinki Watch Committee,
said a report was broadcast on official TV that some children had
been poisoned again recently by gas, and that officials were
investigating.
   He said children from schools No. 55, 53 and 101 were poisoned,
and all schools in the city were closed a week ahead of schedule to
avoid more cases. An undetermined number of children were being
treated for poisoning, he said.
   Protests began in Tbilisi in early April against demands by the
Abkhazian minority in northwest Georgia to have their area
transferred to the Russian republic. But many banners supporting
complete independence for Georgia soon appeared among the
demonstrators.
   The republic's Communist Party chief, Dzhumber Patiashvili, took
responsibility for the violence and resigned.
   Gamsakhurdia, a protest organizer, was arrested the same day
soldiers broke it up. He said he faces charges of violating social
order by organizing protests from last September through April, and
faces up to three years in prison if convicted.
   Also released were Mirab Kostava of the St. Ilya Society, Irakly
Tereteli of the Party of National Independence and Georgy Chanturia
of the National Democratic Party of Georgia, he said.
   All face the same charges, he said.
</TEXT>
