<FIRST>u w AM-Fed-MonetaryPolicy     05-19 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fed-Monetary Policy,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Policymakers Voted in March to Hold Interest Rates Steady</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Policymakers at the Federal Reserve in March
voted to hold interest rates steady unless the slowing of economic
growth proved inadequate to restrain inflation, according to
minutes of the meeting released Friday.
   The Federal Open Market Committee, noting early signs of a
slackening in economic growth, voted 11-1 at its March 28 meeting
to leave rates unchanged initially.
   But most members felt monetary policy ``should be adjusted more
readily and promptly toward greater restraint than toward ease,''
the minutes said.
   The committee, which meets in secret eight times a year, sets
monetary policy for the Federal Reserve, whose main job is to fight
inflation.
   In March 1988, the Fed began to gradually push interest rates
upward in an attempt to cool the economy and thus curb inflation.
Since then, short-term rates have risen three percentage points and
economic growth has shown signs of softening.
   Most analysts believe the Fed is holding off on further
tightening of credit while it analyzes how the economic slowdown
will affect inflation.
   Price increases have been sharp so far this year. The Consumer
Price Index rose at an annual rate of 6.6 percent over the first
four months of 1989, up from the 4.4 percent price increases
registered in 1987 and 1988.
   FOMC members in March found recent price increases to be
``disappointing, if not entirely unexpected'' but many wanted ``to
wait for evidence to accumulate on the possible need for a further
tightening of policy,'' the minutes said.
   Some members felt ``the current slowing of the expansion might
be inadequate to restrain inflationary pressures,'' the minutes
said.
   Since the March meeting, signs of a slowdown have become more
pronounced and analysts believe the Fed is unlikely to push rates
higher.
   The FOMC met again this week but minutes of that meeting will
not be released until after the committee's next meeting in early
July. The committee is made up of the seven Federal Reserve
governors and the presidents of five of its 12 regional banks.
   The committee issues directives that govern the open market
operations of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. Through the
purchase of government securities from banks, the central bank
influences the amount of reserves the banks have to make loans from
and thus the price of those loans _ interest rates.
   The committee's March directive to the New York bank said the
FOMC ``seeks to maintain the existing degree of pressure on reserve
positions.''
   However, it added that ``somewhat greater reserve restraint
would, or slightly lesser reserve restraint might, be acceptable.''
In Fed parlance, the word ``would'' carries stronger implications
than does ``might.''
   The lone dissenter from the March vote was Fed Gov. Martha
Seger, who opposed the tilt toward further increases in interest
rates, according to the minutes.
   Ms. Seger earlier this month told a group of home builders that
with the recent softening in economic growth, ``we need to be very
wary of slipping over the edge into recession.''
   A growing number of private economists have expressed concern
that the Fed's anti-inflation campaign could have the unintended
effect of causing a recession. The latest survey of 50 leading
economists by the Blue Chip Economic Indicators newsletter found
that two-thirds expect a recession to begin this year or in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Rights     05-19 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Rights,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Helsinki Committee Formed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hungarian Helsinki Committee held
its founding session Friday and said it wants to probe human rights
violations in Hungary and elsewhere in the Soviet bloc.
   The meeting was attended by Karl Johannes von Schwarzenberg,
president of the Vienna-based International Helsinki Federation for
Human Rights, said group member Ferenc Koeszeg.
   Participants approved the statutes and elected a 16-member
steering committee, including Koeszeg, a representative of the
League of Free Democrats, and Rudolf Joo of the Hungarian
Democratic Forum.
   In addition to monitoring the Hungarian situation, ``the HHC
would like to send observers to neighboring countries to
investigate circumstances of human rights violations'' there, a
16-page founding document said.
   ``What the government and the police are doing with the
dissidents in Czechoslovakia, with Georgians and Armenians in the
Soviet Union, with Albanians in Yugoslavia and with every citizen
in Romania is in profound contraction with the principles of
Helsinki,'' the document said.
   All European countries except Albania, as well as the United
States and Canada, signed the 1975 Helsinki final act on human
rights and approved additional rights provisions agreed upon at
Helsinki follow-up conferences.
   The founding statement also said, ``We are convinced that there
is still a great deal to be done in the area of human rights (in
Hungary).
   ``The machinery of coercion is still intact, the penal code
still allows the prosecution and jailing of people on political
grounds. The police are empowered to hold people without access to
the courts and to restrict their freedom,'' it added.
   The committee also said it would try to oversee parliamentary
and local elections with the goal of free balloting and the
development of a multiparty system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
