<FIRST>r w AM-Aronson-LatinAmerica     05-19 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aronson-Latin America,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aronson Says Press Reports May Have Overstated Gorbachev's Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Aronson, President Bush's choice to
run Latin American policy in the State Department, said Friday that
some press reports may have overstated Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's apparent pledge to end Soviet military aid to Nicaragua.
   ``It's not clear in what manner military aid will be reduced, if
at all,'' Aronson said at his confirmation hearings before the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   ``My impression is that some of the press reports about it have
been a little more ambitious about what it contains than what it
may contain,'' Aronson said.
   The nominee declined to characterize the contents of a Gorbachev
letter on the subject to Bush, saying that had to be left to the
president.
   He did say that Secretary of State James A. Baker III ``very
much wants to test Soviet intentions'' in the region, especially on
the issues of Soviet aid to Nicaragua and Cuba.
   ``They have an opportunity to demonstrate that in an area of the
world that is very important to the United States that they want a
new beginning,'' Aronson said.
   Aronson was asked by Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of
the panel's Latin American subcommittee, what he thought of White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater's characterization of Gorbachev as
``a drugstore cowboy,' out to score propaganda points.
   ``I think that as a general rule it is wise to conduct our
diplomacy based on a discussion of issues,'' Aronson said, avoiding
a direct reply.
   Dodd pressed the question and Aronson drew laughter when he
replied: ``Don't ask me to start my tenure at the State Department
by criticizing the spokesman at the White House.''
   Aronson, nominated to be assistant secretary of state for Latin
American affairs, opened his testimony by pledging bipartisan
cooperation with the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   Aronson's predecessor, Elliot Abrams, presided over Latin
American policy in the Reagan administration. Abrams' impassioned
advocacy of U.S. military support for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels
was controversial and he had a stormy relationship with Congress.
   ``If I am confirmed I'll bring with me a strong belief in
consultations,'' Aronson said. ``At the end of the day we need to
come together as Democrats and Republicans to form a bipartisan
foreign policy.''
   ``I'm not looking to go off to the State Department and make
policy by myself,'' he said.
   Dodd told the nominee he had been concerned about the nomination
``because of your lack of experience in Latin America.'' But he
added: ``Your responses today have reduced my skepticism ... I'm
going to take you at your word on consultations.''
   Questions spanned the Latin American horizon and included these
issues and countries:
   _Should the United States move to normal relations with Cuba?
   Aronson said that if Cuba is interested in normalizing relations
it should stop arming leftist guerrillas in El Salvador and stop
abusing the rights of its own citizens. Failure to take such steps
would ``stand in the way of a major normalization,'' Aronson said.
   _Nicaragua: If the Sandinista government negotiates rules which
provide a ``level playing field'' for the national elections
scheduled for Feb. 25, 1990, the United States might consider
easing some of its current sanctions.
   _El Salvador: As the newly elected right-wing government takes
office, the United States should insist on ``real progress toward
human rights, a respect for a free judiciary and the rule of law.''
   _Panama: The recent election in which thugs allied to the
country's military leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, beat
opposition candidates ``makes old-style Chicago politics look like
a picnic. ... I think it's important General Noriega understand
that the United States is not going to raise these concerns and
then if the issue is not resolved go back to business as usual.''
   _The decision by the Organization of American States to condemn
the conduct of the Panamanian elections and call for Noriega's
removal: Aronson said that ``it sends a signal that democracy is
threatened and that the democratic community in Latin America and
the Caribbean cares.''
   _The Panama Canal treaties: ``I strongly support the Panama
Canal treaties. Just as the treaties were a proud symbol of
friendship between the American and Panamanian peoples, the
abrogation of the treaties would be seen as a rejection of that
friendship and a return to an earlier relationship. I do not think
it would be a wise or responsible act,'' Aronson said.
   _On democratic governments: Aronson said that ``we never get
into trouble when we defend democracies and we often get in trouble
when we do not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
