<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionConsent     05-19 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Consent,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Doesn't Expedite Abortion-Consent Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court took no
action Friday on a state request for a quick decision on the
validity of an abortion consent law challenged successfully in
lower courts by lawyers for a 15-year-old girl.
   ``They are not going to have any ruling today on that motion,''
said Supreme Court clerk Sid White. ``Possibly Monday.''
   The girl's attorney said that barring action by the state
Supreme Court, her client was free to end her pregnancy, which was
in its 12th week, without the consent of her parents or a judge.
Lawyer Jerri Blair would not say if the girl, identified only as
T.W. of Lake County, had obtained an abortion.
   The U.S. Supreme Court refused Thursday to reinstate Florida's
abortion consent law, clearing the way for the girl and other
single minors to get abortions without consent until the state
Supreme Court deals with the matter.
   The state attorney general's office has moved to speed up the
state Supreme Court justices' review, scheduled for September, of
the validity of the 1988 law or allow enforcement in the meantime.
But the court took no action on that request Friday.
   In papers filed with the court, Assistant Attorney General Jerry
Curington argued there is confusion over whether the law is invalid
statewide.
   Although the law was struck down by only one of Florida's five
district courts of appeal, in Daytona Beach, a 1976 precedent
apparently means it cannot be enforced in the other four districts
either, he wrote.
   Therefore, Curington argued, the justices should expedite their
review or keep the law in effect until they rule on the
constitutional issues.
</TEXT>
