<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lumber Death,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freak Accident Kills Train Operator</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROC1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lumber jutting from a moving freight
train slammed into the engine cab of a passing Amtrak train Friday,
killing the engineer, police said.
   The force of the collision pulverized the lumber and instantly
killed engineer P.L. Sylvester, 59, of Kirkville, said police Capt.
Robert Dewey.
   ``Ultimately, when you add the speeds of both trains you're
talking about 90 miles an hour of impact,'' Dewey said.
   The accident occurred about 4:30 a.m., minutes after Amtrak's
Lakeshore Limited, bound for Chicago, left downtown Rochester with
about 350 passengers.
   Two other Amtrak crew members in the cab were not injured, said
Amtrak spokeswoman Sue Martin.
   Police had not determined how the load of 2-by-6 lumber broke
loose from its steel bands. Boards jutted out nearly 10 feet, but
the crew of the Conrail freight train may have been unaware of it,
Dewey said. The lumber was on the ninth car from the end of a
95-car train.
   The Amtrak train remained at the accident site for 2{ hours
before proceeding under power of a Conrail engine.
