<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan     05-19 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Burns Self to Death at Memorial for Dissident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the opposition party burned
himself to death outside the president's office Friday during a
memorial rally by 10,000 people for a dissident publisher who
committed suicide to avoid arrest.
   Witnesses said Chan Yih-hua was engulfed in flames when he lit
bottles of gasoline strapped to his waist under a black mourning
vest.
   Riot police doused the area with water cannons. Several mourners
helped extinguish the flames with jackets and umbrellas and took
Chan to a nearby hospital, where he was pronounced dead.
   Chan, in his thirties, was a member of the Democratic
Progressive Party formed three years ago, primarily by native
Taiwanese, to oppose the governing Nationalists.
   Party officials said Chan admired Cheng Nan-jung, 42-year-old
publisher of the weekly Freedom Era, who was accused of printing
seditious articles calling for permanent separation from China.
   The Nationalists, who fled from the mainland to Taiwan in 1949
after losing a civil war to the Communists, still claim to be the
legitimate government of all China.
   Cheng died in an apartment fire April 7 after hurling firebombs
at police who had come to arrest him.
   Relatives and police said Cheng committed suicide. Friends said
he had vowed to burn himself to death and become the first martyr
of the Taiwan independence movement.
   More than 3,000 mourners, many wearing black vests printed with
``Establish New Nation,'' remained outside the presidential office
building Friday night for a sit-in in the rain. Thousands of riot
police watched.
   The demonstration was the largest on the island since Taiwan
lifted 38 years of martial law in 1987.
   Mourners, including college students and church members, urged
President Lee Teng-hui to allow freedom of speech, including
advocacy of an independent Taiwan, and release all political
prisoners.
   Police said the mourners dispersed shortly after midnight,
ending a demonstration that had lasted 11 hours.
   Cheng's coffin was taken on a two-hour funeral procession
through Taipei by 2,000 supporters before the memorial service.
Riot police erected barbed-wire barricades to keep the crowd away
from the building.
</TEXT>
