<DOCNO> AP890519-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NaziScience     05-19 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi Science,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Use of Nazi Research Data Has Occurred, Ethicist Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debate over whether to use research by Nazi
scientists on unwilling death camp prisoners is moot because much
of the information already has been used, the organizer of an
international conference on ethics said Friday.
   ``It's wrong to say that the question is whether we should look
at this data. The fact of the matter is that we have looked at it _
and looked at it pretty hard,'' said Arthur Caplan, director of the
University of Minnesota Center for Biomedical Ethics.
   ``Americans have cited it more than 20 times in professional
journals. British military physicians talked about it in the '60s.
In fact, it was used several times here at the conference'' when
scientists described the research and its findings, Caplan said in
an interview after the three-day conference ended.
   He cited the work of Dr. Robert Pozos, an expert on hypothermia
who has gained widespread attention in scientific circles for his
claim that Nazi research should not be wasted even if the means
used to obtain it were despicable.
   Pozos conceded in an interview Friday that Nazi research was
used in his presentation at the conference, the Meaning of the
Holocaust for Bioethics.
   ``That's fair. I'd take it a step further and say this whole
conference was in a sense a use of that data,'' Pozos said.
   Pozos told the scientists Thursday night, ``The value of human
life is great and if we have the means to save human life _ even if
the data is suspect _ we should use it.''
   A professor of physiology and biophysics at the University of
Washington, Pozos cited tests in which 80 to 90 prisoners at Dachau
were dunked in freezing water, sometimes to their deaths, to help
Nazi researchers design protective gear for Luftwaffe pilots who
might be shot down over water.
   ``Physiologically, the data still is valid and has value today
in terms of describing acute cold stress in water,'' Pozos said.
``The situation is one in which I think good might come from evil.''
   Asked if he felt guilt about using the data, Pozos said, ``I
don't feel comfortable with it. The discussion troubles me. I have
very strong mixed emotions about it. It wakes me up at three in the
morning.
   ``But the question is not whether to use the data. It's how to
address the fact that it is being used and how that fact should be
acknowledged.''
   The conference, which Caplan said drew 225 scientists,
ethicists, theologians and Holocaust survivors from eight
countries, also included discussions on the propriety of using Nazi
analogies when discussing abortion and on the relationship between
medicine and Naziism.
   Eva Kor, of Terre Haute, Ind., a survivor of Dr. Josef Mengele's
experiments on twins at Auschwitz, told a panel discussion at the
conference Thursday night that she was appalled by the idea that
scientists might use the data.
   Kor and her sister, Miriam, spent 10 months in Auschwitz when
they were 9 years old. Of their family, only the twin sisters
survived.
   ``I learned the soap I washed with for two years was made out of
human fat,'' Kor said. ``I had nightmares for years later that the
soap I washed with was made from my own parents.''
   Velvl Greene, another panel member who is director of the
Jakobovits Center for Jewish Medical Ethics at Ben Gurion
University in Beer Sheva, Israel, said he was ``sickened and
appalled'' by the straightforward manner in which Pozos appealed
for use of the Nazi data.
   But Greene said he agreed the data should be made available if
it would save lives.
   ``It is not a question of can we use the data, but how best can
we use the data as a memorial,'' he said. ``Maybe by memorializing
it, we will never mitigate it but we will remember.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
