<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Bush     05-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Bush,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Criticizes Bush Speech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in an
interview released Friday that he was amazed by the ``old
ideological film'' on President Bush's address a week ago on
U.S.-Soviet relations.
   His comments in the Communist Party daily Pravda, transmitted by
the Tass news agency, were the first high-level reaction to Bush's
May 12 speech at Texas A&amp;M University.
   ``The speech of President Bush at the Texas university, I admit,
amazed me,'' Shevardnadze said. ``It amazed me with its tone, I
would even say with its somehow old ideological film and in places
with its didactic inclination.
   ``It seemed to us that our political dialogue already had
crossed into a new category, freed from the blinders of ideological
rhetoric, that we may carry it out without empty polemic cliches.''
   The minister, just back from the Soviet-Chinese summit in
Beijing with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said it was
``completely incomprehensible'' to the Soviets why Bush said the
Soviet Union had yielded to Washington's appeals to renew
negotiations on strategic nuclear weapons.
   He said Moscow had long been pressing to restart the talks, but
the Bush administration delayed while it conducted a review of its
arms control policy.
   Still, Shevardnadze said he found some ``correct, positive
thoughts'' in the statements of Bush and Secretary of State James
A. Baker III, who visited Moscow last week.
   And he added, ``We will judge U.S. policies not by their words,
but by their deeds.''
   Both sides said at the end of Baker's two-day visit on May 11
that the new U.S. administration got off to a good start in its
relationship with the Soviet Union.
   They said they would resume negotiations on strategic weapons in
June.
   Gorbachev told Baker the Soviet Union will withdraw unilaterally
500 short-range nuclear warheads from East Europe this year, but
Baker rejected the negotiations the Kremlin sought to remove all
such weapons on both sides.
   Baker said the Soviets still have an overwhelming advantage in
the weapons that must be reduced further before negotiations can
begin.
   The warheads are at the heart of a dispute in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization. The United States and Britain want to
modernize and extend the range of NATO's Lance missiles. West
Germany leads a group of NATO countries that want to start
negotiations with the Soviet Union on removing them.
   In response to a question, Shevardnadze denied that Moscow was
trying to put pressure on NATO.
   He reiterated that the Soviet Union wants to begin negotiations
to remove the missiles. ``Our position on this question derives
from common sense, and there is nothing threatening in it,''
Shevardnadze said.
</TEXT>
