<FIRST>r w AM-AlaskaSpill-Industry     05-19 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Spill-Industry,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Lobby Steps Up Defense of Exxon's Cleanup Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main lobbying group for the major U.S. oil
companies, seeking to blunt public criticism of Exxon Corp.'s
handling of the Alaska oil spill, said Friday the company should
not be faulted for the slow pace of cleanup.
   ``The cleanup moves slowly because it is based upon
environmental and ecological considerations,'' said Charles J.
DiBona, president of the American Petroleum Institute.
   DiBona earlier this week toured Prince William Sound, where
nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil spilled from the Exxon
Valdez supertanker on March 24 in the worst oil spill in U.S.
history.
   He said six of the 88 miles of shoreline hit with the heaviest
amounts of oil have been cleaned up. A total of 364 miles of
beaches was affected by the spill.
   In a bid to deflect some of the criticism from Exxon, DiBona
repeatedly stressed that the company was committed to spending as
much money as necessary to clean the spill completely, even if it
had to return to the scene next spring.
   A Transportation Department official, meanwhile, said a report
to President Bush on the government and industry response to the
spill was ``critical of everybody'' for a ``wholly insufficient''
job of reacting to the accident.
   DiBona sought to portray Exxon's effort as being especially
sensitive to the possibility that the cleanup itself could do
further damage to the area's wildlife.
   He said Exxon crews were engaged in a ``particularly arduous''
cleanup on the north side of Smith Island and other areas where the
seasonal seal birthing, or pupping, is approaching.
   ``Slow progress cleaning the first several thousand feet of
shoreline has discouraged some, but the slowness is the result of
the special considerations associated with these efforts,'' DiBona
said, adding that ``the cleanup needed to be especially rigorous
because of concerns for seal pupping.''
   He said ``progress clearly will accelerate'' once work proceeds
beyond the next few weeks.
   DiBona also downplayed the effects of the spill on fish and
birds in the area.
   ``There is no evidence of a major fish kill,'' he said, adding
that most migratory birds were not hurt by the oil because they
were in an area east of the spill.
</TEXT>
