<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietNuclear     05-19 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Nuclear,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Says Post-Chernobyl Safety Changes Nearly Ready</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad overhaul of Soviet civilian nuclear
safety standards, triggered by the 1986 Chernobyl disaster, will be
completed this summer, a senior Soviet official said Friday.
   The revised ``General Safety Rule'' will include new safety
requirements that correspond to standards set by the International
Atomic Energy Agency, said Vadim M. Malyshev, chairman of the State
Committee on Supervision of Nuclear Power Safety.
   ``Some of the requirements are even higher'' than the
international rules, he added.
   Malyshev spoke in an interview with two American reporters
following talks with his U.S. counterpart, Lando W. Zech Jr.,
chairman of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   A five-man Soviet delegation of nuclear regulatory officials
visited the Calvert Cliffs nuclear plant in Maryland on Wednesday
and is scheduled to tour the Indian Point nuclear station and the
Brookhaven National Laboratory, both in New York, next week.
   U.S. regulators visited Soviet nuclear facilities last August.
   Malyshev and Zech announced after their meeting at NRC
headquarters that they had approved plans for an exchange of
nuclear safety inspectors as part of a broad cooperation agreement
signed in April 1988.
   A two-person team of Soviet inspectors will spend about seven
weeks at the Catawba nuclear station near Rock Hill, S.C., and an
American team will spend a similar period at the Zaporoshye nuclear
facility southeast of Kiev in the Ukraine.
   Each side will study the other's inspection techniques and
operator safety procedures.
   Malyshev, speaking through an interpreter, said a broad review
of safety standards was undertaken following the April 1986
Chernobyl accident in the northern Ukraine that killed at least 31
people and released a cloud of radiation that eventually circled
the globe. It was the worst nuclear accident in history.
   Malyshev did not give specific examples of changes in Soviet
safety standards, but he said a ``revised and re-edited'' set of
rules would be ready by June or July.
   The Soviet official took issue with a report earlier this month
that the local Communist Party chief in Kiev was complaining of
declining attention to safety at Chernobyl, where reactors not
involved in the accident are still operating.
   ``I think that is incorrect,'' Malyshev said. ``I feel the level
of requirements has been raised and the safety culture, as it's
called, has become significantly higher.''
   Malyshev also said safety regulators were studying when and
whether to decommission about 12 old-generation civilian nuclear
plants. The Soviets have a total of 45 civilian nuclear reactors.
   ``We think the closest possible date for decommissioning those
would be sometime before the year 2005, but it may well be
considerably earlier than that,'' he said.
   He cited two reactors already picked for decommissioning: the
No. 2 unit at the Beloyarskiy station, situated in the Ural
Mountains near the city of Sverdlovsk, and the No. 2 unit at the
Novovoronezhskiy station, near the city of Voronezh in the Russian
republic.
</TEXT>
