<DOCNO> AP890519-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Politics     05-19 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Politics,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Party Adopts Political Reform Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party adopted a
political reform plan Friday in hopes of repairing a reputation
left in tatters by a bribery and influence-peddling scandal.
   The plan, proposed to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita on
Thursday, would put lower limits on some political donations,
reduce the number of parliament seats and require all legislators
to disclose their assets. Only Cabinet members now are required to
reveal their wealth.
   It also would require Cabinet members and party officials to
leave their party factions, said Masaharu Gotoda, former chief
Cabinet secretary and chairman of the party Political Reform
Committee.
   Five factions dominate the party, each with a leader who aspires
to be prime minister. The factions are blamed for much of Japan's
big-money politics because the power balance among them is
determined largely by their financial strength.
   In a scandal that began last summer and has reached the top of
politics and business, the Recruit Co. is accused of of trying to
buy favors with large donations and insider stock deals that
benefited about 160 politicians, bureaucrats and business
executives.
   Gotoda described the reform plan to reporters as
``forward-looking'' and said, ``The most important thing is how to
implement it.
   ``Similar scandals have been repeated every 10 years or so, and
this proposal is also intended to eliminate the root of such
scandals,'' he said.
   The reforms now go to the parliament as legislation and are
expected to be enacted by November.
   Provisaions include a ban on speculating with political funds,
requiring that the funds be in government bonds or deposited in
banks, a ban on fund-raising parties by Cabinet members, which are
a common way to dodge limits on political donations, and reducing
the need for campaign money by gradually lowering the number of
parliament seats from 512 to 471.
   Analysts said they found some willingness in the party to make
the changes necessary to regain public confidence, but many
remained skeptical of its ability to abandon the old practices.
   Koichi Kishimoto, a prominent critic of politics, said the party
includes people ``whose prime concern is how to cling to their
power.''
   This is the most serious crisis to date for the Liberal
Democrats, who have governed Japan since 1955.
   Party leaders, including Takeshita and his predecessor, Yasuhiro
Nakasone, took Recruit money and Takeshita admitting to accepting
the equivalent of $1.1 million in various forms. The prime minister
has said he will resign soon.
</TEXT>
