<FIRST>r w AM-US-Solidarity     05-19 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Solidarity,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Says Violent Upheaval Still Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Solidarity leader cautioned Friday that
Poland could face a violent social upheaval despite the new
political arrangement in that country.
   ``The real danger to the new Polish policy is not the resistance
of hardliners but the economic situation,'' said Bronislaw Geremek,
a historian who has served for nine years as a top adviser to Lech
Walesa and is emerging as a senior statesman of the Polish
opposition.
   Geremek met Friday with Vice President Dan Quayle and with
Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, and addressed a
seminar at the Wilson Center of the Smithsonian Institution.
   Speaking at the Wilson center, Geremek warmly praised a speech
on Polish affairs given by President Bush last month in which the
president pledged economic assistance if the government carries
through with economic reforms.
   ``The direction was very good. In President Bush's speech, we
found the enunciation of a general policy,'' said Geremek.
   Poland's Communist authorities have re-legalized Solidarity,
which they outlawed and tried to crush under martial law from 1981
through 1983. And they have agreed to elections next month in which
Solidarity and other opposition groups will be able to put forward
candidates for the first time.
   Under the agreement, a coalition consisting of the communists
and allied parties is guaranteed a majority in the Sejm, or lower
house of parliament, but no quotas are set for a newly created
Senate.
   Equally important, the agreement sets no quotas for Communist
domination under elections scheduled four years hence, and it
allows Solidarity to publish its own mass-circulation newspaper for
the first time since the declaration of martial law in December
1981.
   ``We signed the agreement because we felt that an explosion of
political unrest in Poland could destroy a political deal,''
Geremek told the Wilson Center seminar.
   ``The urgency is not overstated. And I am not sure that we have
obtained a comprehension of that from the government side,'' he
said.
   Communist officials have said they signed the agreement to widen
political support for an economic reform program they have been
pushing unsuccessfully for years.
   ``The existance of strong trade unions is a danger to economic
reforms,'' said Geremek, referring not so much to Solidarity, which
has agreed to work for the reforms, but to official unions that
have been pushing for higher wages.
   ``At the end of the year, the deterioration of the economic life
of Poland could destroy what could be a national rebirth,'' he
said. ``We have a situation in which Solidarity, having gained
tremendous moral authority, may have the ability to prevent that
explosion.''
   Geremek forecast a Poland in which Communist authorities enjoy
increasingly less power, but which would not withdraw from the
Soviet-led defensive alliance, a step that prompted the invasion of
Hungary in 1956.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
