<FIRST>r w AM-Proxmire-GoldenFleece     05-19 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Proxmire-Golden Fleece,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proxmire Issues First Golden Fleece Award as a Private Citizen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., who
waged a running battle against government waste and extravagance
during his 31-year Senate career, on Friday issued his first Golden
Fleece award as a private citizen.
   His target: multi-million dollar spending to help educate
doctors by the Public Health Service of the Department of Health
and Human Services.
   Proxmire's point: Physicians make more money as a class than
virtually any other group of Americans and can easily afford to
finance their own educations, even if they have to go into debt.
   James Brown, a spokesman for HHS's Public Health Service, said
Proxmire's reference to the program he was harpooning was too vague
to ascertain which one he meant.
   ``It's difficult to respond to this because we don't have
specifics,'' Brown said. ``There are a number of programs (in which
money is spent to educate doctors) so it is impossible to determine
which he means.''
   Although Proxmire said the program he wants eliminated costs
$100 million a year, Brown said he was not sure of the figure.
   For example, Brown said, one program dating back to the 1970s
provides special training for new doctors to become primary care
physicians. This year, $59 million will be spent on the program.
   ``This is a program this administration and the previous one
have tried to eliminate, but the Congress keeps putting the money
back in,'' Brown said.
   The administration wants to cut the program ``because it has
already accomplished what we wanted to do _ getting doctors into
the primary care areas,'' he said.
   Proxmire said he believed that program was the one to which his
award pertained and said both Congress and the administration
should share the blame for wasteful spending.
   He said the executive branch should have taken a stronger stand
and insisted the money be taken out of the budget.
   ``If they (the administration) had made their case with
sufficient force, if they had publicly said this is a waste of
taxpayers' money, there's no question Congress would have had to
react and eliminate it,'' Proxmire said.
   At a news conference at the National Press Club, Proxmire said
American doctors represent ``the world's best compensated
occupation.''
   There is no shortage of doctors to justify subsidizing their
educations, he said. Proxmire pointed out that while there were 142
doctors for every 100,000 Americans in 1950, that ratio has
increased to 233 per 100,000.
   ``Doctors are increasing 60 percent faster than the population
at large,'' the former senator said.
   And he says that's not surprising. ``A profession that pays the
average practitioner _ and I mean average _ $120,000 a year will
not not lack for new practitioners,'' he said. ``So what we have is
$100 million of your tax money spent for nothing.''
   Proxmire issued his non-senatorial Golden Fleece in a small
burst of self promotion.
   He is starting a nationwide weekly column syndicated by United
Features in which he will tell the country what he thinks about
subsidizing the education of doctors, as well as other issues.
   The column will be Proxmire's first newspaper job since he was
fired as a reporter by the Madison, Wis., Capitol Times in 1949, he
says.
   Since then he has run his own publishing company, served in the
Senate and issued more than 150 Golden Fleece awards in a series
that was unbroken from March 1975 to last December when he retired
from the Senate.
   Previous targets include Transporation Department officials who
spent $10,000 to inspect the transportation system at Disney World,
and government studies of why people fall in love and why prisoners
want to escape from jail.
</TEXT>
