<FIRST>r a AM-MspiBurning     05-19 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mspi Burning,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Mississippi Burning'' Quietly Opens, Closes in Town Portrayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Mississippi Burning'' has closed
after a quiet, five-day run in the town portrayed in the movie
about the deaths of three civil rights workers.
   The film had been scheduled to open May 24 at the Ellis Theatre,
several months after its national premiere.
   ``I found out it was the last week of schools and graduation so
I moved it up'' to May 10-14, Shelly Steiger, whose family has
owned Philadelphia's only theater for more than 35 years, said
Friday.
   Steiger said the five-day run was ``the way I play all my
pictures.'' He said he never considered extending the time because
it would not pay off in a town of about 7,000 people.
   Attendance was better than average, Steiger said, although he
could not provide figures. ``Most came to see it out of curiosity I
think,'' he said.
   Steiger suggested that many who wanted to see the film had done
so in Meridian, 40 miles to the southeast, where the movie opened
Jan. 27 and ran for eight weeks.
   Monty Royal, manager of R&amp;S Cinema in Meridian, said the movie
was the year's biggest money maker for his theater in the city
where federal trials of those accused in the civil rights murders
were held.
   ``Most people were very understanding of the fact that Hollywood
made a movie that was entertaining,'' Royal said. ``Generally,
everybody that I saw said it was one of the better movies that they
had seen and they did think the atmosphere that was played in the
movie was indicative of the times.''
   ``Mississippi Burning'' is a fictionalized account of the
federal investigation into the murders of James Chaney, Andrew
Goodman and Michael Schwerner in Neshoba County. Their bodies were
found in an earthen dam near Philadelphia six weeks after their
deaths on June 21, 1964.
   The Orion Pictures release was praised by critics and won an
Academy Award for best cinematography. The movie was harshly
criticized by people involved in the civil rights movement,
particularly blacks who said it gave the FBI too much credit.
   Steiger said he observed little reaction from Philadelphia
audiences.
   ``It was just a very quiet crowd. They had very few comments,''
he said. ``Those who said anything said it was overblown; so much
of it didn't happen.''
   Stanley Dearman, publisher of the weekly Neshoba Democrat
newspaper, agreed, saying, ``It's just not being talked about very
much.''
   Dearman added that he was disappointed that Steiger had
``slipped (the movie) in and slipped it out.
   ``I would have loved to have been able to interview people
exiting the movie to get their reaction,'' said Dearman, who said
he was out of town when ``Mississippi Burning'' opened.
   Steiger said the movie was advertised on the two local radio
stations as usual.
</TEXT>
