<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     05-19 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calls For Independent News Agency in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LJUBLJANA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist officials in Slovenia
said Friday that Yugoslavia's most liberal republic needs an
independent news agency, the official Tanjug news agency reported.
   The Slovenian news agency would compete with Tanjug and would
help in ``making the news reporting more objective,'' an official
of the republic's Socialist Alliance, a Communist-led mass
organization, was quoted as saying.
   The Belgrade-based Tanjug is now the only news agency in
Yugoslavia.
   The northern republic of Slovenia, whose leadership advocates
regional autonomy, greater democracy and closer ties with the West,
has long been at odds with the republic of Serbia, where officials
favor greater central control and a stronger federal government.
   Slovenian officials claim the Serbian press, including Tanjug,
is conducting a ``media war'' against democratic processes in
Slovenia.
   The founding of the Slovenian news agency would ``help in
avoiding biased and unobjective informing of the public,''
Slovenian officials reportedly said, adding that the competition
``would also be good for Tanjug.''
   In another development, Slovenia's official youth organization
demanded a retrial of four people sentenced to jail by a military
court, Tanjug reported.
   Three Slovenian journalists from the outspoken Mladina youth
weekly and an army sergeant-major were sentenced last July to jail
terms ranging from 10 months to four years on charges of possesing
a classified document.
   The action sparked a wave of public protests in Slovenia, which
culminated with a rally of about 30,000 people in the regional
capital, Ljubljana, on May 8.
   The protesters claimed the charges and closed trial were rigged
by the military to punish the journalists for publishing numerous
articles sharply criticizing the armed forces.
   The youth organization also demanded that the defendants be
allowed to get civilian legal counsel instead of the military
attorneys stipulated by army regulations.
   Under Yugoslav law, official requests by such organs must be
taken into consideration by the regional authorities.
</TEXT>
