<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-19 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heat Hits Northern Appalachians, Texas; Cold in Northern Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Unseasonably high temperatures crept to 90 degrees Friday
afternoon in portions of New York and interior New England, while
southern and western Texas wilted under another day of heat and
humidity.
   In the northern Rockies, however, afternoon temperatures were
near the freezing mark in Yellowstone National Park and several
inches of snow accompanied by high winds fell overnight on some of
the higher mountains. Dixie, Idaho, reported 9 inches of snow and 4
inches fell at Lolo Pass, Mont.
   Temperatures fell into the teens in some of the higher
elevations of the Northwest.
   In extreme southern Texas, temperatures neared 100 degrees. San
Antonio recorded a high of 97 to break the record of 96 set for the
date in 1939.
   At Beeville, a temperature of 99 degrees and a relative humidity
of 45 percent brought the heat index to 112 degrees.
   The cooling effect of the Gulf of Mexico, however, kept Port
Aransas, Texas, at a comfortable 80 degrees.
   The cold waters of the Atlantic Ocean likewise kept eastern
Boston in the 50s through mid-afternoon, while a short distance
inland temperatures were in the 70s and 80s.
   Burlington, Vt., hit 91 degrees, breaking the city's record of
90 degrees for the date set in 1971.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. CDT ranged from 33
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 100 degrees at Laredo, Texas.
   A low pressure system approaching the Mississippi Valley spread
showers and thunderstorms eastward into the Ohio Valley and
southern Appalachians. Thunderstorms produced small-size hail in
the St. Louis area.
   Rain was scattered from Michigan to Minnesota and Iowa and along
the cold front over the Dakotas, while afternoon thunderstorms
developed along the central Gulf Coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. CDT
included .73 of an inch at St. Louis, .54 at Rockford, Ill., .32 at
South Bend, Ind., and .31 at Grand Forks, N.D.
   A large area of clear skies stretched from California across the
intermountain region and the central and southern Rockies to the
southern half of the Great Plains.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
from the Great Lakes across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys to the
Gulf Coast, over the southern Plains and along the eastern slopes
of the central and southern Rockies. Scattered showers were
forecast across the Dakotas and the Pacific Northwest, and gusty
winds were expected to continue over the northern Rockies and
northern Plains.
   High temperatures were expected in the 60s from the Pacific
Northwest across the northern Rockies to the Dakotas; in the 90s in
Florida and from Texas to the interior valleys of California; and
up to 100 degrees along the Rio Grande Valley of Texas and in the
desert Southwest. Temperatures were expected in the 70s and 80s
across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
