<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Soviet     05-19 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Soviet,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Installment of Troops, Tanks Move Out of Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARBOGARD, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Red Army pulled out an additional
54 tanks and 600 soldiers from Hungary on Friday in a ceremony
highlighted by a military parade, an army band and a Soviet trooper
singing a patriotic song in Hungarian.
   The Soviets withdrew 31 tanks from Kiszkunhalasz base in
southern Hungary on April 25, the first step in a partial Soviet
pullout from East Europe announced by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev last December.
   The plan calls for the Soviet army to be reduced by 500,000 men
by the end of 1990.
   About 62,000 Soviet soldiers are stationed in Hungary. The
Soviets have promised to withdraw 10,000 servicemen, 450 tanks,
3,000 vehicles and more than 200 artillery pieces by the end of
next year.
   From Sarbogard base, about 50 miles south of Budapest, the T-64
tanks of the 141st Tank Regiment of the 13th Guards Tank Division
moved out Friday.
   A Soviet artillery unit, now positioned near the Austrian
border, will occupy this military base. Officials have said the
idea is to create a 100- kilometer (62-mile) zone of confidence
along the border with neutral Austria.
   Hungarian Young Pioneers rushed up to departing soldiers,
handing them flowers and red Pioneer kerchiefs.
   Janos Sabatkai, a local Communist Party secretary of Sarbogard
village, praised the Soviet troops for their help in time of need _
helping out at harvest time or when natural calamity struck.
   He added, ``There were undesirable things that happened as
well'' during the Soviet soldiers' stay, but did not elaborate.
   Lt. Gen. Yuri Vodolazov, first deputy commander of the departing
tank division, stressed that the Soviet troop cuts were unilateral.
   He said these troops will be demobilized when they get home,
adding: ``No one should mistake this move. We are prepared,
together with the Hungarian people's army, to defend socialist
unity. We hope the NATO countries will follow suit.''
</TEXT>
