<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Yellowstone     05-19 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Research Wants Fire Management Plans To Involve Surrounding Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Yellowstone-Let Burn on AM-News Advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ANGELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National park and forest
managers have taken too narrow a view in forming policies such as
the suspended practice of allowing forest fires caused by nature to
burn, an expert said Friday.
   ``The key point is the parks can no longer be considered
ecological or social islands,'' University of Washington professor
James Agee told the Greater Yellowstone Coalition.
   ``They are tied to surrounding areas, for better or for worse.
The park manager who thinks he is ... independent of surrounding
lands is living in a fantasy land.''
   Agee said the goal in any future policies should not be to allow
natural fires to burn for their own sake, but to achieve natural
changes in landscapes.
   Agee, a fire resource management expert, was a featured speaker
at the influential private environmental group's first annual
meeting since last summer's devastating fires burned sections of
nearly half of the 2.2 million-acre national park. The coalition
claims a membership of 3,100 individuals and 60 organizations
nationwide.
   When the Yellowstone fires were raging out of control in July,
the Interior Department suspended a ``let burn'' policy adopted in
1972 under which naturally caused forest fires were allowed to burn
unless they threatened lives or structures.
   Yellowstone spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo confirmed Friday that
lightning-caused fires will be fought in the park this summer.
   Agee said fire management policies in the future will have to be
based on the ``ecosystem'' concept, applying policies to areas in a
region with similar ecologies.
   ``We can no longer rely on the myth of natural regulation,''
said the chairman of the University of Washington's Division of
Forest Resource Management. ``These are not closed systems.''
   Changes in the world's climate also will have to be considered,
Agee said, and current policies are ``not sufficient to the task.''
   ``We must look at a network of land managed for multiple
goals,'' he said. ``We must recognize that the boundaries of the
parks are permeable barriers.''
   And any policy must reflect the impact of man and his role in
natural processes, Agee said.
   Agee's comments followed welcoming statements by Jim Schmitt,
executive vice president of the coalition board, who said ignorance
among politicians, the media and the public were to blame for the
criticism heard about the management of the fires last summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1846EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-North-Iran-Contra     05-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North-Iran-Contra,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Prosecutors Say They Didn't Rely on Immunized Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's prosecutors said Friday they
gathered their evidence independently from the former White House
aide's immunized congressional testimony given in 1987.
   The government made the assertion in a federal court filing
urging rejection of North's request for a post-trial hearing on the
issue.
   In his testimony on Capitol Hill, North detailed many of the
activities for which he was later accused of crimes, including the
three felonies for which he was ultimately convicted.
   Under a 1972 Supreme Court ruling, the office of independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh is required to show that its evidence wasn't
derived from North's immunized testimony.
   North's lawyers are seeking the hearing in an attempt to get the
case against him dismissed. They have said the grand jury that
indicted him and the jury that convicted him might have been
tainted by exposure to his immunized testimony.
   But prosecutor David Zornow's response said the government
demonstrated before and during the trial that its evidence had been
collected without taint from North's 1987 testimony.
   Zornow said the allegation that the juries may have been tainted
was ``speculation'' that was ``unfounded and irrelevant.''
   ``The thorough inquiry which the court has already made on the
grand jury issue more than sufficiently discharges any supervisory
duties that the court may have,'' the prosecution asserted.
   The prosecution also said the court and lawyers conducted a
``searching'' questioning of jurors in the North case before trial
regarding any possible exposure to North's congressional testimony.
   The ex-National Security Council aide was found guilty May 4 of
aiding and abetting an obstruction of Congress, altering and
destroying classified documents and accepting an illegal gratuity.
   North also is asking U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard A. Gesell
to require that each member of the prosecution team be subjected to
questioning at a hearing on possible taint from North's immunized
testimony.
   ``The government demonstrated before trial the extensive
procedures adopted by independent counsel to insulate his staff,
including the three associate counsels who tried the case,'' said
Zornow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PigCarcasses     05-19 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pig Carcasses,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pig Carcass Study Could Help Police Find Buried Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY NEMEC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials and scientists
from across the nation met here Friday to learn more about finding
buried bodies by using an unusual study of buried pig carcasses.
   ``Pigs come closest to humans in bone structure, blood type,''
said Kim Castellano, an investigator with the Douglas County
sheriff's office.
   Her agency and the Arapahoe County sheriff's office began the
buried pig carcass study last fall, dubbing the project PIGS for
``Pigs In the Ground Study.''
   On Friday, the Rocky Mountain Division of the International
Association of Identification opened a two-day conference that drew
140 law enforcement officials and scientists.
   ``This is groundbreaking research. No one has really studied the
effects on buried bodies for law enforcement purposes,'' said Steve
Adams, president of the Rocky Mountain division and a detective
with the Aurora Police Department.
   Volunteer scientists and law enforcement personnel have been
studying pig burial sites at the Highlands Ranch Law Enforcement
Training Facility since last September.
   Investigators said they have observed changes at the sites such
as different plants growing around the graves. They have collected
insects that appear at the sites _ above and below ground _ and
gases emitted from the ground.
   The study has employed bloodhounds, aerial photography and
infrared sensing devices, too, during what may become a five-year
project, officials said.
   The idea of using buried pigs was developed last summer.
Investigators from the Arapahoe and Douglas County sheriff's
departments and the Colorado Bureau of Investigation found
themselves talking about how difficult and expensive it is to
search for hidden bodies.
   The immediate results of the innovative study have been so
dramatic that the Rocky Mountain division has attracted its largest
conference audience ever, said Tom Griffin of the CBI.
   ``This is the most unusual conference in law enforcement I've
ever seen with one effort,'' said Douglas County Sheriff Steve
Zotos.
   ``The main thing that surprised me was the accuracy of the
bloodhounds'' in locating the pig carcasses, said Castellano.
``They went right to the pigs.''
   Conferees have come from as far away as Fairbanks, Alaska, and
Illinois and Texas and represent all branches of law enforcement
from local police department to the FBI, organizers said.
   The research project also has brought in entomologists,
botanists, anthropologists, geologists, archeologists and
geophysicists.
   After a concluding panel discussion Saturday, the conferees were
expected to go out to the actual burial sites to study firsthand
the clues and observe the changes in the areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
