<DOCNO> AP890519-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MathProdigy     05-19 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Math Prodigy,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Teen-age Prodigy Coming to Harvard to Teach, Do Math Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old British math prodigy has
accepted a one-year post as a visiting lecturer at Harvard
University, becoming one of the youngest Ivy League faculty members
ever, Harvard officials said Friday.
   Ruth J. Lawrence was taught by her father in their home in
Huddersfield, England, and had never been to school before she
entered Oxford University at age 11 in 1983.
   She graduated from the prestigious British university just two
years later, at age 13, and expects to receive a doctorate in
mathematics there this year.
   ``She's a very pleasant, well-balanced person, happy to talk
about various topics and not particularly aggressive or
particularly shy,'' said Vaughan Jones, a professor of mathematics
at the University of California at Berkeley.
   Lawrence was courted by several leading American universities,
including Berkeley and the Institute for Advanced Studies at
Princeton University in New Jersey, before she accepted Harvard's
offer.
   Jones, who has visited Lawrence in England, said she is a
vegetarian and likes bicycling on a tandem bike with her father, a
computer consultant.
   While at Oxford, she earned a reputation as ``the best
undergraduate ever in math there,'' Jones added.
   Harvard officials said she will arrive in the fall and spend her
first semester in Cambridge doing research, free of teaching
responsibilities. In the spring, she is scheduled to lead a
graduate seminar on knot theory, an area of theoretical mathematics
dealing with knots and similar curved, three dimensional objects.
   Keith Ramsey, a graduate student in math at Harvard, said
students and faculty are curious to hear the British wunderkind.
   ``There's been a lot of attention given to the fact that she's a
teen-ager, but I think that most of the interest we have is, in
fact, going to be in what she does, rather than in her being a
prodigy,'' he said.
   Harvard officials said they believed Lawrence would be the
youngest woman faculty member in the Ivy League.
   Iris Milotsky, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
University Professors in Washington, said a handful of child
prodigies previously have taught at top universities.
   ``It's certainly unusual, but not unprecedented,'' she said.
   One of the most famous of the prodigies was Cotton Mather, who
entered Harvard at the age of 12 and received his degree three
years later, in 1678.
</TEXT>
