<FIRST>r i AM-Amnesty-Israel     05-19 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-Israel,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Palestinian Allegedly Executed by Israeli Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International said Friday that witnesses
alleged that Israeli soldiers summarily executed a Palestinian
activist in a West Bank village in February.
   The London-based human rights organization demanded that Israeli
authorities urgently investigate the death of Atwah Lufti Umar
Hirzallah, 26, in Deir Abziye near Ramallah.
   It said the Jerusalem Post quoted unidentified Israeli military
sources on March 1 as saying people trying to block a road hurled
rocks at a passing military patrol and soldiers fired, killing
Hirzallah, because they feared their lives were endangered.
   Amnesty said witnesses gave this account in sworn statements:
   Hirzallah and four others walked into Deir Abziye around 9 p.m.
on Feb. 27 after taking home to a nearby village a friend who was
wounded in earlier clashes with Israeli soldiers.
   The five were stopped by two Israeli soldiers who had been
waiting concealed behind a wall and were ordered to raise their
hands.
   One soldier turned a flashlight on them, then focused it on
Hirzallah, and the other soldier shot Hirzallah with an M16 rifle
at almost point-blank range.
   The soldiers told the others to sit on the ground and villagers
later were allowed to take Hirzallah to Ramallah Hospital, where he
was pronounced dead.
   The victim's family was ordered to bury the body within hours.
   Amnesty said it telexed Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on April
28 saying it was ready to turn over the statements to an impartial
inquiry authority if assurances were given that the witnesses would
not be endangered. It said no response was received.
   The statement said Amnesty previously requested investigations
into the killings of Palestinians during the 17-month-old uprising
against Israeli occupation in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and
``this is the first time it has expressed fears of one being the
result of a deliberate extrajudicial execution.''
</TEXT>
