<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Romania,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgian Politician Beaten In Romania, Brussels Recalls Ambassador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgium decided to recall its
ambassador in Romania on Friday, one day after a leading Belgian
politician was beaten when he tried to meet with a Romanian
dissident.
   Gerard Deprez, chairman of the Belgian Christian Democratic
Party and a member of the European Parliament, tried twice Thursday
evening to meet in Kluj, Romania, with Donia Cornea, a leading
dissident who is under virtual house arrest, party spokesmen said
on condition of anonymity.
   The fate of Mrs. Cornea, who has been harrassed for a year by
Romanian authorities, was widely publicized in the West last year
by Belgian television.
   Deprez was first stopped by a dozen plainclothesmen, the sources
said. When he tried a second time, he was beaten by policemen who
took his money, they added.
   Belgian Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans Friday decided to recall
the Belgian ambassador in Bucharest and summoned the Romanian
ambassador to a meeting on Monday.
   Deprez gave up trying to meet with Mrs. Cornea and returned to
Bucharest, from where he will fly back to Brussels Saturday, his
party said.
   The Paris-based Romanian League of Human Rights reported Friday
that Dan Sempeleanu, a Romanian professor of English, was severely
beaten during 18 hours of detention after he tried to meet with
Mrs. Cornea on April 12.
   Sempeleanu reportedly signed a recent letter to President
Nicolae Ceausescu protesting a major village destruction program
which is to set aside new agricultural land for state farms, said
league member Mihnea Berindei in a telephone call from Paris.
   Berindei also said three workers from Sarnesti near Brasov met
with a similar fate when they tried to meet with Mrs. Cornea on May
1. He said the three, who also signed the letter to Ceausescu, are
believed to be still under arrest.
</TEXT>
