<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Media     05-19 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Media,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Plans to Restrict Cross-Ownership in Media</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government outlined proposals Friday to limit
cross-ownership of newspapers and broadcast outlets in an attempt
to prevent control from falling into a few hands.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd said owners of national newspapers
would be prohibited from having more than a 20 percent stake in any
independent television station, new radio stations and the
satellite channels directly awarded by the government.
   The ownership restrictions could hamper the expansion plans of
Britain's biggest media investors, notably Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp. and publisher Robert Maxwell. Both already own major
newspapers.
   Murdoch's company also controls Britain's only satellite
station, Sky Television.
   Maxwell's interests include holdings in cable television and a
planned satellite station. He also has expressed his intention to
bid for a new television license the government plans to offer.
   Owners would not be forced to sell properties they now hold,
said a spokeswoman for the Home Office, who was not identified in
accordance with British practice.
   Under the proposals, regional and local newspapers would be
limited to a 20 percent share of any regional TV and radio licenses
in their geographic areas.
   The same 20 percent limit would be placed on cross-interests
between direct broadcast satellite companies, independent TV and
national radio license holders.
   In a written response to a question in the House of Parliament,
Hurd said the proposed controls underscored the government's
determination that ownership in the independent broadcasting sector
should remain ``widely spread, and that unhealthy concentrations of
ownership and excessive cross-media ownership should be prevented.''
   A comprehensive broadcasting bill including the proposals will
be presented to Parliament late this year.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
