<FIRST>r w AM-SavannahRiver     05-19 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savannah River,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Sets up Special Office for Reactor Restart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins said Friday
he was adding a new supervisory office at the troubled Savannah
River nuclear weapons plant in South Carolina to improve the
department's oversight of the aging complex.
   Watkins announced the establishment of a Special Projects
Office, starting June 1, at Savannah River. Its director, whom he
did not identify, will report directly to the assistant secretary
for defense programs at department headquarters.
   The director will be charged with keeping headquarters informed
of all matters relating to the restart of Savannah River's nuclear
reactors, which are being overhauled.
   Watkins also said the manager of the existing department office
at Savannah River would report to the assistant secretary for
defense instead of to a headquarters official who is not directly
responsible for defense programs.
   ``Establishment of direct line management responsibility is
essential to assure the successful accomplishment of major DOE
programs, including the Savannah River restart effort,'' Watkins
said in a written statement.
   The three Savannah River reactors, which make a gas used in
nuclear warheads, have been shut down for safety reasons since last
spring. Watkins has said he intends to get them running again by
early next year.
</TEXT>
