<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Reported Killed in Army-Peasant Clash</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Two peasants were killed and nine
homes destroyed in confrontations with soldiers during a land
dispute in northern Haiti, radio stations reported Friday.
   Radio Haiti Inter said soldiers trying to settle a disagreement
over land in Grand Bois, 50 miles north of the capital, fought with
rock-throwing peasants Tuesday, killing a youth named Regis Charlo
and wounding three people.
   It said the soldiers had responded to a call for help from
Charite Joseph, an alleged member of the former Duvalier family
dictatorship's Tontons Macoutes militia, who was involved in the
dispute.
   The station said peasants retaliated by beheading Joseph's
mother, Ginette Dor, with a machete and burning down three houses
belonging to a local sheriff.
   On Wednesday, 30 soldiers from the garrison in nearby St. Marc
went to Grand Bois and burned down six houses belonging to
peasants, the reports said.
   Radio Soleil, the Roman Catholic station, said Joseph inherited
the land from Zacharie Delva, an infamous voodoo priest and
spiritual adviser to Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier, who ruled
Haiti from 1957 until his death in 1971.
   Peasants have disputed Joseph's title to the land since the
family dictatorship ended with the flight of President Jean-Claude
Duvalier, the dictator's son, in February 1986.
