<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers     05-19 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Continue in L.A. Teachers Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of at least 22,000 striking
teachers and school officials negotiated for a second day Friday as
the first week of the walkout ended with high absenteeism and
wasted cafeteria food.
   Only 259,120 students in the nation's second largest school
district came to class Friday out of a total enrollment of 551,759,
said district spokesman Shel Erlich. The week started with 329,000
students reporting.
   A total of 11,113 credentialed teachers showed up Friday,
including 8,660 regular teachers and 2,453 substitutes. Normally
there are 26,250 teachers.
   The United Teachers-Los Angeles union and the Los Angeles
Unified School District continued talks under a news blackout
imposed by a state mediator.
   ``At this point I'm cautiously optimistic that maybe we can move
forward. I hope those hopes are not dashed this afternoon at the
meeting,'' said UTLA President Wayne Johnson at a downtown rally
that drew about 2,000 strikers.
   With student attendance nearly cut in half, cafeteria workers
face a nearly impossible game of guessing how much food to prepare
each day. The result has been considerable waste.
   Only 112 of the district's 573 school kitchens have signed up
for a program to donate unused food to various agencies, said Carol
Noelting, deputy director of the food services branch.
   ``We did another mailing to the schools recently, to see if we
could drum up more business,'' she said.
   The UTLA represents 22,000 of the district's 32,000 teachers,
counselors, nurses and librarians.
   Some strikers have applied in the adjacent districts of
Alhambra, Arcadia, La Canada, and South Pasadena, but none have
been hired.
   Since the disclosure Wednesday that the state will enjoy a $2.5
billion tax surplus over the next two years, several wage offers
have been made.
   Johnson said he was confident some of the surplus would go to
the Los Angeles school district under Proposition 98, which
designates for public schools virtually all surplus funds above a
certain expenditure limit.
   He said the union would like a three-year contract with a 26
percent raise, including a 10 percent raise the first year.
   The district said it could not sweeten its 21.5 percent offer
over three years until it was sure it had the funds, but offered a
contingency wage package of 24 percent over three years if it did
receive some of the money.
   The strike is the district's first since a 23-day walkout in
1970.
   Currently, teachers annually earn from $23,440 in beginning pay
to $43,319 to those with doctorates, 98 extra course units and 19
years' experience.
   Administrators' salaries start at $37,000 for program
coordinators and $95,600 for associate superintendents. Britton
earns $141,000 as superintendent.
</TEXT>
