<FIRST>r a AM-TelevisedManhunt     05-19 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Televised Manhunt,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fugitive In Medicaid Fraud Waives Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive captured in Arizona after his case
was depicted on the national TV program ``Unsolved Mysteries''
waived extradition Friday to New York, where he will go to prison
for a $16 million Medicaid fraud.
   Sheldon Weinberg, 64, was being returned to New York by agents
of the state special prosecutor for nursing homes, health and
social services, authorities said.
   Weinberg was arrested Wednesday night in Scottsdale, Ariz., just
hours after his case was detailed on the NBC program. Hundreds of
viewers phoned in tips, and a caller gave the FBI Weinberg's alias
and address at a garden-apartment complex.
   Weinberg and his two sons were convicted Nov. 30, 1988, of
defrauding the health care program of more than $16 million from
1980 to 1987, which was the largest such theft in the 22 years of
the Medicaid program.
   Weinberg, free on $250,000 bail, didn't show up at his Jan. 10
sentencing, prompting a nationwide manhunt. He was sentenced in
absentia to seven to 21 years in prison, and will have to serve
that term in addition to any sentence imposed for fleeing justice.
   Deputy Attorney General Edward J. Kuriansky, the special
prosecutor, said Weinberg used money from false Medicaid billings
to finance an $18,000-a-month apartment in Manhattan's Trump Tower,
a $5 million lakefront mansion in Boca Raton, Fla., yachts and a
fleet of custom cars.
   Medicaid is a government program to pay for health care for poor
people.
</TEXT>
