<FIRST>u w AM-US-Angola     05-19 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Official Sees Some Hope for Angola Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An eight-nation African summit meeting this
week has produced the first hopes of a greater willingness by the
Angolan government to enter into serious peace negotiations with
U.S.-backed rebels, a Bush administration official said Friday.
   But a representative of the rebel group here said he saw no
change in the Angolan government's position.
   Although details of the meeting remain sketchy, the U.S.
official said Angolan President Eduardo Dos Santos for the first
time expressed support for the concept of ``reconciliation'' with
the UNITA rebels.
   ``Reconciliation can only come in the context of negotiation,''
said the official, asking not to be identified. He noted that
Angola's Marxist government has steadfastly refused to engage in
such talks with the anti-communist insurgents.
   UNITA's longstanding policy has been to promote negotiations
leading to national reconciliation and ultimately to free,
multi-party elections.
   The summit meeting, held last Tuesday in the Angolan capital of
Luanda, marked a departure from the Angolan government's prior
insistence that neighboring countries not have a role in seeking a
solution to the country's destructive, 14-year-old civil war.
   At one point, the official, speaking to a small group of
reporters, alluded to the possibility of a ``breakthrough'' in the
Angola deadlock but acknowledged that State Department information
on the details of the Angolan government's position was thin.
   Last December, the United States brokered an agreement that
calls for independence and black majority rule in Namibia coupled
with the withdrawal of Cuban forces in Angola over a 27-month
period.
   U.S. officials have been encouraging Angola to open serious
negotiations with UNITA sooner rather than later because the
country's negotiating position will weaken as the number of Cuban
troops declines.
   According to official estimates, the Cuban presence has dropped
by about 8,000 since the agreement was signed five months ago. The
total now is believed to be about 44,000.
   Apprised of the U.S. official's position, a local UNITA
representative, Jardo Mukeilia said, ``I don't necessarily share
his optimism.''
   The Angolan government is still insisting the UNITA rebels lay
down their arms and then reintegrate into Angolan society as part
of a national reconstruction effort, he said.
   He added that Dos Santos referred to ``reconciliation in the
context of amnesty and clemency,'' and not as the result of a
negotiating process.
   In addition to Angola, the nations attending the Luanda meeting
were Zambia, Zimbabwe, Zaire, the Congo, Gabon, Mozambique and Sao
Tome y Principe.
</TEXT>
