<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     05-19 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independence Plan for Namibia to Proceed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostilities have ceased between
South African troops and guerrillas, clearing the way for the
independence plan for Namibia to proceed, a three-nation commission
said Friday.
   Representatives of South Africa, Angola and Cuba, joined by
Soviet and American observers, said they had received confirmation
``that South African forces were again confined to base and that a
de facto cessation of hostilities existed in the northern area of
Namibia.''
   The statement, issued at a meeting in Cahama, Angola, said,
``additional measures to avoid further interruption of the peace
process'' were discussed.
   It said Angola and the U.N. Transition Assistance Group informed
the commission that guerrillas of the South-West African People's
Organization in Angola ``were confined to bases north of the 16th
parallel under UNTAG monitoring.''
   The commission recommended resumption of the U.N.-sponsored plan
to have elections in Namibia, also known as South-West Africa, in
November.
   The independence process was interrupted April 1, the day it
started, when South Africa reported hundreds of guerrillas had
crossed into Namibia from Angola. Namibian officials said 316
guerrillas and 27 security force members were killed in the
fighting as South African troops left their bases to engage the
rebels.
   SWAPO leaders recalled their guerrillas to Angola, but South
Africa demanded assurances that they would be restricted to their
bases.
   That assurance was given Friday by Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N.
special representative for Namibia, and Louis Pienaar, the South
African-appointed territorial administrator who will run Namibia
until a new government is installed.
   Under the U.N. plan the guerrillas and thousands of other
Namibians who fled the territory during the rebels' 23-year battle
for independence will be allowed to return, unarmed, to participate
in the elections.
   Angola, South Africa and Cuba reached agreement late last year
on the independence accord that includes the withdrawal of Cuban
troops in Angola to support the Marxist government.
   South Africa has administered Namibia since World War I.
</TEXT>
