<HEAD>Omaha Credit Union Chief Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf to UPDATE with Kings released
without bail, given court date.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manager of a credit union accused of
diverting as much as $39 million in funds to his own use was
arrested Friday on charges of fraud and violation of federal income
tax laws.
   Lawrence E. King, 44, was charged in a 40-count federal
indictment before U.S. Magistrate Richard Kopf. King's wife, Alice,
was also arrested on charges of violating federal income tax law.
   Both were released without bond and ordered to report to court
May 23.
   The National Credit Union Administration shut down Franklin
Community Federal Credit Union in November, alleging in civil
lawsuits that as much as $39 million was missing from its coffers
and accusing King of taking the money.
   Losses at the credit union were estimated Friday at $41.8
million.
   King, 44, who is black, has denied any wrongdoing and said he is
the victim of racial discrimination.
   The indictment opened Friday named King in on charges of
conspiracy, mail fraud, wire fraud, bank fraud, credit union
embezzlement, making false entries in credit union records and
filing false tax returns.
   The indictment accused Mrs. King, 42, of 12 counts for alleged
conspiracy, wire fraud and bank fraud.
   Also indicted were Noel Seltzer, Larry J. Murphy and Robert
Morley, all former development officers of the credit union and the
Consumer Services Organization, of which King was president.
   All three were charged with two counts each of filing false tax
returns, and Morley additionally was charged with one count of
perjury before the federal grand jury.
   The Omaha World-Herald said among those who testified before the
grand jury was E. Thomas Harvey Jr., who supervised Franklin's
accounting department. Harvey was not named in the indictment.
</TEXT>
