<SECOND>AM-Marcos, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0708,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Remains Very Critical But Responding To Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0759 to CORRECT writethru sequence; SUBS grafs
4-5, `Imelda Marcos ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Mrs.
Marcos, spokesman; picks up 6th graf: `Marcos has ...; INSERTS 1 graf after
12th graf pvs: ``Much as . .., with Mrs. Marcos' comment on prospects of
return to homeland.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines-Marcos, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HU2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos was
said to be responding to treatment Friday for kidney, heart and
lung failure, pneumonia and bacterial infections but hospital
officials said he remained in critical condition.
   ``His condition is episodic,'' said Gene Tiwanak, assistant
administrator of St. Francis Medical Center. ``It rises and falls,
and in this case he is rallying.''
   Marcos remained on kidney dialysis and a respirator in the
hospital's intensive care unit, and is drifting in and out of
consciousness, Tiwanak said. His prognosis is still very poor, he
said.
   ``It is very serious, but he's hanging on,'' Imelda Marcos, wife
of the 71-year-old deposed leader, told reporters with a smile as
she arrived at the hospital Friday afternoon and was escorted into
the hospital chapel.
   Earlier in the day, Mrs. Marcos told reporters that her
husband's fever was rising, and she said in a telephone interview
from her home that doctors fear for Marcos' life and that he could
``go any time.''
   However, a hospital source who spoke on condition of anonymity
told The Associated Press that Marcos was responding to treatment.
   Art Aruiza, a top Marcos aide, said Marcos was sleeping most of
the time and ``is better, well, not as bad as it was yesterday.''
   Marcos has been hospitalized for more than four months but his
condition worsened this week.
   He was lapsing in and out of consciousness following a surgical
procedure Thursday to prepare him for kidney dialysis, said Dr.
Azucena Ignacio, one of Marcos' attending physicians.
   Mrs. Marcos was at the hospital early Friday but returned home.
She planned to return later in the day.
   Marcos' son, Ferdinand Jr., and sister, Fortuna Barba, also were
at the hospital. The couple's daughter, Irene Araneta, was heading
to Hawaii on Friday from her home in Woodside, Calif., said Joe
Lazo, a family friend.
   Mrs. Marcos made a public appeal to Philippine President Corazon
Aquino to allow Marcos to return to his homeland to die.
   Mrs. Aquino said she would not allow Marcos to return and would
not permit him to be buried on Philippine soil, out of concern his
presence would spark unrest.
   ``Much as I agree that Mr. Marcos has his rights, I still have
to consider also the rights and interests of millions of
Filipinos,'' said Mrs. Aquino, who succeeded Marcos following a
popular uprising in February 1986.
   ``I'm confident that sooner or later, the Filipino people will
allow him to come home because there is no reason not to,'' said
Mrs. Marcos when she emerged from the hospital chapel, clutching a
rosary in her hands.
   Tomas ``Buddy'' Gomez, Philippine consul general in Honolulu,
acknowledged that Marcos is ill, but said reports on his condition
have been exaggerated.
   ``There is an obvious element of exaggeration and orchestration
here,'' he said.
   Report of Marcos' condition were released in Manila by a
pro-Marcos radio station before the hospital released information
in Honolulu, Gomez said.
   Marcos has been hospitalized since Jan. 15. He was returned to
the intensive care unit on Monday and lapsed into critical
condition Tuesday. It was the third time he had been hospitalized
since early December.
   The Marcoses are under federal indictment, accused of stealing
more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury to buy art and
real estate in New York. In April a judge ruled that Marcos was too
ill to stand trial, but Mrs. Marcos remains charged. She is free on
$5 million bail.
   The couple have lived in exile in Hawaii since fleeing the
Philippines in February 1986.
</TEXT>
