<FIRST>r a AM-StealthCritic     05-19 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Critic,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Defense Official Says Stealth Program Should End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon's former chief of procurement
said he argued unsuccessfully to end the B-2 stealth bomber program
because of rising cost and concerns about quality and management.
   ``I have serious and grave concerns,'' said Robert B. Costello,
who last week stepped down from his Pentagon post. ``The quality
issues on the B-2 are a significant concern to me.''
   However, he said, the Joint Chiefs of Staff insisted the B-2 was
the only program that could penetrate Soviet air defenses and put
targets at risk.
   He also said he had more than one heated meeting with Thomas V.
Jones, chairman of Los Angeles-based Northrop Corp., the plane's
principal contractor. Costello, former undersecretary of
acquisitions, said that Northrop's quality controls on development
and production of the planes is ``terrible,'' The Washington Post
reported in its Friday editions.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Deputy Secretary of Defense
Donald Atwood are scheduled to visit Northrop next Friday to
examine the bomber.
   Jones and other Northrop officials vigorously defend the bomber.
Jones has called it ``an extraordinary new aircraft system.''
   The Northrop chairman told his company's annual shareholders
meeting Wednesday that the B-2's ``unprecedented technical
successes'' will eventually be realized.
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci fought efforts by
Costello to kill the program, the Post said. But his successor,
Cheney, has delayed full-scale production of the bomber by a year
and critics are calling for a longer delay to allow more time for
testing.
   Its first flight is scheduled for this summer, about 18 months
behind schedule.
   Unidentified members of Costello's staff told the Los Angeles
Times that a confidential internal cost analysis shows the price
for the bombers has soared to $750 million per aircraft, the
newspaper reported Friday.
   Jones estimated the cost at $265 million per plane, a price that
does not include research and development costs, future inflation
and ground equipment.
   The stealth bomber is Northrop's most important program,
accounting for 51 percent of the company's revenue. It is being
built at Northrop plants in Pico Rivera and Palmdale.
</TEXT>
