<HEAD>Doctor Who Arranged Boy for Steinberg Loses License</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Peter J. ..., to CORRECT that Lisa was illegally,
sted legally, adopted.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The doctor who arranged for a baby boy to be
given to Joel Steinberg and who pleaded guilty to illegally placing
a baby for adoption lost his state medical license Friday.
   Peter J. Sarosi's license was revoked because of his role in
placing the boy with Steinberg, who was convicted of manslaughter
in the death of another illegally adopted child, 6-year-old Lisa,
said Emlyn Griffith, chairman of the sttate Board of Regents'
Committee on Professional Practice.
   The board, which oversees professional licensing in the state,
voted 14-0 to revoke Sarosi's license, Griffith said.
   Sarosi, 36, may apply for reinstatement after one year. He did
not return calls, but a woman in his office said he has been seeing
patients all week.
   The doctor pleaded guilty in January to ``illegally placing a
child out for adoption,'' a misdemeanor punishable by up to a year
in jail. He admitted he delivered a boy born June 21, 1986, to
Nicole Smigiel, an unwed Long Island teen-ager, and illegally gave
the infant to Steinberg two days later.
   In sentencing Sarosi, Criminal Court Judge John Stackhouse
called him a ``highly respected and beloved physician.'' He put him
on three years probation, ordered him to do 100 hours of community
service, and fined him $1,000.
   Sarosi was gynecologist and fertility doctor for Hedda Nussabum,
Steinberg's live-in companion. She testified at Steinberg's trial
for Lisa's death that she had trouble conceiving so Steinberg
arranged with Sarosi to get a baby boy.
   The boy, called ``Mitchell'' by Steinberg, was found tied to a
playpen, drinking spoiled milk and wearing a soiled diaper when
police and paramedics arrived at Steinberg's apartment Nov. 5,
1987, to find Lisa unconscious.
   The toddler was returned to his mother and renamed Travis
Christian Smigiel. Lisa died a few days later of injuries the jury
decided were inflicted by Steinberg.
</TEXT>
