<HEAD>Hustler Cartoonist Arrested on Molestation Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cartoonist who draws a Hustler
magazine comic feature titled ``Chester the Molester'' was arrested
for investigation of molesting a teen-age girl, police said Friday.
   Police arrested Dwaine Tinsley, 43, at his home Thursday after
the girl told officers that she had been sexually molested, said
Lt. Bob Klamser. He declined to give the victim's age, although he
said she allegedly was molested for several years.
   The girl talked to police Wednesday. By Thursday, officers had a
search warrant and arrested Tinsley and searched his home in this
city about 40 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
   Klamser refused to talk about the search or say what evidence,
if any, had been seized.
   Tinsley was booked for investigation of child molestation and
bail was set at $100,000. He remained in custody Friday afternoon
and arraignment was scheduled for Monday.
   Tinsley has worked as cartoon and humor editor for LSP Inc., the
parent company of Hustler magazine and other publications, said
editorial director Tim Conaway.
   Conaway confirmed that Tinsley draws the ``Chester the
Molester'' cartoon, which depicts a lecherous character and his
attraction to young girls.
   Hustler is the sexually explicit magazine founded by
controversial publisher Larry Flynt.
