<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 2331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Grandmother'sPlea     05-19 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grandmother's Plea,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Picketing Grandmother Gets Help from NAACP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 80-year-old woman who has been picketing
in front of a courthouse for two years won the support of the local
NAACP chapter Friday in her bid to free her grandson from prison.
   Morgan Miller, 31, has been in prison for five years for an
armed robbery he contends he did not commit, and his case should be
reopened, said Lee Williams, local director of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Williams said he has read transcripts of the trial and looked
into the case. He said he was ``appalled'' at the number of
inconsistencies, including the fact that another man had confessed
to the robbery.
   ``This case was pushed through the court system without regard
to the facts. The system needs to right itself. I'm really
convinced he's innocent,'' Williams said.
   Williams said he has asked the national organization to
investigate the case and to hire Charles Carter, a lawyer who
helped free Lenell Jeter from a Texas jail. Jeter, a computer
programmer, was wrongly convicted of robbing a fast-food
restaurant, a judge ruled.
   Williams said the Miller case was brought to his attention by
Reaber Brown, who has been picketing twice a week for two years in
front of the Lucas County Courthouse. Ms. Brown sold her house to
pay for her grandson's legal fees.
   Lucas County Prosecutor Anthony Pizza said his office ``welcomes
anybody to look at the facts of the case. We have no problems with
that.''
   ``I feel sorry for his grandmother, but I commend her for her
persistence,'' Pizza said. ``But there isn't much more that can be
done at this point.''
   Miller was convicted of aggravated robbery and assault in 1984
in connection with the Dec. 14, 1983, robbery of a fast-food
restaurant in which a Toledo police officer was shot and wounded.
   Miller was sentenced to 20 to 40 years in prison and is in the
Lebanon Correctional Institution.
   Williams said a number of points were ignored during the trial.
He said Miller, a professional musician, had no police record.
   Miller is physicially similar to Joseph Clark, who allegedly
confessed to the holdup. Clark is on death row for two murders.
   Miller was identified by a witness from a group of men in which
he was the only black.
   Miller also said he was at the restaurant with a friend, who was
home on leave from the Navy, earlier the night it was robbed. When
Miller went on trial, the friend was supposed to testify, but did
not receive notice about the trial until several days after it had
ended.
   Pizza said Clark confessed to the holdup and later recanted the
story.
   According to an affidavit obtained by The Associated Press, two
prisoners who were in the same Lucas County jail cell with Clark on
April 24, 1984, said Clark bragged about several fast-food
restaurant robberies and shooting a Toledo police officer. The men
said one of the robberies was the one in which Miller was convicted.
   The 6th Ohio District Court of Appeals has upheld Miller's
conviction. Williams said he would want Miller to be retried or
Gov. Richard Celeste to grant Miller clemency.
   ``This young man has had a means of living and had not been in
trouble before. He became a victim of the system. We want to
correct that. He should not be in jail,'' Williams said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
