<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0802 05-19 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0802,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Huddles with Military Advisers on NATO Summit, Soviet Arms Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 5th graf to correct spelling of ``Danielle.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Germany Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush met with top military
advisers at his seaside home Friday to review plans for a NATO
summit threatened by discord and to discuss strategy for arms talks
with the Soviet Union.
   As talks were under way in Washington to ease the NATO crisis,
Bush met at his vacation retreat with Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney, Joint Chiefs Chairman Adm. William Crowe, national security
adviser Brent Scowcroft and other aides. White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said no final decisions would be
announced Friday from the meeting.
   Under cloudy skies and in chilly weather, Bush and his advisers
posed for pictures in front of the wind-swept sea wall near his
home but did not comment on their talks.
   The session came on the eve of the arrival here of French
President Francois Mitterrand, who generally backs Bush on the NATO
dispute.
   Mitterrand and his wife Danielle will spend the night in a guest
home on Bush's compound, located on a rocky point jutting out into
the Atlantic Ocean.
   NATO's harmony has been shaken by a dispute largely between the
United States and West Germany.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, facing domestic pressure for
disarmament, has called for East-West negotiations soon on reducing
short-range nuclear weapons.
   Bush has rejected the idea, arguing Western Europe needs the
weapons to compensate for the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact's large
advantage in troops, tanks and other conventional forces.
   ``The SNF (short-range nuclear forces) issue of course is one
that's under consideration right now and is driving the meeting''
of Bush and his advisers, Fitzwater said.
   He said he did not know if a compromise could be struck before
the NATO meeting opening May 29.
   In Washington, Secretary of State James A. Baker III held a
second day of talks with West Germany defense minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg to try to resolve the dispute.
   Baker flew to Kennebunkport and joined Bush, Scowcroft and John
Curley, the U.S. ambassador to France, for a game of golf. Mugging
for cameras on the 18th hole, Bush admonished photographers to be
quiet.
   As the president prepared to swing, a baby cried. Bush stopped
and theatrically said, ``Please, this is very important. We're two
down.''
   White House chief of staff John Sununu also was to fly here
Friday.
   The West Germans also oppose a U.S.-British effort to more than
triple the range of existing Lance missiles to just below 300
miles. The aging, U.S.-built Lance now can hit targets from about
75 miles, and most of the 88 launchers and 700 single-warhead
missiles are based in West Germany.
   Mitterrand, at a news conference Thursday before leaving Paris,
spoke out against elimination of the short-range nuclear weapons
but said NATO did not have to decide about modernizing the weapons
until 1992.
   Fitzwater denied that Mitterand's comments urging a go-slow
approach on modernizing NATO's nuclear forces were in conflict with
the U.S. stance.
   ``President Mitterrand's comments yesterday indicate that his
position is very similar to ours. (He) shares our general concern
about the strength of the NATO alliance,'' Fitzwater said.
   Aside from the NATO flap, Bush and the military advisors
discussed details of a defense strategy review dealing with
strategic nuclear weapons and arms control.
   Fitzwater said Bush would disclose some findings of the review
in a speech Wednesday at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy. ``And so
they need to make some ... final judgments before that address
occurs,'' he said.
   The review also will put in place the groundwork for the
resumption of strategic arms talks between the United States and
Soviet Union.
   Fitzwater also brushed aside reports that Mitterrand's party was
unhappy with his accommodations in Kennebunkport.
   ``As far as I know, the accommodations are satisfactory to the
French delegation. The discussions of accommodations have gone
quite well. We don't have any problems,'' he said.
   The New York Daily News quoted unidentified sources as saying
Mitterrand was unhappy with the size of the bed and the height of
the toilet in the house where he'll say. The house, owned by Bush's
mother, Dorothy Walker Bush, is next to the president's home.
   The article also said that Barbara Bush was upset about the
Mitterrand's visit, claiming it to be disruptive.
   Fitzwater said the Bushes had decided to restrict press coverage
of the Mitterrand visit within the oceanside compound.
   ``The family feels their home is their private residence and
should not be used for publicity purposes. They want to keep it
personal, and I think that's reasonable,'' he said.
   Bush plans to travel to Greenwich, Conn., on Sunday to visit his
ailing 87-year-old mother, a White House aide said Friday.
   ``He's just coming in to see her, and then he's leaving,'' said
John Meserve, the press aide.
   The president's mother was released from Greenwich Hospital May
11 after four days of treatment for a blood clot in her right leg,
the hospital said.
</TEXT>
