<FIRST>a i AM-Canada-Chinese Adv23   05-19 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Chinese, Adv 23,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, May 23 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Concern About Racism Follows Surge in Hong Kong Investment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears that Hong Kong
investors and immigrants will change the placid ways of this scenic
Pacific city have surged into the open with charges of racism not
far behind.
   Mayor Gordon Campbell, who is sponsoring a series of public
forums intended to calm the escalating controversy, said people are
looking for an easy way to explain the rapid changes tied to the
city's growth.
   ``I think there's no question that people are concerned,'' he
said in an interview. ``I think the fears are real ... so let's
shine the light on them.''
   Soaring housing prices and high profile projects in commercial
real estate in the past year have made Asian, specifically Hong
Kong, investment the hottest topic in the area.
   The local newspapers are devoting full pages to letters to the
editor about the issue.
   ``Native Vancouverites will be made to feel like strangers in
their own city as the influx of Asians and their capital freezes
them out,'' wrote one reader to The Province.
   ``This is a golden opportunity to absorb investment and skilled
professionals,'' said another on the same page. ``It is of
paramount importance that British Columbia not just become a
prosperous province, but also maintain a harmonious multicultural
environment for all its inhabitants, old and new.''
   The debate covers a wide range, including the increasing number
of Asian children in neighborhood schools.
   Perhaps no project has attracted as much attention as the $1.6
billion Pacific Place project on the False Creek downtown
waterfront lands where Expo '86 attracted attention to the city.
   Li Ka-Shing, the Hong Kong magnate who is the project's major
financier, purchased the lands from the city for the Canadian
dollar equivalent of $269 million. The government must bear the
substantial cost of removing industrial waste from the site.
   ``There's an old Chinese saying that a big tree gathers the
wind,'' Stanley Kwok, a senior vice president of Concord Pacific
Developments Ltd., said in explaining the attention paid his
company's massive project.
   ``Wherever there's change, one thing will stand out,'' said
Kwok, who has been in Vancouver for 21 years. ``Just like any North
American neighborhood, nobody wants change.''
   About 20 percent of the Vancouver area population of 1.2 million
is of Chinese origin, many of them people whose families have been
in Canada for generations.
   The External Affairs Department in Ottawa has estimated that
investment from Hong Kong will increase sharply to $3.3 billion in
Canada this year from $2 billion in 1988.
   Always in the equation is 1997 when control of Hong Kong goes
back to China from Britain.
   Racism, Mayor Campbell said, ``gets to be a very quick answer.
That's wrong.''
   The heated housing market that sent the average price of a
Vancouver home up by some 45 percent to $181,282 at the end of
March from $127,344 has been hard for Vancouver residents to ignore.
   ``The supply and demand got out of balance, and there was a
major price correction upward,'' said Jerry Jackman, senior vice
president for residential real estate for the large Royal LePage
realtors. ``The finger seemed to be pointed at the Asian investor .
.. and they were absolutely not the culprit.''
   Victor Li, son of Li Ka-shing and another senior vice president
at Concord Pacific, set off a furor in December when he put 216
Vancouver condominiums on sale in Hong Kong without offering them
first in Canada.
   Most sold within hours. Li has promised that it won't happen
again.
   T-shirts started circulating, however, that read: ``Hongcouver,
B.C. `89.'' A charge that they were racist led to them being pulled
off the market.
   Graham Johnson, a sociologist at the University of British
Columbia who has studied Chinese migration extensively, said racism
has been a constant problem in the region since the first Chinese
arrived in 1858 but has boiled over in the past year.
   ``What you have going on is a degree of scapegoating,'' he said.
   Johnson said the change has been the movement of Chinese
immigrants out of traditional ethnic neighborhoods to the affluent
West Side, where the tearing down of modest older properties and
replacement by huge homes became a noticeable trend.
   Johnson said the number of Chinese immigrants has not increased
sharply over past periods, with an estimated 5,000 last year, but
the arrival of affluent immigrants has not taken place to this
extent before.
   ``All of this raises a lot of hackles,'' he said. ``One doesn't
see a very swift solution to some of the problems that we
identify.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, May 23</NOTE>
