<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-19 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0838</SECOND>
<DATELINE>PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl
rejected a call for his resignation but assured shareholders that
he and other Exxon management would be part of major policy changes
at the company, including random drug testing.
   Rawl told about 1,700 Exxon shareholders attending the first
annual meeting since the March 24 spill by the tanker Exxon Valdez
the company would begin random drug testing of all employees,
``including me.''
   He also repeated on Thursday his apologies for the disaster and
pledged to clean up the fouled waters and beaches on Alaska's
Prince William Sound.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission took a
critical step toward commercial operation of the $6 billion
Seabrook, N.H., nuclear plant, approving a license for low-power
testing of the reactor.
   The commission immediately froze the license on Thursday to give
a federal appeals court seven days to rule on a request by
opponents for an emergency stay pending further legal review.
   It was an important milestone for a plant that is already a
decade behind schedule and billions over budget.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David S. Ruder resigned as chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission after guiding the agency through
two tumultuous years that included the worst stock crash in history
and an unprecedented probe of Wall Street corruption.
   In a letter to President Bush, Ruder said Thursday he planned to
return to teaching at Northwestern University School of Law at the
end of August. He left there in August 1987 to head the SEC, which
regulates the nation's financial markets and oversees disclosure
requirements for U.S. publicly traded corporations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal examiners discovered new evidence of
fraud in nearly one in four of the 219 savings institutions taken
over by the government so far this year, regulators told the Bush
administration.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., in a report released
Thursday, said that since beginning the takeover of the nation's
most deeply insolvent S&amp;Ls on Feb. 7, its examiners have uncovered
potential criminal violations in about 50 institutions and referred
the cases to the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. may have abandoned a takeover
pursuit of Avon Products Inc. because it concluded uniting the two
companies would be a stormy marriage, Avon's Chairman James E.
Preston said.
   Preston also reaffirmed Thursday his conviction that Avon
shareholders and sales representatives will be far better off if
Avon remains independent, permitting management to carry out
current plans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said it has agreed to acquire
Thrifty-Rent-A-Car Systems Inc. for $263 million, becoming the last
of the Big Three automakers to take a stake in the rental car
business.
   The agreement, announced Thursday by Chrysler Chairman Lee
Iacocca during the company's annual meeting in San Francisco, calls
for Chrysler to pay $27.75 a share for all of the Tulsa,
Okla.-based Thrifty's stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burger King's new management moved to turn around
years of erratic advertising results by selecting two new agencies
to handle the major portion of its $215 million advertising and
marketing account.
   D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles of New York will concentrate on
reinforcing brand identity, while Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Advertising of
New York will concentrate on day-to-day brand retailing, Burger
King said Thursday.
   The agencies replace N.W. Ayer, the New York-based ad agency
hired 20 months ago that created the ``We do it like you'd do it''
theme Burger King began using in January 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said it
will order airlines to strengthen and replace parts on aging Boeing
jetliners _ at a cost of millions of dollars and tens of thousands
of man hours _ but would give the airlines four years to finish the
work.
   With the average age of U.S. jetliners climbing to nearly 13
years, the FAA proposed Thursday a series of ``airworthiness
directives'' altering the government's approach to ensuring the
safety of older airliners.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that pioneered all-music programming
on cable television in the early 1980s plans to launch a cable
channel devoted to comedy programming early next year.
   The service from MTV Networks, a unit of Viacom Inc., would
compete with one from Home Box Office unit of Time Inc., which
disclosed earlier this week it expects to start the first
all-comedy cable network this fall.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead to a new post-crash high Thursday
as the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.69 to 2,470.12.
   The price of long-term government bonds advanced. The dollar
sagged, falling under pressure by the central banks.
   Precious metals futures prices fell sharply, grain and soybeans
were mixed, livestock and meat prices settled mostly lower and
energy futures were mostly higher.
</TEXT>
