<DOCNO> AP890519-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-Preston     05-19 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Preston,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Chief Suggests Why Amway Slammed Door on Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY37 of May 18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP Business Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. may have gotten cold feet about
pursuing a takeover of Avon Products Inc. because it decided the
two direct-sales companies wouldn't be a good match, suggests
Avon's Chairman James E. Preston.
   Preston also says he is convinced Avon shareholders and sales
representatives will be better off if Avon remains independent,
permitting management to carry out current plans.
   However, Avon's stock plunged $7.12{ a share to $33 in heavy New
York Stock Exchange Trading Thursday, a day after Amway withdrew
its $2.1 billion bid.
   During an interview Thursday, Preston said Amway's decision to
withdraw the $39-a-share takeover proposal hours after Avon's board
unanimously rejected the offer, may have been prompted by second
thoughts about the feasibility of joining the two companies.
   Preston supplied copies of letters sent to him by sales reps
disturbed by the prospect of having Amway as a corporate parent.
   Several of the letters were addressed to Amway's co-founders
Richard DeVos and Jay Van Andel and denounced the way Amway
distributors do business. Van Andel is chairman of the privately
held company and DeVos is president.
   One of the correspondents, Avon representative Constance M.
Wendt of Jacksonville, Fla., told the Amway executives: ``Our
prayers are for a continued strong, united family _ the Avon family
and Avon traditions known to our loyal consumers for the past 104
years of service ...''
   The letters were described by Preston as just a sample of the
huge amount of correspondence Avon received since Amway, an Ada,
Mich.-based direct-selling concern, started making takeover
advances.
   Amway's statement that it would operate its own distributor
network separately from Avon's direct-sales business if it
prevailed in its takeover attempt apparently did not alleviate the
concerns, Preston said.
   In a survey Avon conducted, nearly half of Avon's sales reps,
which operate independently and aren't Avon employees, said they
would cease selling for Avon if Amway acquired control of the
company.
   Preston said Avon's worldwide image as a beauty products company
would be impaired by a linkage with Amway.
   Meanwhile, Preston said Avon will step up efforts to improve its
balance sheet. The emphasis will be placed on reducing costs, which
have been averaging 53 percent of sales. The goal is to shave the
percentage to 47 percent by 1990.
   As an example of where costs would be trimmed, he said the use
of ``premiums'' to attract customers would be scaled back or
discontinued in Avon's direct-selling operation. These premiums are
items that companies give away to customers when they make a
purchase, such as a free tote bag for buying a certain amount of
makeup.
   He said any possible expansion of Avon's lines will be aimed at
complimenting the company's primary focus on beauty products.
``People don't want to buy their fragrance from a company that
sells dog food or toilet brushes,'' he said.
   In a letter to shareholders Thursday, Avon forecasted sales from
direct selling will grow by 7 percent to 8 percent this year.
   Sales in its retail operation, which consists of some of the
country's top-selling fragrances such as Giogio and Red, will grow
faster. These Avon scents are sold at department stores and other
retail outlets, not by Avon's independent sales force.
   Preston said in the interview that numerous parties, which he
did not name, have expressed interest in acquiring Avon's retail
fragrance business. Amway said it would have sold it off if it took
over Avon.
   Preston, who also is Avon's chief executive officer, said he is
thrilled by the strong performance of the prestige fragrance
business and has no intention of selling it.
   Avon has been restructuring and the process is to be completed
this year with the divestiture of its remaining businesses in the
health care services field. The company lost $404.5 million in 1988
due to losses on discontinued operations. Sales totaled $3.06
billion last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
