<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   05-19 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Union Says Future Trump Pilots Don't Have To Honor Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reversing their earlier position, pilots union
leaders at strike-torn Eastern Airlines said 170 Eastern pilots can
go to work for the company's Northeast shuttle if it is sold to
developer Donald Trump.
   The pilots, who already have been hired for the planned Trump
Shuttle, had said they planned to defy union leadership's earlier
position directing them not to work for Trump until the Eastern
strike was over.
   Trump's agreement to buy the business for $365 million from
Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. still must be approved by the
federal bankruptcy court.
   The Master Executive Council of the Air Line Pilots Association
at Eastern had asked its pilots not to work for Trump or receive
further training for the Trump shuttle as long as the strike
against Eastern continued.
   After a meeting Thursday with Trump Shuttle officials, the
pilots' leadership decided prospective Trump pilots would be
approved to start training, said Dan Ashby, a spokesman for ALPA in
New York.
   In an earlier message to pilots, Jack Bavis, the head of the
Eastern pilots union, had directed that ``no pilot, including those
who have accepted employment with the Trump Shuttle, will engage in
any training of any kind until the strike is over or until the
(Master Executive Council) endorses another course of action.''
   Eastern's unions have opposed a sale of the profitable New
York-Washington-Boston shuttle and other Eastern assets.
   The company has been in bankruptcy court protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a Machinists
union strike that was joined by Eastern's pilots and flight
attendants unions and virtually grounded the airline.
   In a letter dated May 2 to Henry Duffy, national president of
ALPA, pilot Bill Sanford said ``the Trump pilots have to question
whether the association is working toward our best interest at
Trump. If the (Master Executive Council) continues to interfere in
our business and ALPA continues to ignore us, then a reassessment
and further examination of our alternatives will obviously have to
be explored.''
   In recent weeks, other prospective Trump pilots have sent a
flurry of similar letters to Trump, Duffy and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland, who is overseeing Eastern's Chapter 11
proceeding. Copies of some of the letters were obtained by The
Associated Press.
   Trump Shuttle management already has signed labor agreements
with pilots and flight attendants.
   America West Airlines, which has made a competing, higher offer
for the shuttle, has said it mainly would use its own employees to
operate the service although Eastern workers would be eligible to
apply for jobs. America West, a regional carrier based in Phoenix,
Ariz., is non-union.
   The company has offered to pay $415 million for the Eastern
shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing 757s.
   In addition to the 170 Eastern pilots already hired, another 40
or so pilots have been hired for the Trump Shuttle from other
carriers and elsewhere. Before the strike, Eastern's shuttle was
its only profitable operation. Since then, it has been running
nearly at full schedule but with skimpy passenger loads as many
passengers have defected to Pan Am Corp.'s rival service.
   Eastern said earlier this week that its share of the shuttle
market, split with Pan Am, has dropped to around 23 percent from 53
percent in December of last year.
</TEXT>
