<FIRST>r f PM-ComedyNetwork     05-19 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comedy Network,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>MTV Plans to Launch New Comedy Network in Early 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable TV programmers are promising viewers yocks
around the clock with a pair of new all-comedy networks.
   MTV Networks, the Viacom Inc. subsidiary that pioneered
all-music programming on cable television in the early 1980s, said
Thursday it plans to launch a cable channel devoted to comedy
programming early next year.
   That service would compete with one from Home Box Office unit of
Time Inc., which disclosed earlier this week it expects to start
the first all-comedy cable network this fall.
   And there may be others. Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc.,
the movie and television programmer, reportedly is considering
starting a comedy channel with Cox Cable Communications, a cable
system operator based in Atlanta.
   David Andersen, spokesman for Cox Cable, said while Cox has
discussed the possibility of teaming up with Columbia Pictures on a
comedy channel, those discussions are ``very preliminary.''
   Columbia Pictures had no comment on the matter, a spokesman said.
   ``Nobody has a corner on the concept,'' said Larry Gerbrandt, an
analyst for Paul Kagan Associates, a media research firm based in
Carmel, Calif.
   But he said cable operators may find the concept appealing
because they need new programming services in their efforts to sign
up more subscribers.
   Rob Stengel, senior vice president for programming at
Continental Cablevision Inc. in Boston, said he hasn't seen
specifics on either proposed comedy channel but said the concept
``makes a lot of sense.''
   ``There is high-intensity consumer interest in comedy,'' he said.
   Continental Cablevision is the third-largest cable system
operator in the nation with about 2.5 million subscribers.
   Stengel said he is not certain many cable operators or
subscribers would be interested in a channel ``that is just a
dumping ground for a lot of old sitcoms or things that have been on
network TV.''
   But he said a service that offers ``new material, new concepts
and new forms'' of comedy could be a valuable addition to a
system's basic service.
   Both MTV Networks and Home Box Office plan to offer their comedy
channels as parts of the basic cable service rather than as a pay
service that customers would have to pay an extra fee to get. Both
channels will carry advertising.
   MTV Networks plans to call its comedy channel the ``HA TV Comedy
Network'' and said it has been developing it for 18 months.
   Tom Freston, chairman and chief executive of MTV Networks, said
he planned to offer cable operators and programmers a chance to buy
a stake in the service, a feature that he called ``a unique slant.''
   Barry Kluger, a spokesman for MTV Networks, said another
difference would be that HA TV Comedy would specialize in offering
longer programs such as original situation comedies and movies.
   Home Box Office's plans call for comedy hosts to make liberal
use of short clips from comedy shows, movies and performances in
their shows.
   Freston noted that MTV has gained a lot of experience over the
years with three basic cable services _ Nickelodeon launched in
1979, MTV: Music Television in 1981 and VH-1: Video Hits One in
1985.
   Home Box Office is the leading pay TV programer with its HBO and
Cinemax services.
</TEXT>
