<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     05-19 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Lower Against Yen, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved slightly lower against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo today, while stock prices rebounded.
   The dollar finished the week at 138.77 yen, down 0.11 yen from
Thursday's closing of 138.88 yen. After opening lower at 138.55
yen, the U.S. currency ranged between 138.15 and 138.90 yen during
the day.
   ``The dollar's rising momentum took a respite today,'' said
Noburu Yokohashi of the Foreign Exchange Fund Department at
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank.
   But Yokohashi predicted the dollar next week would approach the
140-yen level, which he said the market considers an important
psychological barrier.
   During morning trading, the Bank of Japan sold an estimated $400
million to support the yen, traders said. The nation's central bank
does not customarily comment on its market interventions.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Maruyama told a news conference today
there was ``no reason at the moment for Japan to change its
monetary stance,'' despite speculation the central bank may be on
the verge of hiking its official discount rate to counter the
rising dollar.
   Maruyama attributed the dollar's continued strength against the
yen to ``moves by speculators'' and said such activities must be
countered by intervention in currency markets.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which lost 136.12 points Thursday, gained 145.63 points or
0.43 percent to finish the week at 34,001.96. Volume on the first
section was an estimated 750 million shares, up from Thursday's 600
million.
   ``Trading on the stock market was inactive because of the lack
of fresh incentives and the approaching weekend holiday,'' said
Kinji Ishizuka of Daiwa Securities Co.
   He said the decline in the dollar against the yen had helped
boost stock prices.
</TEXT>
