<FIRST>u f BC-Ford-AirBags     05-19 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ford-Air Bags,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Chairman Says Air Bags To Be Standard In Nine Models</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine lines of Ford Motor Co. cars will
have supplemental air bags as standard equipment in the 1990 model
year, Chairman Donald E. Petersen disclosed this week.
   The Tempo and Topaz, which are produced at a Ford Motor plant in
nearby Claycomo, are not among the nine lines. But Ford would offer
air bags as options on them instead, Petersen announced Thursday.
   Petersen, who was in Kansas City to receive the Midwest Research
Institute's Trustee Citation for his leadership and emphasis on
quality, did not specify which nine lines would be outfitted with
the air bags.
   About 500 people attended the annual dinner of the non-profit
independent organization, which does research for government,
private business, associations and individuals.
   In his speech, Petersen also stressed the importance of quality
in all facets of customer and community relations. He gave as an
example Ford's recent decision to shift the site for its new paint
shop at Claycomo to the east to distance it from homes of nearby
residents.
   ``The change was not without some financial cost to Ford,'' he
said. ``But it was worth it.''
   In an interview after the award presentation, Petersen said
workers at Ford's Claycomo plant have shown marked improvement in
productivity over the years.
   Nine years ago in a visit to Kansas City, Petersen, who was then
president of Ford, chastised employees at Claycomo for absenteeism
and poor productivity.
   ``Claycomo has become an excellent example of the tremendous
progress we're making in developing a real sense of teamwork,''
Petersen said.
</TEXT>
