<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MerrillLynch     05-19 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Merrill Lynch,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merrill Lynch Choses Lakewood Center Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. will open a
regional operations center in Lakewood, eventually creating 900 new
jobs within the New York-based financial services giant.
   Data-processsing and bookkeeping functions for customer accounts
will be housed at the new facility, on a 13.9 acre site in the
Academy Park office complex.
   Company officials outlined the proposal at a news conference
Thursday in Gov. Roy Romer's office.
   Merrill Lynch has agreed to buy the 207,000-square-foot Denver
Service Center building from Manville Corp. to house the operations
center, but the purchase has not yet been completed. The company
will gut and remodel the building.
   An incentive package of $1.24 million in grants and loans was
given to Merrill Lynch by the Colorado Office of Economic
Development, the Greater Denver Chamber of Commerce and the City of
Lakewood.
   Merrill Lynch will open the facility late this year or in early
1990 and will employ 350 by next year. The operation will reach a
full employment level of 1,020 including the present 120 within
three years, said Mario Nigro, senior vice prsident.
   The majority of the jobs will be entry-level clerical positions.
But Nigro said the center will also hire skilled technicians and
profesionals. The operations center will include ``a fairly
involved legal operation,'' Nigro said. Some 600 to 700 employees
will be hired locally. The rest will relocate from other regional
operations centers.
   Landing Merrill Lynch is ``a very significant event in our
economic history,'' Romer said. It marks the biggest economic
development coup, in terms of jobs, since U S West selected Boulder
in 1987 for its research laboratory and a potential 1,500 jobs.
   Colorado's economic development blueprint targets the financial
services industry, Romer said. Landing Merrill Lynch will enhance
Colorado's ability to get the kinds of companies it wants, he said.
   ``Lakewood took a very aggressive posture with merill Lynch once
they decided on Colorado as the site for their regional
operation,'' said John Mullins, director of Lakewood's Department
of Economic Development.
   ``What we brought to the table was job training funds, in
addition to those provided by the state, in the amount of
$160,000.'' The city also is contributing $150,000 of a $500,000
loan the state is making to the New York-based brokerage.
   Earlier this year, American Express got $80,000 in job training
funds from the city when it moved operations to Lakewood, Mullins
said.
</TEXT>
