<FIRST>r f PM-OilSpillCriticism 1stLd-Writethru f0021 05-19 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill Criticism, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Report Levels Strongest Criticism Yet of Oil Spill Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, The 37-page, to correct quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil companies and the governments who are
supposed to clean up after spills did a ``wholly insufficient'' job
of responding to the Alaska oil spill, says a report sent to
President Bush.
   It was the strongest criticism yet leveled in the wake of the
disaster that spilled 11 million gallons of oil into Alaska's
pristine Prince William Sound after the tanker Exxon Valdez hit a
clearly marked reef.
   The 37-page report sent to Bush on Thursday was ``critical of
everybody,'' said a Department of Transportation official.
``Critical of the state, of Alyeska (pipeline company), Exxon, the
federal government.''
   ``In view of the fact that everything had been going so well for
so many years, I think everybody got a little complacent,'' said
the source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The report was prepared by Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner and William K. Reilly, administrator of the Environmental
Protection Agency. They visited Alaska five days after the March 24
accident.
   While the report criticized all agencies and companies, it also
noted that even if had better safeguards had been in place, the
largest oil spill in U.S. history was too enormous to contain, the
source said.
   Skinner ``has indicated that there is no technology available
today that could really have coped with that amount of oil in that
period of time in that particular climactic condition,'' the source
said.
   ``It escaped in such an incredible hurry, so fast, that even if
the equipment had been in place, it wouldn't have been enough,'' he
said.
   During their trip to Alaska, Skinner and Reilly directed efforts
by the National Response Team, a group of 14 agencies that
participated in the cleanup, to prepare a report assessing damage
and cleanup efforts. Results of the report were reported in today's
editions of The Washington Post.
   The review noted that although six contingency plans were
available to cope with accidents, their implementation was not
coordinated or organized.
   Exxon's shipping subsidiary, which owns the Exxon Valdez, had a
voluntary plan but ``no specific details,'' the report said.
   Cleanup technologies were ``primitive'' and more research should
done in that area, the report said.
   Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., which operates the Trans-Alaska
pipeline and the shipping terminal in Valdez, had a plan in place
to break up crude oil with chemical dispersants. But it failed to
take into account that the dispersants were stored in Arizona and
would take several hours to reach Alaska, the report said.
   ``Alyeska was not prepared to respond to this spill,'' it said,
according to the source.
   The report recommended that Congress pass laws ensuring that
operators of oil tankers create a fund large enough to pay for
cleanups. It noted that existing oil spill funds would have been
rapidly depleted ``if Exxon had not voluntarily assumed financial
and cleanup responsibility for the spill.''
   Earlier this week, Skinner proposed legislation to increase oil
spill liability and compensation. The bill would require a fund of
at least $500 million, financed by a 1.3-cent-per-barrel oil
industry surcharge.
   White House officials could provide no details about the report.
``I know nothing about a report,'' a spokesman said.
   Also Thursday, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., accused the
nation's oil companies of taking advantage of the spill to raise
gasoline prices.
   ``I suspect foul play. I say that candidly,'' D'Amato said at a
news conference in his Capitol Hill office. ``I suspect an
opportunity psychologically that the oil companies felt that they
could increase their prices.''
   The senator released copies of a letter he sent to Energy
Secretary James Watkins asking for ``an expeditious and thorough
investigation and evaluation'' of the nationwide gasoline price
increases since the spill.
   Gasoline prices climbed an average of 11.2 percent in April, the
fastest rate on record, from 97.4 cents to $1.098 per gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
