<FIRST>r f PM-USAir-Eastern     05-19 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir-Eastern,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preate Objections Off Base, USAir Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir is defending plans to purchase eight
Eastern Airlines gates at Philadelphia International Airport
against charges by the state attorney general that the deal would
create a ``near monopoly'' in Pennsylvania.
   ``The objections raised by the Pennsylvania Attorney General are
based on an erroneous and simplistic assessment of competition in
the passenger air transportation markets served from
Philadelphia,'' USAir said in comments filed Thursday with the
federal bankruptcy court in New York overseeing Eastern's financial
troubles.
   Attorney General Ernie Preate moved to block the deal earlier
this month after USAir said it would spend $70 million to buy the
gates from Eastern, which filed for bankruptcy protection in March
after being grounded by a labor strike.
   In a petition filed with the court, Preate said USAir may be
trying to dominate air service in Pennsylvania by purchasing the
gates. By dominating the market, USAir could raise fares, he said.
   The purchase would give USAir the majority of gates at the
state's two largest airports, Philadelphia and Greater Pittsburgh
International.
   ``Pennsylvania consumers already enjoy unrestricted air fares
that are lower than fares offered by other major airlines in
markets of comparable distance,'' said Randall Malin, USAir's
executive vice president for marketing.
   ``The attorney general also ignored the fact that a recent U.S.
Department of Transportation study concluded that USAir's average
fares at Pittsburgh actually decreased by 6 percent between the
first half of 1985 and the first half of 1988,'' he said.
   USAir cited its unrestricted fare of $108 one way for the
185-mile flight from Pittsburgh to Harrisburg. Fares charged by
other airlines on trips of similar distance range from $168 to $194.
   USAir also said its $126 one-way unrestricted fare from
Pittsburgh to Philadelphia is more than 40 percent cheaper than
fares charged by other airlines on similar trips.
   The purchase of eight Eastern gates at Philadelphia would
increase USAir's total at the airport by only four, to 19, because
USAir plans to dispose of four Piedmont gates. The Piedmont gates
are on a concourse separate from the one used by USAir.
   Piedmont and USAir plan to merge Aug. 5.
   The Eastern gates on an adjacent concourse would be more
convenient to passengers, USAir said. The additional gates also
would allow for new service for Philadelphia passengers, the
company said.
   USAir also said there is ample space for other airlines to
expand their service at Philadelphia. Eleven gates will be
available when a new terminal is completed in 1991.
   USAir operates nine daily departures from each of its
Philadelphia gates, while seven other major airlines average only
four departures from their gates.
   The attorney general's office will respond at a bankruptcy court
hearing expected to occur no earlier than June 7, said Jack Lewis,
a Preate spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
