<HEAD>Rain and Few Overseas Orders Force Down Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean prices opened lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices were down on disappointing export sales figures.
Prices also were pressured by overnight rain and forecasts of more
precipitation over the weekend.
   Analysts also blamed the drop in corn prices on the rain. They
also attributed the loss to the quiet export market.
   The weather also forced down wheat prices. However, there is
concern the heavy rains reported in parts of the central plains
will cause the loss of crops.
   Prices may be helped by the purchase yesterday of 200-thousand
metric tons of wheat by Bangladesh, and news of an offer by Egypt
for 300-thousand tons.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.05{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
lower to a \ cent higher with May at $2.74{ a bushel; oats were a {
cent to 1\ cents lower with May at $1.82{ a bushel; soybeans were
1{ cents to 3{ cents lower with May at $7.34{ a bushel.
   Livestock prices were most lower, and meat prices higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .30 cent lower with June at 70.60
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower to .10 cent higher
with May at 76.72 a pound; hogs were .13 cent to .45 cent higher
with June at 48.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .30 cent
to .33 cent higher with July at 35.65 cent a pound.
   Livestock and pork futures settled lower Thursday.
</TEXT>
