<FIRST>u f PM-AccountingMerger 4thLd-Writethru   05-19 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accounting Merger, 4th Ld-Writethru,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arthur Young, Ernst &amp; Whinney To Merge</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 3 new grafs after 6th graf pvs, We are ... to include
information from news conference. Picks up 7th graf pvs, A merger ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major accounting firms, Arthur Young &amp; Co.
and Ernst &amp; Whinney, have agreed in principle to a merger that they
say would form the world's largest accounting agency, the companies
announced today.
   In statements issued in London and New York, the companies
confirmed they have reached an agreement to join their worldwide
practices into a new firm called Ernst &amp; Young.
   The partnerships of both organizations will begin voting on the
proposed merger in June, the companies said. The announcement said
it was expected that the firms will begin joint opertation as soon
as practical after the vote.
   In a joint statement, the firms said their respective chairmen,
William L. Gladstone of Arthur Young and Ray J. Groves of Ernst &amp;
Whinney, would become co-chief executives of the combined firm
which will be based in New York. Young is now based in New York and
Ernst &amp; Whinney is in Cleveland.
   ``The combining of our two organizations will give us unrivaled
professional service capabilities to meet and anticipate needs of
clients of all sizes at the local level and in the global economy
into the final decade of the century and beyond,'' the London
statement said.
   ``We are a good match of skills, specialities and cultures which
we are confident will be integrated effectively,'' it said.
   At a news conference in New York, Gladstone and Groves said they
did not expect to lay off employees or to lose clients due to
conflicts as a result of the merger.
   Gladstone said he expects the combined firm will have more
employees a year from now than the firms have separately today.
   ``Most of what we do is serve clients,'' Groves said. ``That
doesn't change when you put two firms together.''
   A merger would unite the world's fourth- and fifth-largest
accounting firms, creating the No. 1 firm with a combined $4.3
billion in revenue, the firms stated. That would surpass world
accounting leader KMPG-Peat Marwick, which had $3.9 billion in
revenue last year.
   Ernst &amp; Whinney had $2.2 billion in revenue last year, while
Arthur Young had $2.1 billion. Domestically, the joined firms would
have $2.02 billion in revenue, just ahead of Chicago-based Arthur
Andersen &amp; Co.'s $1.71 billion.
   The combined firms also would have 6,100 partners and about
70,000 employees working in 100 countries, the statement said. In
the United States, the combined operation would have 2,105 partners
and 25,391 total employees.
   A report in Bowman's Accounting Report, an Atlanta newsletter,
said international partners met last week and details were hammered
out Monday at a secret meeting at Arthur Young headquarters in New
York as security guards stood outside.
   The newsletter said rumors of the merger had circulated for
months. It said the greatest threat to the combination would be
competition among partners in Canada and England, where both firms
have strong practices.
   Arthur Bowman, editor of Bowman's Accounting Report, said the
merger was being taken because of the firms' relative positions in
the middle of the pack of Big Eight accounting firms. He also
predicted mergers by smaller accounting firms that need to stay
competitive.
   ``The major emphasis here is both firms are slow growers
relative to the other Big Eight,'' Bowman said in a telephone
interview. ``It also creates a lot of pressure on the firms at the
bottom of the Big Eight to do something.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CherryLoss     05-19 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cherry Loss,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growers Say Western Montana Cherry Crop is Total Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POLSON, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The harsh Montana winter may have dealt a
permanent blow to the state's western cherry industry, growers say.
   ``It's very grim,'' said Polson grower Corky Morehead, head of
Treasure State Cherries. ``It's a loss of $5 (million) or $6
million'' to the local economy.
   There are virtually no cherry blossoms on the trees. And while
some trees are beginning to leaf, the leaves are few and scattered,
raising fears of permanent damage.
   ``My concern is for the health of the trees,'' said Robert
McClain of Yellow Bay, president of the Flathead Lake Cherry
Growers Association.
   Morehead said that if tree losses are heavy, ``I don't think
we'll ever see the cherry industry the way it has been.''
   Growers have been saying for weeks that the crop had been badly
damaged. But until now, they had hoped that trees in protected
locations might still blossom and yield partial crops.
   But Howard Thomas, a Finley Point grower, said that while he's
seeing a few blossoms, it amounts to two or three blossoms where
``we should see two or three thousand.''
   The damage occurred Jan. 31 and in subsequent days, when an
arctic front followed a January thaw. Temperatures plummeted 50
degrees in a few hours, freezing and splitting trees that had begun
to lose winter dormancy.
   In addition to the damage to sweet cherries, most apricots were
killed, along with peaches and nectarines. Recent mild winters had
encouraged growers to cultivate those crops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890519-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AccountingMerger-List     05-19 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Accounting Merger-List,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen Biggest Accounting Firms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Accounting Merger Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of the 15 biggest accounting
firms on the basis of their 1988 revenue from U.S. operations,
compiled by Bowman's Accounting Report of Atlanta.
   Included are each firm's U.S. partners, U.S. revenue and
international revenue.
   1. Arthur Andersen, 1,227 U.S. partners, $1.71 billion U.S.
revenue, $2.82 billion international revenue.
   2. KPMG (Peat Marwick), 1,933 U.S. partners, $1.64 billion U.S.
revenue, $3.90 billion international revenue.
   3. Ernst &amp; Whinney, 1,280 U.S. partners, $1.17 billion U.S.
revenue, $2.19 billion international revenue.
   4. Coopers &amp; Lybrand, 1,270 U.S. partners, $1.14 billion U.S.
revenue (estimate), $2.50 billion international revenue (estimate).
   5. Price Waterhouse, 870 U.S. partners, $960 million U.S.
revenue, $2.20 billion international revenue.
   6. Arthur Young, 889 U.S. partners, $843 million U.S. revenue,
$2.05 billion international revenue.
   7. Deloitte Haskins &amp; Sells, 853 U.S. partners, $820 million
U.S. revenue, $1.92 billion international revenue.
   8. Touche Ross, 774 U.S. partners, $796 million U.S. revenue,
$1.84 billion international revenue.
   9. Laventhol &amp; Horwath, 460 U.S. partners, $306 million U.S.
revenue, $556 million international revenue.
   10. Grant Thorton, 341 U.S. partners, $200 million U.S. revenue,
$721 million international revenue.
   11. BDO Seidman, 316 U.S. partners, $157 million U.S. revenue,
$758 million international revenue.
   12. McGladrey &amp; Pullen, 380 U.S. partners, $139 million U.S.
revenue, $402 million international revenue.
   13. Kenneth Leventhal, 61 U.S. partners, $126 million U.S.
revenue, $292 million international revenue.
   14. Pannell Kerr Forster, 125 U.S. partners, $87 million U.S.
revenue, $317 million international revenue.
   15. Spicer &amp; Oppenheim, 97 U.S. partners, $70 million U.S.
revenue, $344 million international revenue.
