<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EpcotPavilion     05-19 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Epcot Pavilion,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit in Failed Effort to Build Disney Attraction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for a South American pavilion at Walt
Disney World's Epcot Center were derailed by prospective partners
from Paraguay, according to a damage suit filed in Orlando by an
Argentinian company.
   The Circuit Court lawsuit, seeking $35 million in damages from
five Paraguayans, said the failure of the investors to put up $2
million for shares in the venture caused the company to forfeit its
license to operate the pavilion at Disney.
   The suit was filed by the Florida subsidiary of Eskantorp S.A.,
a development company based in Buenos Aires, which said it entered
into preliminary agreement with Disney in 1985 as a developer and
sponsor of the tourist site.
   Walt Disney World officials would not comment on the suit
Friday, saying they had not seen it.
   Epcot's World Showcase section includes 11 foreign-themed
pavilions, usually subsidized by the countries involved and
investors from those nations.
   Eskantorp said company officials met many times with senior
officials of the Paraguayan government, and Gen. Guillermo Clebsch,
chief of military forces at that time, had agreed that the
government would be an investor in the pavilion.
   Clebsch and four Paraguayan investors agreed to acquire 10
percent of the oustanding shares of Eskantorp for $2 million to pay
for the initial planning of the pavilion, Escantorp said in court
documents. Escantorp then entered into an agreement with the
Orlando-area tourist resort.
   However, the Paraguayans then backed out, causing Eskantorp to
forfeit its right to go through with the venture, the suit said.
   John Boudet, a lawyer in Orlando for Eskantorp, said the Buenos
Aires developer ``has made an effort to bring in some new
investors'' that would allow it to go ahead with the development,
but efforts have not been successful.
   The $35 million sought in damages represents the value of the
license over 25 years, Boudet said.
   ``Another way of looking at it is that it's 25 years worth of
lost profits'' to Eskantorp, the lawyer said.
</TEXT>
