<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru f0024 05-19 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Official Says Oil Industry Failed to Fulfill Promise to Clean
Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with oil industry executives testifying
today; Picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, ``I don't ...; Also moved on general
newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge normally equipped with cleanup
gear was unloaded for repairs at the time the Exxon Valdez ran
aground, and it took workers 10 hours to reload it, oil industry
officials testified today.
   After workers loaded the barge with 25 tons of equipment,
including booms, a skimmer and other cleanup gear, it took 3{ hours
to get it to the stricken tanker, said Lawrence Schier, Alyeska
Pipeline Service Co.'s marine manager.
   An investigator asked Schier how much oil would had been removed
from Prince William Sound if the loaded barge had been docked at
Bligh Reef when the ship ran aground March 24, spilling 10.9
million gallons of crude oil.
   ``I can't respond to that,'' he said.
   On Thursday, Alaska's environmental commissioner said the Exxon
Valdez disaster proved the oil industry couldn't fulfill its
promise to contain and remove a massive oil spill quickly in Prince
William Sound.
   But an Exxon Corp. executive told federal investigators that it
was impossible to stop the spread of the crude that gushed out of
the tanker.
   ``I don't think there was a power on Earth that could have
removed it from the water,'' Exxon Shipping Co. President Frank
Iarossi said.
   Iarossi and Commissioner Dennis Kelso testified in the third day
of hearings before a National Transportation Safety Board panel.
The hearings into the spill's cause continue today and are
scheduled to conclude Saturday.
   At Exxon's annual shareholders meeting in Parsippany, N.J., on
Thursday, environmentalists lashed out at Exxon Corp. by calling
for the oil company's chairman to resign and for senior executives
to forgo bonuses to help pay for the nation's worst oil spill.
   Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl tried for hours to deflect criticism,
repeating earlier public apologies and pledging to clean hundreds
of miles of waters and oil-soaked beaches. He also showed a short
film on the cleanup effort to allay concerns the company is failing
to do enough.
   State and industry officials at the hearings in Alaska took
turns Thursday blaming each other for making matters worse in their
response to the disaster.
   Kelso said Exxon and Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. failed to meet
deadlines to get equipment to the spill site, as required in their
contingency plan.
   Alyeska, a consortium of oil companies that owns and operates
the trans-Alaska oil pipeline and the Valdez terminal, is
responsible for initially responding with booms and cleanup gear to
spills within the sound.
   ``If the powers that were present, Alyeska and Exxon, did what
they had committed to do in the plan, it would be a very different
situation today,'' Kelso testified.
   Iarossi defended Exxon's response, noting his company mobilized
equipment from around the world and got it to the scene quickly
despite logistical problems.
   Even if the required equipment had been ``right around the
corner,'' the spill's vastness made mechanical removal of the oil
impractical, Iarossi said.
   The panel also heard more testimony on alcohol abuse, a central
issue in the disaster. Joseph Hazelwood, the tanker's captain who
had a history of alcohol problems, was fired after he was charged
with operating the Exxon Valdez while drunk. He has pleaded
innocent.
   Iarossi said Exxon ships go through rigorous alcohol and drug
searches involving dogs, trained searchers and occasionally U.S.
Customs Service agents.
   The company's alcohol and drug policy resulted in 55
disciplinary cases among its ship crews over five years, including
34 firings, he said. Five of those cases were appealed by unions
and all five were overturned by arbitrators, who found the policy
too severe.
   Iarossi said ``it was just by chance'' that he heard of
Hazelwood's alcohol problem in May 1985 after the captain completed
a hospital treatment program. Iarossi noted that such employee
information usually is kept confidential.
   After Hazelwood returned to work, he was monitored by two
supervisors who visited him in port twice a month and discussed his
behavior with the crew. ``It was all iced tea and Perrier,''
Iarossi said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
