<DOCNO> AP890519-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-USSemiconductors     05-19 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Semiconductors,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Warns Against Being Named an Unfair Trader in Semiconductors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese trade officials warned that targeting
Japan for sanctions by naming it an unfair trader in semiconductors
would be counterproductive, American officials said Friday.
   In regular consultative meetings Thursday and Friday, Japanese
officials explained plans for expanded purchases of foreign
semiconductors by Japanese companies, including electronics firms
and automobile manufacturers.
   But the U.S. government remains ``highly dissatisfied'' with the
U.S. share of the Japanese semiconductor market, an American trade
official said.
   ``Our dissatisfaction is with the fact that the (foreign) share
of the Japanese market remains at about 10 percent while the
competitiveness of U.S firms would indicate a much higher share,''
said the official, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity.
   ``Although continuing efforts are being made (by the Japanese
government and companies) and progress is being made, the United
States continues to be highly dissatisfied'' with American market
access, the official said.
   Japanese officials countered that the government is doing its
best to open the semiconductor market, and that Japan would ``react
very strongly'' if it is named an unfair trader in semiconductors.
   ``We are doing affirmative action concerning the penetration of
U.S. semiconductors to the Japanese market,'' said Hidehiko
Nishiyama, deputy director of the Americas-Oceania Division of the
Ministry of International Trade and Industry.
   ``We have been demanding that the U.S. side remove existing
sanctions, so it's unimaginable for us to get additional
sanctions,'' Nishiyama said in a telephone interview.
   Within a few weeks Japan may be named for obstructive trading
practices under the ``Super 301'' provision of the 1988 Omnibus
Trade Act, which requires that the U.S. government study sanctions
against countries that do not remove unfair trade barriers after
negotiations.
   ``The Japanese side expressed the view that the naming of
semiconductors under section 301 would be counterproductive,'' the
U.S. official said.
   Semiconductors are a key issue among the many complaints the
United States has about Japanese trade practices. ``Failure to
implement the market-access provisions of the (1986 U.S.-Japan
semiconductor) agreement is very serious and affects billions of
dollars in sales,'' the U.S. official said.
   However, both the U.S. and Japanese sides described the meetings
as ``constructive.''
   ``There is clearly a commitment (by the Japanese side) to
improve market access for U.S. semiconductor firms,'' the U.S.
official said.
   Both sides apparently did not raise an earlier dispute about
whether the 1986 agreement between the two countries promised the
United States a 20 percent share of the Japanese semiconductor
market by 1991. Officials from both countries ``understand that it
is not constructive to discuss the 20 percent issue,'' Nishiyama
said.
   On the issue of high-definition television, MITI said ``Japanese
firms had indicated a willingness to work with U.S. semiconductor
producers on HDTV projects,'' the U.S. official said.
   The two sides also discussed ``TRON,'' a basic computer design
standard created by a Japanese professor that is intended to make
future computers more compatible and flexible. TRON stands for
``The Real-time Operating System Nucleus.''
   Participation in the development of TRON is open to U.S. firms
and a number are participating, but Japanese companies are ahead in
developing TRON products.
   Because Japanese schools and the semi-private telecommunications
giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. are considering the TRON
standard for some future purchases, the U.S. is concerned about
preventing ``government intervention in the marketplace which
creates a trade barrier,'' said another U.S. official, who also
demanded anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
