<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Friday in light trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors
pulled back from the market to see if growing conditions improve
over the weekend.
   Soybean futures were mostly lower due to the uncertain prospects
for more rain next week, analysts said.
   ``What happened in the market was that most people didn't want
to establish new positions until after the weekend,'' said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
``They wanted to see what the rains were like over the weekend.''
   Corn prices closed higher on reports of less-than-expected rain
in the Corn Belt. Corn prices also were supported by reports the
Soviet Union and Mexico may be in the market soon.
   Wheat prices dropped on trader disappointment over a lack of new
purchase orders from the Soviets or China. The market also was
affected by good rains in Missouri, where there were fears of crop
loss because of dryness.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.03\ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
lower to 1} cents higher with May at $2.74} a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 4} cents lower with May at $1.80{ a bushel; soybeans were
a { cent lower to 2\ cents higher with May at $7.39 a bushel.
