<FIRST>r f AM-Philippines-Westinghouse     05-19 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Westinghouse,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Pleased By Court Ruling On Philippine Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. officials said
Friday they were delighted a federal judge in New Jersey has
shifted to arbitration the bulk of the legal allegations made by
the Philippines over a mothballed nuclear reactor.
   Only one of 15 counts, claiming the Philippine people were
harmed by alleged corruption in the contracting of the plant, will
remain in federal court to determine its merits, said Louis
Briskman, deputy general counsel for Westinghouse, the nation's
largest producer of nuclear power plants.
   U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevois in Newark ruled
Thursday that the claims made by the current government of
President Corazon Aquino belong before the International Chamber of
Commerce as specified in the contract Westinghouse entered with the
government when Ferdinand Marcos was president.
   ``This ruling is strong affirmation of the position we've been
taking'' since the suit was filed against Westinghouse and the
project architect-engineer, Burns &amp; Roe Enterprises Inc., said
Nathaniel Woodson, president of the Westinghouse's international
division.
   Attorneys for the Philippines argued the corruption surrounding
the contract was so massive that the federal court should keep the
case and disregard contract provisions specifying arbitration as
the forum for settling disputes.
   The Aquino government claims bribes were paid to the Marcos
government to win the contract, and it filed the suit in an attempt
to void the contract.
   The suit also alleges that the $2.3 billion, 600-megawatt plant
on the Bataan Peninsula, which has been mothballed since its
completion in 1985, is unsafe.
   Briskman said there is no evidence any of the $17 million
Westinghouse paid in fees to contract consultants in the
Philippines went to Marcos as a bribe. He said he was confident of
winning any court case on the remaining count.
   Westinghouse has claims pending before the Chamber of Commerce
in Switzerland seeking $30 million in remaining charges on the
project.
</TEXT>
