<FIRST>u f AM-StockBaskets-Copyright     05-19 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stock Baskets-Copyright,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Exchange Charges Amex Copied Its New Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange on Friday
accused the American Stock Exchange of improperly copying its new
stock index-based security, a charge the American exchange promptly
denied.
   The exchanges both began trading the securities _ known as Cash
Index Participations on the Philadelphia exchange and Equity Index
Participations on the Amex _ a week ago after the Securities and
Exchange Commission lifted a ban on them.
   Amex copied parts of the Philadelphia exchange's rules for the
security that were submitted to the SEC, Thomas A. Russo, an
attorney for the Philadelphia exchange, wrote in a letter to Amex
attorneys.
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange sought SEC approval for the Cash
Index Participation, a security based on the ``basket'' of stocks
represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's Index of 500 stocks, in March
1988.
   Two weeks later, the Amex filed with the SEC seeking approval
for its Equity Index Participation, a similar instrument.
   ``It took me a few months just to get the rules specific,'' said
William W. Uchimoto, the Philadelphia exchange's general counsel.
``I don't think they could develop a product in two weeks that's
identical to ours.''
   In a prepared statement read by Amex spokesman Bob Shabazian,
the exchange said, ``There is no basis to contend infringement of
any purported copyright.''
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange also came out with a similar
product. However, Uchimoto said, because that exchange had not
begun trading its version and was not aggressively promoting it the
Philadelphia exchange decided not to complain.
   If the Amex and the Philadelphia exchange cannot agree on ways
to make the Amex product substantially different, Uchimoto said, he
planned to sue to bar Amex from trading the security.
   He said one change that might satisfy the Philadelphia exchange
would be for the Amex security to be tied to an index other than
the S&amp;P 500.
   The index participation products are based on the current value
of indexes of stocks. Investors receive quarterly cash payments
equal to a proportionate share of any regular cash dividend
declared on the component stocks of the underlying index.
   The complaint came a day after the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Chicago denied a request by the Chicago Board of Trade
and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange to temporarily halt trading of
the securities.
   Fearing the securities would cut into their futures business,
the two Chicago exchanges have argued the securities actually are
futures contracts and should be regulated by the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, rather than the SEC.
</TEXT>
