<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-19 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices finished higher Friday,
driven up mainly by traders adjusting their holdings before
expiration of the June crude oil contract.
   The June contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 40 cents to $20.60 a barrel on the New
York Mercantile Exchange. On Thursday, the contract settled up by 7
cents.
   The July crude oil contract slipped 6 cents to $18.74 a barrel.
It will become the near-month contract Tuesday after expiration of
the June contract Monday.
   Jerry Samuels, a broker with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said
trading in the June contract was particularly hectic in the final
minutes of the session.
   Most of the activity was due to maneuvering by traders ahead of
the weekend and before the final day of trading in the June
contract, he said.
   Uncertainty about what may occur at the June 5 gathering of OPEC
members discouraged crude prices from moving sharply in either
direction, energy traders said.
   At the Vienna meeting, members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries will review their current output quota of 18.5
million barrels a day. There has been speculation that the ceiling
will be raised.
   Prices of refined petroleum products traded on the Mercantile
Exchange moved slightly higher.
   The June contract for wholesale gasoline, which rose 1.26 cents
on Thursday, settled at 65.19 cents a gallon, up 0.66 cent.
   Wholesale home heating oil for June delivery increased 0.51 cent
to 48.06 cents a gallon. The contract had risen 0.41 cent on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
