<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-19 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rally Resumes; Gold Keeps Falling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar's rally resumed Friday despite
containment efforts by central banks and the price of gold
continued tumbling.
   Central banks managed to keep a cap on the dollar through Asian
and European trading but lost control as trading shifted to the
United States.
   Dealers absorbed the dollar sales by the government banks and
came back for more, said Robert Pucciariello, a trader for Union
Bank of Switzerland in New York.
   The U.S. currency closed at its highs of the day but below its
highest point of the week. This week the dollar reached levels not
seen since 1987 against the Japanese yen and since 1986 against the
West German mark.
   Although the dollar's swift rise has captured most of the
attention, the dive in gold has been even swifter.
   Speculative selling of gold accelerated at the end of April when
it fell below $380 a troy ounce, an important level for traders
chart price trends, according to Jeffrey Nichols, president of
American Precious Metals Advisors Inc.
   On Friday, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid
at $364.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down sharply from $368.30
late Thursday to a level not seen in nearly three years. A year ago
gold was around $450 an ounce.
   Gold also has been hurt by the rise of the dollar and by an
unexpected increase in the world gold supply, Nichols said. The
volume of gold entering the open market set an annual record last
year and is continuing at high levels this year, he said.
   The Federal Reserve, the Bank of Canada, the Bank of Japan and
several European central banks sold dollars, traders said. West
Germany's Bundesbank apparently did not take part, they said.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6190 from $1.6180 late
Thursday. In New York sterling fell to $1.6120 in late trading from
$1.6175 Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.11 yen to close at 138.77 yen. Later in London,
the dollar was quoted at 138.75 yen. In New York the dollar rose to
139.01 Japanese yen from 138.65 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9770 West German marks, up from
1.9670; 1.7635 Swiss francs, up from 1.7568; 1.1912 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1927; 6.6905 French francs, up from 6.6585;
and 1,439.00 Italian lire, up from 1,433.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.9695 West German marks, up from 1.9660; 1.7583
Swiss francs, up from 1.7552; 6.6700 French francs, up from 6.6490;
2.2210 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2240; 1,435.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,439.50; 1.1911 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1927.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $365.75 a troy ounce, its
lowest level since August 1986, from $370.75 late Thursday. In
Zurich, gold closed at a bid of $365.20, down from $370.25 late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $4.51 to close at a bid of
$367.22 a troy ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $365.70 an ounce from $369.70 Thursday.
   Silver bullion fell on the London market to a late bid of $5.35
a troy ounce from Thursday's $5.43. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.229 an ounce from $5.401.
</TEXT>
