<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-19 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains and Soybeans Mixed In Light Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed
Friday in light trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors
retreated from the market to see if growing conditions improve over
the weekend.
   On other markets, precious metals continued sliding, livestock
prices were mixed, meat was higher and energy futures rose in
modest trading.
   Grain and soybean prices mostly were lower due to the uncertain
prospects for rain next week, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents to 5 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.03\ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to 1}
cents higher with May at $2.74} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4}
cents lower with May at $1.80{ a bushel; soybeans were a { cent
lower to 2\ cents higher with May at $7.39 a bushel.
   ``What happened in the market was that most people didn't want
to establish new positions until after the weekend,'' said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Ind. in Chicago.
``They wanted to see what the rains were like over the weekend.''
   Corn closed higher on reports of less-than-expected rain in the
Corn Belt. Corn prices also were supported by reports the Soviet
Union and Mexico may be in the corn market soon.
   Wheat prices dropped due to trader disappointment over a lack of
new purchase orders from the Soviets or China. The market also was
affected by good rains in Missouri, where there had been fears of
crop loss because of dryness, analysts said.
   Gold and silver prices continued tumbling on New York's
Commodity Exchange. Prices have plunged partly due to the recent
surprising rise of the dollar, which has drawn investors away from
the metals.
   ``The dollar remains strong despite intervention by the central
banks,'' said David Syphen, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc. in New York. ``There is a lot of disinvestment. The
fundamentals on gold and silver don't justify accumulation.''
   Gold was $3.70 to $6.20 lower with May at $365.70 a troy ounce;
silver was 17.2 cents to 21.1 cents lower with May at $5.229 a troy
ounce.
   Livestock prices were mixed and meat futures rose on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Hog prices rose on lighter-than-expected marketings, said Dale
Benson, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   In livestock futures trading, participants continued to look at
the Agriculture Department's cattle-on-feed report, which showed
larger-than-expected April placement of cattle in feed lots. The
increased placements could lead to lower prices later in the year.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .03 cent higher with June at
70.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with May at 76.77 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .60
cent higher with June at 48.72 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent to 1.08 cent higher with May at 36.10 cents a
pound.
   Energy futures were higher in light trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with prices driven up during maneuvering by
traders before expiration of contracts for delivery in June.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 3 cents lower to 40 cents
higher with June at $20.60 a barrel; heating oil was .22 cent to.51
cent higher with June at 48.06 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was .16 cent to .66 cent higher with June at 65.19 cents a
gallon.
