<FIRST>u f AM-Digital-Salaries     05-19 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digital-Salaries,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Digital Equipment Imposes Salary Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp., seeking to avoid layoffs
despite a sharp drop in earnings, said Friday it will delay all
salary increases for its 73,500 employees in the United States.
   The salary freeze will go into effect July 2, the beginning of
Digital's fiscal year, and will be re-evaluated in late September
or October, said spokeswoman Nikki Richardson.
   ``Because business is down in the U.S. for Digital as well as
for computers in general, we need to control costs in order to
improve profitability,'' Ms. Richardson said.
   Digital stock closed at $96.625, down 50 cents in composite
trading Friday on the New York Stock Exchange. The stock has sagged
badly since 1987, when it peaked at $199 a share.
   The Maynard-based computer maker reported earnings in the
quarter ending April 1 of $256.4 million, down almost 16 percent
from $305.1 million a year earlier. Operating revenues were $3.12
billion, up 11 percent over the same period of 1988.
   Ms. Richardson said no layoffs or early retirement incentives
are planned. She noted that Digital has never had a layoff in its
31-year history.
   Although there is no written guarantee against layoffs, Digital
and its employees have a tacit covenant of lifetime job security,
said George Colony, president of Forrester Research Inc., a
computer market researcher in Cambridge.
   ``I think it is virtually impossible for Digital to break that
covenant. They cannot do it, and I don't think they should do it. I
think this is a better alternative to layoffs,'' he said.
   Digital imposed a previous salary freeze in 1982, during an
industry downturn, but it was lifted after three months when the
company's sales turned around.
   All U.S. employees will experience the same delay in their
salary increases, regardless of their employment anniversary date,
when salary reviews normally take place, Ms. Richardson said.
   Digital's 52,000 employees working abroad will not be affected
by the freeze because ``demand and profitability remain strong in
the international area for Digital,'' she said.
   Analysts said the root of the U.S. downturn is that sales of
personal computers and groups of PCs linked to so-called local area
networks are cutting into demand for Digital's more expensive
minicomputers.
   If that trend reaches Europe and the Far East, Colony said,
Digital may be forced to take additional cost-cutting measures in
the fall.
   ``We expect the next step will be a redeployment of people from
headquarters out into the field, which would be a de facto layoff,
because people don't want to move from Boston to Oshkosh,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
