<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms     05-19 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Sets Bidding Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp.'s latest deadline for
takeover bids passed Friday, but a lawyer for rival poultry
processor Tyson Foods Inc. indicated his client would refrain from
making an offer.
   ``I wouldn't be holding your breath until we bid,'' Rodman Ward,
a Tyson lawyer in Delaware, said Friday afternoon. He declined
further comment.
   Tyson of Springdale, Ark., has pursued Holly Farms since last
October and has been battling with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb., for
control of the Memphis-based company.
   The takeover battle, worth about $1 billion, is tied up in a
Delaware court and the legal squabbling will likely continue
regardless of how the bidding goes.
   Court records indicate that Tyson and ConAgra have been
negotiating behind the scenes to settle on a buyer of Holly Farms,
a diversified company heavily involved in fresh fryer sales.
   Ted Bailey, a spokesman for Holly Farms, declined to comment on
the bidding, saying a statement would be made after his company's
board of directors met Saturday in New York.
   ``The board will meet about midday, but I don't have any idea
when we will have anything to say,'' he said.
   The Holly board has voted several times to reject buyout offers
from Tyson. A spokesman for ConAgra failed to return phone calls.
   Tyson has previously offered Holly stockholders $63.50-a-share
for their stock, but the tender offer is conditioned on removal of
an asset purchase agreement between Holly and ConAgra.
   That agreement would let ConAgra buy about a third of Holly
Farms if the company is sold to anyone other than ConAgra.
   Tyson is challenging that agreement in court and has accused
Holly Farms of trying to favor ConAgra as a suitor.
   Holly stockholders voted last month to reject a proposal to
merge Holly Farms with ConAgra. The asset purchase agreement stems
from that merger plan.
   Tyson tried to stop the latest bidding for Holly Farms but
Chancellor Maurice Hartnett of Delaware refused the request.
   Hartnett said, however, that the bidding procedures clearly
favored ConAgra over Tyson.
</TEXT>
