<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-19 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Tumbled To One-Year Low For Long Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yield on the government's benchmark 30-year
bond fell Friday to its lowest level in more than a year as credit
markets rallied, partly in response to the stronger dollar.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond rose 23-32 point, or more
than $7 for every $1,000 in face value, while its yield fell to
8.70 percent from 8.77 percent late Thursday.
   That was the lowest yield since the 30-year bond delivered 8.68
percent on April 8, 1988.
   Analysts said the dollar's continued strength in foreign
exchange _ which increases the attractiveness of returns on
dollar-denominated investments such as bonds _ and the absence of
selling sentiment in the bond market pushed prices higher.
   ``It seems to have a lot of strength,'' said Robert Chandross,
chief economist with Lloyds Bank PLC in New York. ``It's running on
momentum now.''
   Chandross said the market broke through technical support
levels, triggering further buying in speculation that prices would
be bid even higher.
   ``What you have in the bond market is a huge appetite for
dollar-denominated investments. The stability and strength in U.S.
currency has further encouraged foreign investors to be more active
in the market,'' said Maria F. Ramirez, money market economist for
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The dollar resumed a rally Friday despite containment efforts by
central banks. This week the dollar has reached levels not seen
since 1987 against the Japanese yen and since 1986 against the West
German mark.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments rose 3-32 to 3-16 point, intermediate maturities were
up between \ and 7-16 point and long-term issues advanced between }
and 25-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, gained 2.99 to 1,148.57.
   In corporate trading, industrials also were higher. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 1.55 to 312.15.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 9-32 to 9311-16 point. The average
yield to maturity dropped to 7.44 percent from 7.47 percent late
Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills slipped to 8.64 percent as
the discount fell 1 basis point to 8.35 percent. Yields on
six-month bills dropped to 8.85 percent as the discount fell 1
basis point to 8.37 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.87
percent as the discount fell 4 basis points to 8.22 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 9| percent, down from 9} percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
