<FIRST>r f AM-GMMeeting     05-19 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Meeting,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Shareholders Hear Upbeat Message from Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher fuel economy regulations for 1990
model-year cars won't compel General Motors Corp. to cut production
of large models in the immediate future, GM Chairman Roger Smith
said Friday.
   Smith, speaking at a news conference following the company's
annual shareholders' meeting, reiterated statements that an
increase in the corporate average fuel economy standard, which will
be 27.5 miles per gallon for the 1990 model year, could result in
closings of plants making large automobiles.
   However, he said, ``I don't see that happening right now for the
1990 year, as we look forward to it. We have to see how the sales
go.''
   He refused to rule out plant closings in 1990 for other reasons.
   Earlier this week, Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said
he would not seek a change in the regulation requiring automakers'
fleets to average 27.5 mpg.
   That was a break from the Reagan administration, which granted
appeals from GM and Ford Motor Co. to lower the standard. Chrysler
Corp.'s fleet, which has a larger percentage of smaller, more fuel
efficient cars, has had little trouble meeting the requirements.
   Planning production for the 1990 model year has been under way
for months. GM's Chevrolet Division already is selling its 1990
Lumina sedan.
   Smith also said that in the fall, a committee of the board of
directors would be formed to search for his successor. As
previously reported, Smith will step down as chairman of the
world's largest industrial company July 31, 1990.
   At the news conference and the board meeting earlier in the day,
Smith said there was no heir apparent.
   ``We don't have a crown prince,'' he told shareholders. ``We
have a lot of excellent executives.''
   Smith also told stockholders GM was on the way to a
``reindustrialization'' of itself. By the end of the year, Smith
said, GM will have spent nearly $76 billion on building and
modernizing plants and other facilities.
   ``Today, though we still have much more work to do, we've made
excellent progress,'' Smith said. ``We'll go into the 1990s a far
different company from the one that entered the 1980s.''
   Smith singled out a need for the company to improve its North
American operations. Like No. 2 Ford Motor Co., GM's earnings
during the past several years have been buoyed by European
operations.
   ``We want to increase our North American passenger-car market
penetration,'' Smith said. ``Right now, it isn't where we'd like
it.''
   During the 1980s, GM has watched its share of the entire
automobile market shrink from 46 percent as the decade began to
35.8 percent on March 10. Most of that erosion in market share has
has gone to Ford and overseas automakers.
</TEXT>
