<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Amway     05-19 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Amway,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Releases Memo Alleging Insider Trading by Amway Execs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee said
Friday it is investigating allegations of insider stock trading by
officials of Amway Corp. before the company offered to buy Avon
Products Inc.
   In a letter, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., asked the chairman of
the Securities and Exchange Commission, David Ruder, to open his
own probe of the allegations. Ruder said in New York that the SEC
planned to investigate as it does whenever it receives such
allegations.
   Amway, a door-to-door sales business headquartered in Ada,
Mich., on May 10 offered $39 a share in a takeover bid for its
larger rival, Avon. Amway withdrew its $2.1 billion offer Wednesday.
   Dingell's committee released a memorandum it had received from
an unspecified source alleging that Otto Stolz, Amway's executive
vice president, and William Nicholson, Amway's chief operating
officer, apparently intended to profit personally when they
purchased Avon stock in late March and early April before the
takeover bid was announced.
   The memorandum said that Irwin Jacobs, a Minneapolis investor
and a partner of Amway, also purchased stock prior to the takeover
announcement. Jacobs, the memorandum said, was being paid out of
profits from trading in Avon stock before the takeover announcement.
   Federal law forbids trading securities based on information not
available to the general public. Avon shares rose more than $2 per
share immediately after the takeover bid was announced.
   Nicholson said the shares were assigned to the partnership with
Jacobs at cost, the transactions were reported to the SEC, and
there was no personal profit involved.
   ``This is the standard part of the smear campaign of Avon and
its advisors to divert attention from their own performance or
problems,'' Nicholson said.
   Avon said no one was available to comment on Nicholson's
assertion.
   Jacobs said the allegations were ``preposterous, plain and
simple.''
   ``It is strictly politically motivated. We welcome any
government agency that wishes to look into this thing. Our books
are wide open to them,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the House committee, Dennis Fitzgibbons,
declined to discuss the source of the memorandum.
   ``The allegations are sufficiently serious that the chairman had
to ask Ruder and the commission to look at them,'' Fitzgibbons said.
   The memorandum said Stolz purchased 10,000 Avon shares on March
23 and 6,600 shares on March 27, at a value of $356,000.
   Nicholson, the memo said, on April 5 purchased options to buy
40,000 Avon shares at $25 per share, with the options costing
$70,400.
   The memorandum alleged that ``the timing and nature of that
trading is consistent ... with attempts to profit personally from
insider trading, not with any purported agency transaction on
behalf of Amway.''
   Meanwhile, investors continued to unload Avon shares Friday,
although the selloff seemed to be subsiding. Avon stock closed at
$32.25 a share, off 75 cents, in composite New York Stock Exchange
trading.
   Avon stock had reached a 52-week high of $41.25 earlier in the
week amid speculation Amway might raise its offer or another, more
generous bidder might emerge. But, after Amway withdrew its
takeover proposal Wednesday night, Avon shares plunged $7.12{ on
Thursday.
   Takeover-stock speculators were nursing heavy losses on Avon
shares and several of them directed pointed questions at Avon
executives during a meeting with financial analysts in New York on
Friday.
   In a related matter, attorneys for Avon said at least eight
lawsuits have been filed against Avon in New York State Supreme
Court on behalf of several shareholders.
   The suits, most of which were filed since Amway and investment
partner Jacobs announced they had acquired a 10.3 percent stake in
Avon, challenge takeover deterrents Avon has adopted.
</TEXT>
