<FIRST>u f AM-Electrolux-Regina     05-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Electrolux-Regina,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrolux Plans To Acquire Regina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electrolux Corp., a leading home-care
products company, said Friday it has agreed to buy the Regina
Company Inc., a New Jersey-based maker of products such as vacuum
cleaners and home whirlpool baths.
   Terms were not disclosed and the transcation was subject to
completing a definitive purchase agreement and approval by a
federal bankruptcy judge.
   Regina, based in Rahway, N.J., filed for reorganization under
Chapter 11 bankruptcy laws April 26.
   Steven Cooper, senior vice president and general counsel for
Electrolux, said Electrolux hoped Regina would provide ``a
different channel for retail distribution.''
   Electrolux, a privately-held company, is primarily a direct
sales organization specializing in home-care products such as water
purification products.
   Cooper said details of the purchase agreement and Electrolux's
plans for personnel at Regina were still sketchy.
   Regina has stated its value at $65 million to $70 million, but
the purchase price was subject to negotiations with the bankruptcy
judge, Cooper said.
   ``We want to finish the negotiations as quickly as possible, but
I really can't say how soon that will be,'' he said.
   Electrolux has listed its annual sales at $400 million. Regina's
last full fiscal year yielded about $160 million, Cooper said.
   Cooper said a bankruptcy attorney for Regina had requested a
hearing to be scheduled within 15 days.
   Officials at Regina's corporate headquarters could not be
reached for comment by telephone Friday because they had left their
offices after business hours.
   Regina's ability to survive as an independent company was put in
doubt on May 4, when a U.S. Bankruptcy Judge William Tuohey in
Newark, N.J., refused to approve a $5 million financing package
worked out between the company and its two largest creditors, Chase
Manhattan Bank and Philadelphia National Bank.
   The agreement was contingent on the banks' ability to combine
the new loan with the company's old debt, amounting to about $25
million.
   The banks also demanded to be put ahead of all other creditors
for repayment.
   Tuohey said he rejected the agreement out of concern for
unsecured creditors, who have total claims of $36 million.
</TEXT>
