<DOCNO> AP890519-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-United Bjt   05-19 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-United, Bjt,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another United Order Gives Boeing Another Record Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. set an industry record for single-year
commercial jetliner orders Friday when United Airlines announced
its fourth major order for Boeing aircraft in two years, a 32-plane
package the airline valued at $3 billion.
   United's firm order for 16 extended-range 767-300ERs and options
for another 16 of the widebody twinjets came just three weeks after
United gave Boeing the largest aircraft order ever with a single
manufacturer, for up to 370 planes valued at as much as $15.74
billion.
   And Stephen M. Wolf, United's chairman and president, said his
company's buying spree isn't over for the year.
   ``A third and major order addressing our widebody needs for both
our growing Pacific service as well as for additional domestic
airplanes will be forthcoming later this year,'' Wolf said from
United's Chicago headquarters.
   With the new orders, Boeing has a backlog of 1,535 jets, which
should guarantee prosperity for the jetmaker well into the
mid-1990s.
   Although a crush of orders from airlines and leasing companies
have raised questions on how well the big three jet manufacturers
can keep up, Boeing officials say they have been planning as best
they can for the new work.
   Wolf said the new 767s are envisioned for both domestic and
trans-Atlantic service, even though United does not yet fly to
Europe.
   In United's configuration, the 767s will carry about 200
passengers and will be able to fly from anywhere in the continental
United States to Western Europe.
   Boeing, which lists dollar figures only for firm orders, priced
the 16 firm 767s at about $1.4 billion.
   With the order, Boeing set an industry record for dollar value
of planes ordered in a calendar year: $30.1 billion for 543
aircraft. That mark, also a company record for new orders for the
fifth year in a row, betters the $29.7 billion for 636 Boeing
planes ordered for all of 1988.
   In the past two years, United, which was formed by Boeing in the
1930s but split off in 1934, has given Boeing about $23.4 billion
in new business, counting aircraft options. United now has on order
every type of commercial jet Boeing makes.
   United's April order was for 120 Boeing 737s twinjets and 60
midsized 757s, plus options for 130 737s and 60 757s.
   In May 1987, United ordered 15 747-400 jumbo jets and 21 737s,
worth a total $2.1 billion, and in April 1988, ordered 30 757s and
took options on 30 more in a deal worth $1.3 billion for the firm
orders.
   ``United has been a good customer for a long time,'' said Boeing
spokeswoman Elizabeth Reese.
   Boeing salesmen also are working on getting the United order for
later this year. ``We'll be showing them what we have in the
salesroom,'' Ms. Reese said.
   Wolf said United would receive its first five 767-300ERs in
1991, two more in 1992, eight in 1993 and one in 1994. Four of the
jets on option are to be delivered in 1994, five in 1995 and seven
in 1996.
   The planes will be powered by Pratt &amp; Whitney engines.
   Boeing and its two major competitors, McDonnell Douglas Corp.
and Europe's Airbus Industrie, have been blessed with a crush of
orders in recent years, due to concerns about older aircraft,
forecasts of continued rapid growth of air travel, and a need for
planes to meet tougher noise standards and to be more economical.
   Boeing and McDonnell Douglas both have suffered delays in
delivering new aircraft, Boeing with its 747-400 jumbo jet and
McDonnell Douglas with its MD-11 widebody. But Boeing officials say
they don't expect delays to spread to other assembly lines.
   Ms. Reese said United's new order was anticipated and ``isn't
going to impact the production line because we plan things like
this in advance.''
   Phil Condit, Boeing Commercial Airplanes executive vice
president, said in a briefing last week that Boeing has
substantially met its revised schedule for delivering the new 747s,
though it has had to negotiate penalties with at least four
customers.
   Condit said those delays were due in great part to overly
ambitious plans to introduce four different variations of the jumbo
jet simultaneously.
   Boeing says it is increasing production rates, from 27 jets a
month to 34 by mid-1990s, and is spending $1.1 billion on capital
improvements this year, including major upgrades at its Renton 737
and 757 plant and at its widebody factory in Everett, Wash.
   Condit said Boeing's production schedules are being planned
years in advance, and that the company is carefully increasing
production so as not overwhelm its own and its suppliers' capacity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
